"order": 0,
"title": "Objective I",
"summary": "Set up the standard right-handed axes used for directions on Earth's surface: $\\hat{i} =$ East, $\\hat{j} =$ North, $\\hat{k} =$ vertically up (this triad satisfies $\\hat{i}\\times\\hat{j}=\\hat{k}$).",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- The component of a vector $\\vec{A}$ along a direction making angle $\\theta$ with it is $A\\cos\\theta$. Since $-1 \\le \\cos\\theta \\le 1$, the component can take **any value from $-A$ to $+A$**: - At $\\theta = 0°$: component $= A$ (equals the magnitude) - At $\\theta = 90°$: component $= 0$ - At $\\theta = 180°$: component $= -A$ So the component is sometimes equal to the magnitude, sometimes less, sometimes zero, and can even be negative — it is never *always* less than (rules out A), never *always* greater than (a component can't exceed the magnitude, so B is impossible too, but \"always\" makes it false), and never *always* equal (only true for $\\theta=0$). Since no single fixed relation holds in every case, the answer is (D) none of these.\n- Set up the standard right-handed axes used for directions on Earth's surface: $\\hat{i} =$ East, $\\hat{j} =$ North, $\\hat{k} =$ vertically up (this triad satisfies $\\hat{i}\\times\\hat{j}=\\hat{k}$). Given $\\vec{A} = A\\hat{k}$ (up) and $\\vec{B} = B\\hat{j}$ (north): $$\\vec{A}\\times\\vec{B} = AB(\\hat{k}\\times\\hat{j})$$ Using the cyclic rule $\\hat{i}\\times\\hat{j}=\\hat{k},\\ \\hat{j}\\times\\hat{k}=\\hat{i},\\ \\hat{k}\\times\\hat{i}=\\hat{j}$, and that swapping the order reverses the sign: $$\\hat{k}\\times\\hat{j} = -(\\hat{j}\\times\\hat{k}) = -\\hat{i}$$ So $\\vec{A}\\times\\vec{B} = -AB\\,\\hat{i}$, which points in the $-\\hat{i}$ direction, i.e., **West**. (You can verify the same with the right-hand rule: curl the fingers of the right hand from \"up\" towards \"north\" — the thumb points west.) Answer: (A).\n- The radius $r = 2.12$ cm is given to **3 significant figures**. The area is $$A = \\pi r^2 = \\pi (2.12)^2 = \\pi \\times 4.4944 = 14.1204\\ldots \\text{ cm}^2$$ A calculated quantity cannot be more precise than the least precise measurement that produced it — the result must also be quoted to 3 significant figures (the constant $\\pi$ and the \"squaring\" don't add precision beyond what $r$ has). Rounding $14.1204\\ldots$ to 3 significant figures gives $$A = 14.1\\ \\text{cm}^2$$ Option (a) \"14 cm²\" has only 2 significant figures (under-reports precision), while (c) and (d) keep too many digits (over-stating the precision of the measurement). Answer: (B).\n- Pressure = Force / Area. $$[P] = \\frac{[\\rm Force]}{[\\rm Area]} = \\frac{\\rm MLT^{-2}}{\\rm L^2} = [\\rm ML^{-1}T^{-2}]$$ This is also the dimension of stress, Young's modulus, and bulk modulus. Answer: (B).\n- - Work: $[\\rm ML^2T^{-2}]$; Power: $[\\rm ML^2T^{-3}]$ — different. - **Torque**: $\\vec{\\tau}=\\vec{r}\\times\\vec{F}$: $[\\rm ML^2T^{-2}]$; **Energy**: $[\\rm ML^2T^{-2}]$ — **same**. - Force: $[\\rm MLT^{-2}]$; Impulse: $[\\rm MLT^{-1}]$ — different. - Linear momentum: $[\\rm MLT^{-1}]$; Angular momentum: $[\\rm ML^2T^{-1}]$ — different. Although torque and energy share the same dimensions, they are physically distinct (torque is a vector, energy is a scalar). Answer: (B).\n- Let $v = k\\,T^a\\mu^b$. Dimensions: $[\\rm LT^{-1}] = [\\rm MLT^{-2}]^a[\\rm ML^{-1}]^b$. Matching exponents: - M: $0 = a+b \\Rightarrow b=-a$ - L: $1 = a-b = a+a = 2a \\Rightarrow a=\\tfrac12$ - T: $-1 = -2a \\Rightarrow a=\\tfrac12$ ✓ So $v \\propto T^{1/2}\\mu^{-1/2} = \\sqrt{T/\\mu}$. This is the exact correct formula. Answer: (B).\n- Significant figures rules: - All non-zero digits are significant. - Zeros between non-zero digits are significant. - Trailing zeros **after** a decimal point are significant. $6.020\\times10^{23}$: digits are 6, 0, 2, 0. The zero between 6 and 2 is significant (rule 2), and the trailing zero after 2 is significant (rule 3). Total: **4** significant figures. The exponent ($10^{23}$) does not affect significant figures. Answer: (C).\n- Dimensional analysis requires every term to have the same dimensions. However, **trigonometric functions, logarithms, and exponentials are dimensionless** — their arguments must be dimensionless, and their outputs are dimensionless. In $\\sin\\theta = v/c$, the right side has dimensions $[\\rm LT^{-1}/LT^{-1}]$ = dimensionless, and $\\sin\\theta$ is dimensionless. While the equation may be dimensionally consistent, dimensional analysis cannot verify or derive such a relation (it can only check it for polynomial power-law relations). Answer: (D).",
