"id": "note-units-and-measurement-significant-figures",
"chapter": "Units and Measurement",
"subtopic": "Significant Figures",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-units",
"unitLabel": "Unit I — Physical World & Measurement",
"order": 0,
"title": "How significant figures and error propagation express precision",
"summary": "Significant figures are the reliably known digits of a measurement; rules govern counting them and how errors combine in calculations.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- All non-zero digits are significant; zeros between significant digits count; leading zeros do not.\n- Multiplication/division: keep as many significant figures as the least precise factor. Addition/subtraction: keep the least number of decimal places.\n- Error propagation: for $Z=ab$ or $a/b$, relative errors add; for $Z=a^n$, $\\dfrac{\\Delta Z}{Z}=n\\dfrac{\\Delta a}{a}$; for sums/differences, absolute errors add.\n**Exam traps**\n- Use least significant figures for ×/÷, but least decimal places for +/−.\n- Relative errors (not absolute) add for products and quotients.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{\\Delta(ab)}{ab}=\\dfrac{\\Delta a}{a}+\\dfrac{\\Delta b}{b}",
"meaning": "Relative error in a product/quotient"
},
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{\\Delta Z}{Z}=n\\dfrac{\\Delta a}{a}\\ \\ (Z=a^n)",
"meaning": "Error in a power"
},
{
"latex": "\\Delta(a\\pm b)=\\Delta a+\\Delta b",
"meaning": "Absolute error in a sum/difference"
}
],
