"unitLabel": "Unit I — Physical World & Measurement",
"order": 0,
"title": "How the SI system builds every unit from seven base units",
"summary": "SI has seven base units (metre, kilogram, second, ampere, kelvin, mole, candela); all derived units are products of powers of these.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- The seven base quantities: length (m), mass (kg), time (s), electric current (A), temperature (K), amount of substance (mol), luminous intensity (cd).\n- Derived units are combinations of base units, e.g. force $\\text{N}=\\text{kg m s}^{-2}$.\n- Plane angle (radian) and solid angle (steradian) are dimensionless.\n**Exam traps**\n- There are exactly seven base units; SI is a coherent system.\n- Plane and solid angles have units but no dimensions.",
