"title": "Acceleration",
"summary": "This situation is plotted on (v-t) graph.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- $$ \\mathrm{v}(t)=\\frac{dx}{dt}=4\\alpha t^{3}+2\\beta t+\\gamma $$ $$ \\alpha(t)=\\frac{d v}{d t}=12\\alpha t^{2}+2\\beta $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}&\\mathbf{v}(0)=4\\boldsymbol{\\alpha}\\times\\boldsymbol{0}+2\\boldsymbol{\\beta}\\times\\boldsymbol{0}+\\boldsymbol{\\gamma}=\\boldsymbol{\\gamma}\\\\&\\boldsymbol{\\alpha}(0)=12\\boldsymbol{\\alpha}\\times\\boldsymbol{0}+2\\boldsymbol{\\beta}=2\\boldsymbol{\\beta}\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$ The ratio of initial velocity to its initial acceleration is: $$ \\frac{\\mathrm{v}(\\mathfrak{A})}{a(0)}=\\frac{\\gamma}{2\\beta} $$\n- The velocity (v) as a function of position of particle is given by, Acceleration. $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathbf{v}&=\\beta\\mathbf{x}^{-2n}\\\\a&=\\frac{d\\mathbf{v}}{dt}=\\frac{dx}{dt},\\frac{d\\mathbf{v}}{dx}\\\\a&=\\frac{d\\mathbf{v}}{dx}.\\mathbf{v}=\\mathbf{v},\\frac{d\\mathbf{v}}{dx}\\\\&=\\beta\\mathbf{x}^{-2n}.(-2n\\beta\\mathbf{x}^{-2n-1})\\\\a&=-2n\\beta^{2}\\mathbf{x}^{-4n-1}\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\begin{array}{c}C)\\text{Acceleration,}\\frac{d\\mathbf{v}}{dt}=f=f_{0}\\left(1-\\frac{t}{\\mathrm{T}}\\right)\\\\ \\Rightarrow\\quad\\int_{0}^{\\mathrm{v}}d\\mathbf{v}=f_{0}\\int_{0}^{\\mathrm{T}}\\left(1-\\frac{t}{\\mathrm{T}}\\right)dt\\\\ \\Rightarrow\\quad\\mathbf{v}=f_{0}\\left(t-\\frac{t^{2}}{2\\mathrm{T}}\\right)_{0}^{\\mathrm{T}}\\\\ =f_{0}\\left(\\mathrm{T}-\\frac{\\mathrm{T}^{2}}{2\\mathrm{T}}\\right)=\\frac{1}{2}f_{0}\\mathrm{T}\\end{array} $$\n- Acceleration. $$ \\frac{dv}{dt}=\\frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}} $$ Velocity, $$ \\mathbf{v}=\\frac{dx}{dt}. $$ The given equation is, $$ x=a t^{2}-b t^{3} $$ Velocity, $$ \\mathrm{v}=\\frac{dx}{dt}=2at-3bt^{2} $$ Acceleration. $$ a=\\frac{d\\mathbf{v}}{dt}=2a-6bt $$ but $$ a=0 $$ (given) $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\bullet\\\\ \\bullet\\bullet\\end{array} $$ $$ 2a-6bt=0 $$ $$ 6bt=2a $$ $$ t=\\frac{2a}{6b}=\\frac{a}{3b} $$ or\n- This situation is plotted on (v-t) graph. In (v-t) graph, OA represents the accelerated part and AB represents the decelerated part. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//3b3777f9-8c7d-4c2a-be98-f0e26bc415ca/markdown_4/imgs/img_in_image_box_829_164_996_322.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A04Z%2F-1%2F%2F94c599b744cfdbbdd6e123833cf0780ecc89fd287bdaf148b3d6e429b26a2b47\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"14%\" /></div> Let $ t_{1} $ and $ t_{2} $ be the times for part OA and AB respectively. At point A velocity is maximum and let it be $ v_{max} $ But, $$ t=t_{1}+t_{2} $$ $$ \\mathbf{t}=\\mathbf{v}_{\\max}\\left(\\frac{1}{\\alpha}+\\frac{1}{\\beta}\\right)=\\mathbf{v}_{\\max}\\left(\\frac{\\alpha+\\beta}{\\alpha\\beta}\\right) $$ or $$ \\mathbf{v}_{\\max}=t\\left(\\frac{\\alpha\\beta}{\\alpha+\\beta}\\right) $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//3b3777f9-8c7d-4c2a-be98-f0e26bc415ca/markdown_4/imgs/img_in_image_box_641_601_673_643.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A04Z%2F-1%2F%2Fced233f300afa228e87330afc79cc54118f4196656ec97f884ef124b56ef0783\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"2%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory This problem can also be solved by checking the dimensions on both sides. On checking the dimensions, we note that the dimensions of option (d) match with that of velocity.",
