"id": "note-motion-in-a-straight-line-instantaneous-velocity-and-speed",
"chapter": "Motion in a Straight Line",
"subtopic": "Instantaneous Velocity and Speed",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-kinematics",
"unitLabel": "Unit II — Kinematics",
"order": 1,
"title": "Instantaneous Velocity and Speed",
"summary": "The given equation is $$ x=40+12t-t^{3} $$ On differentiating, we get, $$ u=\\frac{dx}{dt}=12-3t^{2} $$ When particle comes to rest means, v = 0 $\\therefore$ $12-3t^{2}=0$ $\\Rightarrow$ $t=2s$ The distance travelled…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- The given equation is $$ x=40+12t-t^{3} $$ On differentiating, we get, $$ u=\\frac{dx}{dt}=12-3t^{2} $$ When particle comes to rest means, v = 0 $\\therefore$ $12-3t^{2}=0$ $\\Rightarrow$ $t=2s$ The distance travelled before coming to rest $$ \\begin{aligned}\\int_{0}^{s}ds&=\\int_{0}^{2}\\mathbf{v}dt\\\\\\left[s\\right]_{0}^{s}&=\\int_{0}^{2}(12-3t^{2})dt\\\\s&=\\left[12t-\\frac{3t^{3}}{3}\\right]_{0}^{2}\\\\&=12\\times2-(8-0)\\\\&=16m.\\end{aligned} $$\n- From question, $$ x=ae^{-\\alpha t}+be^{\\beta t} $$ $$ \\mathrm{v}=\\frac{dx}{dt}=-a\\alpha e^{-\\alpha t}+b\\beta e^{\\beta t} $$ $$ \\mathbf{v}=-a\\alpha e^{-\\alpha t}+b\\beta e^{\\beta t} $$ ∴ Velocity will go on increasing with time.\n- Instantaneous velocity is the slope of displacement-time graph. At point E, the slope is negative, so instantaneous velocity of the particle is negative. At points C and F, the slope is positive and at D, the slope is zero.",
