"title": "Relative Velocity",
"summary": "$$ \\mathbf{v}_{s}=10+10=20\\;\\mathbf{m}\\mathbf{s}^{-1} $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Here, $ v_{SR} = 20 \\, m/s $ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//10bc9ad3-8476-4959-86d1-2968a4f9e613/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_image_box_707_1288_962_1491.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A52Z%2F-1%2F%2F9779ac5ab22236a8de6af6e48ce4b9b0f5b7a23836e1da7070de9a6cd1f2044d\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"21%\" /></div> $$ \\begin{array}{r}{\\mathbf{v}_{\\mathrm{R G}}\\quad=10\\mathrm{m/s}}\\end{array} $$ $$ \\mathbf{\\tilde{v}_{SG}}\\stackrel{\\rightarrow}{=}\\mathbf{\\tilde{v}_{SR}}\\stackrel{\\rightarrow}{+}\\mathbf{\\tilde{v}_{RG}} $$ $$ \\sin\\theta=\\left|\\frac{\\mathbf{v}_{\\mathrm{RG}}}{\\mathbf{v}_{\\mathrm{SR}}}\\right|=\\frac{10}{20}=\\frac{1}{2} $$ ↓ $$ \\theta=30^{\\circ}\\mathrm{w e s t}. $$\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//10bc9ad3-8476-4959-86d1-2968a4f9e613/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_96_253_372_423.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A54Z%2F-1%2F%2F9ba2c41a3d17bbcd42fa589a981b4124358dc5050f0d0156ba427d55648538ab\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"23%\" /></div> Let bullet collide at time t. $$ \\because $$ $$ x_{1}+x_{2}=100m $$ $$ 25t+25t=100 $$ $$ t=2s $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}y=\\frac{1}{2}gt^{2}=\\frac{1}{2}\\times10\\times2^{2}\\\\=20m\\\\h=200-20=180m\\end{aligned} $$ Hence, bullets will collide after 2 s at the height 180 m above the ground.\n- Velocity of girl with respect to elevator = $ \\frac{d}{t_1} = v_1 $ Velocity of elevator with respect to ground = $ \\frac{d}{t_2} = v_2 $ $ \\therefore $ Velocity of girl with respect to ground = $ v_g = v_1 + v_2 $ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{d}{t}&=\\frac{d}{t_{1}}+\\frac{d}{t_{2}}\\\\\\frac{1}{t}&=\\frac{1}{t_{1}}+\\frac{1}{t_{2}}\\\\t&=\\frac{t_{1}t_{2}}{t_{1}+t_{2}}\\end{aligned} $$\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//10bc9ad3-8476-4959-86d1-2968a4f9e613/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_94_1110_357_1285.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A55Z%2F-1%2F%2F5d2c8400a70c773d85c369ebe118e820c0f2ca40ad3d9f2ae03032ba0624805d\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"22%\" /></div> From the diagram, the distance S between the ships is, $$ \\mathrm{S}=\\sqrt{(100-x)^{2}+x^{2}}[\\mathrm{From~A~to~B}] $$ for $ S_{min} $, $$ \\frac{d\\mathbf{S}}{dx}=0 $$ $$ \\frac{dS}{dx}=\\frac{[-2(100-x)+2x]}{2[(100-x)^{2}+x^{2}]^{1/2}} $$ $$ \\left[-2\\left(100-x\\right)+2x\\right]=0 $$ $$ \\implies\\quad4x-200=0 $$ ⇨ $ x = 50 ~km $ So after both the ships have covered 50 km. The time taken is. $$ t=\\frac{x}{10}=\\frac{50}{10}=5h $$\n- S $ \\rightarrow $ 1 km B $ \\rightarrow $ $ u = 10 \\, ms^{-1} $ S = Scooter B = Bus Let v = relative velocity of S w.r.t. B $$ \\begin{aligned}&\\mathbf{V}=\\mathbf{V}_{S}-\\mathbf{V}_{\\mathbf{B}}\\\\&\\mathbf{V}_{S}=\\mathbf{V}+\\mathbf{V}_{\\mathbf{B}}\\end{aligned} $$ \\therefore Relative velocity = \\frac{Displacement}{time} = \\frac{1000}{100} = 10 ms^{-1} Putting this value in eq. (i),\n- $$ \\mathbf{v}_{s}=10+10=20\\;\\mathbf{m}\\mathbf{s}^{-1} $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//10bc9ad3-8476-4959-86d1-2968a4f9e613/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_790_748_1009_832.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A55Z%2F-1%2F%2F0b70845d2f0d2d4e8beab49a265c8997dd001c9da296682e4b7fafaee60af0d2\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"18%\" /></div> After time t, <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//10bc9ad3-8476-4959-86d1-2968a4f9e613/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_743_880_988_1114.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A55Z%2F-1%2F%2F18aa6e192038df1503e791b6ddb2d286c4a83c0f69635d1840b7119dbf33e740\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"20%\" /></div> $$ (\\mathbf{v}t)^{2}=a^{2}+(\\mathbf{v}_{1}t)^{2} $$ $$ \\mathbf{v}^{2}t^{2}=a^{2}+(\\mathbf{v}_{1}^{2}t)^{2} $$ $$ (\\mathbf{v}^{2}-\\mathbf{v}_{1}^{2})t^{2}=a^{2} $$ $$ t=\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{\\mathbf{v}^{2}-\\mathbf{v}_{1}^{2}}} $$\n- Average speed = $ \\frac{\\text{Total distance}}{\\text{Total time taken}} $ Average speed = $ \\frac{2s}{\\frac{s}{v}+\\frac{s}{2v}} $ $ =\\frac{2s\\times2v}{2s+s}=\\frac{4vs}{2s}=\\frac{4v}{3} $\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//10bc9ad3-8476-4959-86d1-2968a4f9e613/markdown_3/imgs/img_in_image_box_273_143_592_228.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A57Z%2F-1%2F%2F42b9d9af50043815e1a13c36777371438e7cf57c94d71549b5d2fd3c2cab047f\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"26%\" /></div> Time taken. $$ t_{1}=\\frac{x}{\\mathbf{v}_{1}}\\quad\\text{and}\\quad t_{2}=\\frac{x}{\\mathbf{v}_{2}} $$ $\\therefore$ Average velocity $\\mathbf{v}=\\frac{x+x}{t_{1}+t_{2}}=\\frac{2x}{\\frac{x}{v_{1}}+\\frac{x}{v_{2}}}=\\frac{2v_{1}v_{2}}{v_{1}+v_{2}}$ $$ \\frac{2}{\\mathbf{v}}=\\frac{1}{\\mathbf{v}_{1}}+\\frac{1}{\\mathbf{v}_{2}} $$ OR $$ \\mathbf{v}=\\frac{2\\mathbf{v}_{1}\\mathbf{v}_{2}}{\\mathbf{v}_{1}+\\mathbf{v}_{2}} $$\n- Average speed = $ \\frac{\\text{Total distance}}{\\text{Total time}} $ $ =\\frac{2d}{\\frac{d}{v_u}+\\frac{d}{v_d}}=\\frac{2v_d v_u}{v_d+v_u} $\n- Let the distance between two places be $d$ and $t_{1}$ is time taken by car to travel first-half length, $t_{2}$ is time taken by car to travel second-half length. Time taken by car to travel first-half length, $$ t_{1}=\\frac{\\left(\\frac{d}{2}\\right)}{40}=\\frac{d}{80} $$ Time taken by car to travel second-half length. $$ t_{2}=\\frac{\\left(\\frac{d}{2}\\right)}{60}=\\frac{d}{120} $$ ∴ Total time. $$ \\begin{aligned}t&=t_{1}+t_{2}\\\\&=\\frac{d}{80}+\\frac{d}{120}\\\\&=d\\left(\\frac{1}{80}+\\frac{1}{120}\\right)=\\frac{d}{48}\\end{aligned} $$ $\\therefore$ Average speed, $=\\frac{d}{t_{1}+t_{2}}=\\frac{d}{\\left(\\frac{d}{48}\\right)}$ $=48\\mathrm{~km/h}$",
