"id": "note-motion-in-a-plane-addition-and-subtraction-of-vectors-graphical-method",
"chapter": "Motion in a Plane",
"subtopic": "Addition and Subtraction of Vectors – Graphical Method",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-kinematics",
"unitLabel": "Unit II — Kinematics",
"order": 2,
"title": "Addition and Subtraction of Vectors – Graphical Method",
"summary": "According to the parallelogram law of vector addition, we can say that, $$ \\vec{d}+\\vec{e}=\\vec{f} $$",
"body": "**The figure (six vectors a–f)**\n<div style=\"text-align:center\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 360 200\" width=\"340\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Six vectors a to f; d points up, e points left, f is the up-left resultant, with d plus e equals f as a 3-4-5 right triangle\"><defs><marker id=\"ab\" markerUnits=\"userSpaceOnUse\" markerWidth=\"9\" markerHeight=\"9\" refX=\"7\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0L7,3L0,6Z\" fill=\"#2563eb\"/></marker><marker id=\"ag\" markerUnits=\"userSpaceOnUse\" markerWidth=\"9\" markerHeight=\"9\" refX=\"7\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0L7,3L0,6Z\" fill=\"#059669\"/></marker><marker id=\"ar\" markerUnits=\"userSpaceOnUse\" markerWidth=\"10\" markerHeight=\"10\" refX=\"7\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0L7,3L0,6Z\" fill=\"#dc2626\"/></marker></defs><text x=\"8\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#475569\" font-style=\"italic\">As shown in the figure</text><text x=\"216\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#475569\" font-style=\"italic\">Why &#8201;d&#8407; + e&#8407; = f&#8407;</text><line x1=\"200\" y1=\"26\" x2=\"200\" y2=\"192\" stroke=\"#e2e8f0\"/><line x1=\"40\" y1=\"64\" x2=\"40\" y2=\"40\" stroke=\"#94a3b8\" stroke-width=\"2\" marker-end=\"url(#ab)\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"46\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#64748b\">a</text><line x1=\"90\" y1=\"66\" x2=\"112\" y2=\"46\" stroke=\"#94a3b8\" stroke-width=\"2\" marker-end=\"url(#ab)\"/><text x=\"116\" y=\"48\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#64748b\">b</text><line x1=\"146\" y1=\"53\" x2=\"174\" y2=\"53\" stroke=\"#94a3b8\" stroke-width=\"2\" marker-end=\"url(#ab)\"/><text x=\"158\" y=\"46\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#64748b\">c</text><line x1=\"40\" y1=\"150\" x2=\"40\" y2=\"114\" stroke=\"#059669\" stroke-width=\"2.5\" marker-end=\"url(#ag)\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"134\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#059669\" font-weight=\"bold\">d</text><line x1=\"120\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"72\" y2=\"130\" stroke=\"#059669\" stroke-width=\"2.5\" marker-end=\"url(#ag)\"/><text x=\"92\" y=\"124\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#059669\" font-weight=\"bold\">e</text><line x1=\"184\" y1=\"156\" x2=\"148\" y2=\"120\" stroke=\"#dc2626\" stroke-width=\"2.5\" marker-end=\"url(#ar)\"/><text x=\"160\" y=\"146\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#dc2626\" font-weight=\"bold\">f</text><line x1=\"300\" y1=\"178\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"138\" stroke=\"#059669\" stroke-width=\"2.5\" marker-end=\"url(#ag)\"/><text x=\"305\" y=\"162\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#059669\" font-weight=\"bold\">d</text><line x1=\"300\" y1=\"138\" x2=\"248\" y2=\"138\" stroke=\"#059669\" stroke-width=\"2.5\" marker-end=\"url(#ag)\"/><text x=\"268\" y=\"132\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#059669\" font-weight=\"bold\">e</text><line x1=\"300\" y1=\"178\" x2=\"248\" y2=\"138\" stroke=\"#dc2626\" stroke-width=\"2.5\" marker-end=\"url(#ar)\"/><text x=\"258\" y=\"166\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#dc2626\" font-weight=\"bold\">f</text><path d=\"M300,148 L290,148 L290,138\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#94a3b8\"/></svg></div>\n- In the given figure $ \\vec{d} $ points up and $ \\vec{e} $ points left, so placing $ \\vec{e} $ head-to-tail on $ \\vec{d} $ closes the triangle along $ \\vec{f} $ — a 3–4–5 right triangle.\n- **By the triangle / parallelogram law:** $$ \\vec{d}+\\vec{e}=\\vec{f} $$\n- **Why the others fail:** $ \\vec{b}+\\vec{c} $, $ \\vec{d}+\\vec{c} $ and $ \\vec{b}+\\vec{e} $ do not line up head-to-tail to reproduce $ \\vec{f} $, so options A, B and D are false. Only $ \\vec{d}+\\vec{e}=\\vec{f} $ holds. **(AIPMT Screening 2010)**",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\vec{d}+\\vec{e}=\\vec{f}",
"meaning": ""
}
],
