"title": "Projectile Motion",
"summary": "<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Max. height, H = $ \\frac{u^{2}\\sin^{2}\\theta}{2g} $ Here: $$ u=280~\\mathrm{m s}^{-1} $$ $$ \\theta=30^{\\circ} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}H&=\\frac{(280)^{2}\\times\\sin^{2}30^{\\circ}}{2\\times9.8}\\\\&=\\frac{(280)^{2}\\times\\frac{1}{4}}{2\\times9.8}=1000m\\end{aligned} $$\n- Given: velocity of ball = 10 m/s, Angle with vertical direction = $ 60^{\\circ} $ From question. we can say that speed of the ball at the highest point = v $ \\cos \\theta $ where, $ \\theta = 90^{\\circ} - 60^{\\circ} = 30^{\\circ} $ $$ \\mathbf{v}=10\\times\\cos\\left(30^{\\circ}\\right)=10\\times\\left(\\frac{\\left(\\sqrt{3}\\right)}{2}\\right) $$ $$ \\mathbf{v}=5\\sqrt{3}\\mathrm{~m/s} $$\n- The speed of a projectile at its maximum height $$ \\mathbf{v}^{\\prime}=\\mathbf{v}_{0}\\cos\\theta $$ According to given problem, $$ \\mathbf{v}^{\\prime}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}_{0}}{2} $$ $$ \\frac{\\mathbf{v}_{0}}{2}=\\mathbf{v}_{0}\\cos\\theta $$ $$ ↳\\Downarrow $$ $$ \\theta=\\frac{1}{2} $$ $$ \\theta=60^{\\circ} $$\n- The equation of trajectory is, $$ y=x\\tan\\theta-\\frac{gx^{2}}{2u^{2}\\cos^{2}\\theta}, $$ where, $\\theta$ is the angle of projection and $u$ is the velocity with which projectile is projected. For equal trajectories and for same angles of projection, $$ \\frac{g}{u^{2}}=constant $$ As per question, $$ \\frac{9.8}{\\left(5\\right)^{2}}=\\frac{g^{\\prime}}{\\left(3\\right)^{2}}, $$ where $g'$ is acceleration due to gravity on the planet.\n- We know that, $$ g^{\\prime}=\\frac{9.8\\times9}{25}\\approx3.5\\mathrm{~m/s^{2}} $$ Range, $$ R=\\frac{u^{2}(2\\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta)}{g} $$ and Height, $$ \\mathrm{H}=\\frac{u^{2}\\sin^{2}\\theta}{2g} $$ According to the question, $$ \\boldsymbol{R}=\\boldsymbol{H} $$ $$ \\frac{u^{2}(2\\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta)}{g}=\\frac{u^{2}\\sin^{2}\\theta}{2g} $$ $$ 2\\cos\\theta=\\frac{\\sin\\theta}{2} $$ $$ \\Downarrow\\Downarrow $$ $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\tan\\theta=4\\\\\\theta=\\tan^{-1}\\left(4\\right)\\end{array} $$\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//b2be096f-d674-4960-9509-b14d75f1ea94/markdown_0/imgs/img_in_image_box_778_575_995_685.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A30Z%2F-1%2F%2F05620f5089d104032402691cc279b81a844bff21bf63ed3322c24f752f07d520\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"18%\" /></div> Height of Projectile, $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\text{H}=\\displaystyle \\frac{u^{2} \\sin^{2} \\theta}{2g} \\\\ = \\displaystyle \\frac{u^{2} \\sin^{2} 45^{\\circ}}{2g} \\\\ = \\displaystyle \\frac{u^{2}}{4g}\\end{array} $$ and Range of projectile, $$ \\begin{aligned}R&=\\frac{u^{2}\\sin2\\theta}{g}\\\\&=\\frac{u^{2}\\sin90^{\\circ}}{g}\\\\&=\\frac{u^{2}}{g}\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{2}=\\frac{u^{2}}{2g} $$ $$ \\tan\\alpha=\\frac{H}{R/2}=\\frac{u^{2}/4g}{u^{2}/2g} $$ considering eq. (i) and eq. (ii), $$ \\tan\\alpha=\\frac{H}{R/2} $$ $$ \\alpha=\\frac{1}{2} $$ $$ \\alpha=\\tan^{-1}\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right) $$\n- As we know that, maximum range, $$ \\mathrm{R}_{\\max}=\\frac{u^{2}}{g}=\\frac{(20)^{2}}{10}=40\\mathrm{~m} $$\n- Horizontal range. $$ \\mathrm{R}=\\frac{u^{2}\\sin2\\theta}{g} $$ When angle of projection is $ (45^{\\circ}-\\theta) $ then, $$ \\begin{aligned}R_{1}&=\\frac{u^{2}\\sin2(45^{\\circ}-\\theta)}{g}\\\\&=\\frac{u^{2}\\sin(90^{\\circ}-2\\theta)}{g}\\\\&=\\frac{u^{2}\\cos2\\theta}{g}\\end{aligned} $$ If angle of projection is $ (45^{\\circ} + \\theta) $ then, $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\text{R}_{2}=\\displaystyle\\frac{u^{2}\\sin2(45^{\\circ}+2\\theta)}{g}\\\\ \\quad=\\displaystyle\\frac{u^{2}\\sin(90^{\\circ}+2\\theta)}{g}\\\\ \\quad=\\displaystyle\\frac{u^{2}\\cos2\\theta}{g}\\end{array} $$ Now, $$ \\frac{R_{1}}{R_{2}}=\\frac{u^{2}\\cos\\frac{2\\theta}{g}}{u^{2}\\cos\\frac{2\\theta}{g}}=1:1 $$\n- Range of projectile is given by, $$ \\mathrm{R}=\\frac{u^{2}\\sin2\\theta}{g} $$ For maximum range, angle should be $ 45^{\\circ} $. $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\text{R}_{\\text{max}}=\\displaystyle\\frac{u^{2}\\sin2\\times45^{\\circ}}{g}\\\\=\\displaystyle\\frac{u^{2}\\sin90^{\\circ}}{g}\\end{array} $$ Or $$ R_{max}=\\frac{u^{2}}{g} $$ Here, $$ \\begin{aligned}R_{max}&=\\frac{u^{2}}{g}=16km\\\\&=16000m\\end{aligned} $$ or $$ \\begin{array}{l}u=\\sqrt{16000\\times g}\\\\=\\sqrt{16000\\times10}\\\\=400\\mathrm{~m s}^{-1}\\end{array} $$",
