"id": "note-motion-in-a-plane-uniform-circular-motion",
"chapter": "Motion in a Plane",
"subtopic": "Uniform Circular Motion",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-kinematics",
"unitLabel": "Unit II — Kinematics",
"order": 2,
"title": "Uniform Circular Motion",
"summary": "$$ \\begin{aligned}\\overrightarrow{r}&=\\cos\\omega t\\overrightarrow{x}+\\sin\\omega t\\overrightarrow{y}\\\\\\overrightarrow{v}&=\\frac{\\overrightarrow{d}\\overrightarrow{r}}{dt}=-\\omega\\sin\\omega…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- $ \\omega_{1}x_{1}=\\omega_{2}x_{2}=\\omega_{3}x_{3}=k $ The product of angular speed and angular distance remains constant for each hand of the clock.\n- A particle moving with uniform speed in a circular path has varying velocity as the direction of motion changes continuously. The magnitude of velocity remains constant. As the direction of centripetal acceleration is changing. The particle has varying acceleration. ##### △! Caution Students should not get confused about the direction of acceleration. It is always directed towards centre but position of particle keep changing and hence overall direction of acceleration vector changes.\n- In case of rolling, the velocity of the point of contact with the surface is zero. Also, the velocity of the point of the highest point of the rolling body is twice the velocity of COM of the body. So. point body P moves faster then point Q.\n- Given, $$ \\begin{array}{l}Radius=R\\\\Time=T for one revolution\\end{array} $$ Angle of projection = $ \\theta $ $$ H_{max}=4R $$ $$ \\mathbf{v}=\\frac{2\\pi\\mathbf{R}}{\\mathbf{T}}\\quad(from~circular~motion) $$ $$ \\mathrm{H}_{\\max}=\\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{y}^{2}}{2g}=\\frac{\\mathrm{v}^{2}\\sin^{2}\\theta}{2g}=4\\mathrm{R} $$ $$ \\frac{4\\pi^{2}R^{2}}{T^{2}}\\times\\frac{\\sin^{2}\\theta}{2g}=4R $$ $$ \\sin^{2}\\theta=\\frac{8gT^{2}}{4\\pi^{2}R}=\\frac{2gT^{2}}{\\pi^{2}R} $$ $$ \\theta=\\sin^{-1}\\left(\\frac{2g\\mathrm{T}^{2}}{\\pi^{2}\\mathrm{R}}\\right)^{1/2} $$\n- $$ \\begin{aligned}\\overrightarrow{r}&=\\cos\\omega t\\overrightarrow{x}+\\sin\\omega t\\overrightarrow{y}\\\\\\overrightarrow{v}&=\\frac{\\overrightarrow{d}\\overrightarrow{r}}{dt}=-\\omega\\sin\\omega t\\overrightarrow{x}+\\omega\\cos\\omega t\\overrightarrow{y}\\\\\\overrightarrow{a}&=\\frac{\\overrightarrow{d}\\overrightarrow{v}}{dt}=-\\omega^{2}\\cos\\omega t\\overrightarrow{x}-\\omega^{2}\\sin\\omega t\\overrightarrow{y}\\\\&=-\\omega^{2}\\overrightarrow{r}\\end{aligned} $$ $ \\overrightarrow{a} $ is directed towards the origin. Also, $ \\overrightarrow{r} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{v} = 0 $, Hence, $$ \\overrightarrow{r}\\perp\\overrightarrow{v} $$\n- We have, centripetal acceleration of rotating body Since, $$ \\begin{array}{l}a_{c}=\\frac{v^{2}}{r}=\\frac{v^{2}\\omega^{2}}{r}=r\\omega^{2}\\quad(\\text{as}v=r\\omega)\\\\\\omega=2\\pi v,\\end{array} $$ where v is frequency of rotation. ∴ $$ a_{c}=r\\left(2\\pi\\mathbf{v}\\right)^{2}=r\\times4\\pi^{2}\\mathbf{v}^{2} $$ Here, $$ r=30cm=30\\times10^{-2}m=0.30m $$ $$ \\mathrm{v}=120\\mathrm{rev}/\\mathrm{m}=\\frac{120}{60}\\mathrm{rev}/\\mathrm{s}=2\\mathrm{rev}/\\mathrm{s} $$ $$ \\begin{array}{l}a_{c}=(0.30\\times4\\times3.14\\times3.14\\times2\\times2)\\\\=47.4\\mathrm{~m s}^{-2}\\end{array} $$",
