"unitLabel": "Unit III — Laws of Motion",
"order": 3,
"title": "How weight, normal reaction, tension and friction act",
"summary": "Everyday mechanics uses weight (mg), the normal reaction (perpendicular to the surface), tension (along strings) and friction (opposing relative motion, with f ≤ μN).",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Weight $W=mg$, directed downward; normal reaction $N$ acts perpendicular to the contact surface.\n- Tension acts along a string and is the same throughout a light (massless) string.\n- Friction: static $f_s\\le\\mu_s N$, kinetic $f_k=\\mu_k N$, with $\\mu_s>\\mu_k$.\n- Angle of repose: $\\mu_s=\\tan\\theta$.\n**Exam traps**\n- The normal force is not always equal to $mg$ (think of inclines and accelerating lifts).\n- Static friction adjusts up to its maximum; kinetic friction is essentially constant.",
