"title": "How rigid-body motion = translation of the CM + rotation about the CM",
"summary": "Any rigid-body motion splits into translation of the centre of mass plus rotation about the CM; every linear quantity has a rotational analogue, and rolling links the two through $v_{cm}=\\omega R$.",
"body": "**Linear ↔ rotational analogues**\n- $x\\leftrightarrow\\theta,\\ v\\leftrightarrow\\omega,\\ a\\leftrightarrow\\alpha$.\n- mass $m\\leftrightarrow$ moment of inertia $I$; force $F\\leftrightarrow$ torque $\\tau$; momentum $p\\leftrightarrow$ angular momentum $L$.\n- $\\dfrac{1}{2}mv^2\\leftrightarrow\\dfrac{1}{2}I\\omega^2$.\n**Rolling without slipping**\n- Condition: $v_{cm}=\\omega R$.\n- Total KE: $KE=\\dfrac{1}{2}Mv_{cm}^2+\\dfrac{1}{2}I_{cm}\\omega^2=\\dfrac{1}{2}Mv_{cm}^2\\left(1+\\dfrac{k^2}{R^2}\\right)$.\n- Down an incline: $a=\\dfrac{g\\sin\\theta}{1+\\dfrac{I_{cm}}{MR^2}}$.\n**Exam traps**\n- For bodies rolling down the same incline the acceleration order is sphere $>$ disc $>$ ring (smaller $I/MR^2$ wins).\n- In pure rolling, static friction provides the torque but does no work.",
