"order": 6,
"title": "How Kepler's three laws describe planetary orbits",
"summary": "Kepler: (1) orbits are ellipses with the Sun at a focus; (2) the radius vector sweeps equal areas in equal times (angular-momentum conservation); (3) T² ∝ a³.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Law of orbits: each planet moves in an ellipse with the Sun at one focus.\n- Law of areas: $\\dfrac{dA}{dt}=\\dfrac{L}{2m}=\\text{constant}$, so a planet moves fastest at perihelion.\n- Law of periods: $T^2\\propto a^3$, where $a$ is the semi-major axis.\n**Exam traps**\n- The equal-area law is a direct consequence of angular-momentum conservation.\n- $T^2\\propto a^3$ uses the semi-major axis, not the instantaneous distance.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{dA}{dt}=\\dfrac{L}{2m}=\\text{constant}",
"meaning": "Law of areas (areal velocity)"
},
{
"latex": "T^2\\propto a^3",
"meaning": "Law of periods"
},
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{T_1^2}{T_2^2}=\\dfrac{a_1^3}{a_2^3}",
"meaning": "Comparing two orbits"
}
],
