"id": "note-mechanical-properties-of-solids-objective-ii",
"chapter": "Mechanical Properties of Solids",
"subtopic": "Objective II",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-properties",
"unitLabel": "Units VI & VII — Properties of Bulk Matter",
"order": 7,
"title": "Objective II",
"summary": "On Earth, the sphere reaches terminal velocity ($20$ m/s) when the upward viscous drag force exactly balances its (effective) downward weight: $F_{\\text{drag}}(20\\text{ m/s}) \\approx mg$ (treating the sphere as dense…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Molecules at the surface of a liquid behave differently from those deep in the bulk because of their **asymmetric environment**: - **(C)** A surface molecule has *liquid* molecules on one side (below/around it) but a *different kind of medium* — air/vapour molecules — on the other side, within its sphere of molecular influence. A bulk molecule, by contrast, is surrounded uniformly by molecules of its own liquid in all directions. - **(D)** Because of this asymmetry, the net force of attraction on a surface molecule (from the liquid molecules on one side, which vastly outnumber/outweigh the attraction from the sparse vapour molecules on the other) is **unbalanced and directed into the bulk** — unlike a bulk molecule, which experiences zero net force due to symmetric attraction from all sides. This net inward pull is the microscopic origin of surface tension. (Surface molecules are not physically smaller, and they don't acquire charge through collisions — these are not real effects relevant here.) Answer: (C, D).\n- The capillary rise is given by $h = \\dfrac{2S\\cos\\theta}{\\rho g r}$, where $S$ (surface tension) and $\\theta$ (contact angle) both depend on the **nature/material** of the liquid and the tube's surface — so: - **(A)** The rise depends on the **material** (of both liquid and tube, through $S$, $\\rho$, and $\\theta$). ✓ - **(D)** The rise depends directly on the **inner radius** $r$ of the tube — this is the radius that determines the curvature of the meniscus and appears explicitly in the formula. ✓ - **(C)** The **outer radius** of the tube plays no role — it doesn't affect the meniscus or the pressure balance inside the bore of the tube. ✗ - **(B)** The **length** of the tube normally doesn't matter (for a sufficiently long tube, the formula above gives the rise independent of length) — *but* if the tube is shorter than the height $h$ that the formula predicts, the liquid can only rise as far as the top of the tube, where the meniscus then adjusts its curvature to a smaller value to maintain equilibrium. So for short tubes, the length *does* limit/affect the rise — making this a valid dependency in general. ✓ Answer: (A, B, D).\n- The **contact angle** is determined by the relative strengths of the **adhesive forces** (between liquid molecules and the solid surface) and the **cohesive forces** (between liquid molecules themselves) — both of which depend on the *chemical/molecular nature* of the materials involved: - **(A)** the material of the **solid** — determines the strength of adhesion. ✓ - **(B)** the material of the **liquid** — determines the strength of cohesion (and also influences adhesion). ✓ - **(C)**, **(D)** the *shape* or *mass* of the solid have no bearing on the molecular-level interactions that set the contact angle — a larger or oddly-shaped piece of the same solid material gives exactly the same contact angle with a given liquid. ✗ Answer: (A, B).\n- With contact angle zero, the liquid wets the walls completely, and the surface-tension force acts **vertically** (tangent to the liquid surface, along the wall) on each element of the contact line (the line where the liquid meets the tube's inner wall), with magnitude equal to $S \\times (\\text{length of contact line})$. For a semicircular cross-section of radius $r$: - The **curved part** (the semicircular arc) has a contact-line length of $\\pi r$. - The **flat part** (the diameter) has a contact-line length of $2r$. Since the surface tension force on each part is simply $S$ times the corresponding contact-line length, the ratio of the forces is just the ratio of these lengths: $$\\frac{F_{\\text{curved}}}{F_{\\text{flat}}} = \\frac{S(\\pi r)}{S(2r)} = \\frac{\\pi}{2}$$ Answer: (C).\n- The capillary rise/depression is governed by $h = \\dfrac{2S\\cos\\theta}{\\rho g r}$. For the liquid level inside the tube to **neither rise nor fall** ($h = 0$), we need $\\cos\\theta = 0$ (i.e., $\\theta = 90°$) for an ordinary liquid with nonzero surface tension — this is the principal physical condition for \"no capillary action,\" since a contact angle of exactly $90°$ means the liquid surface inside the tube meets the wall without any net vertical pull in either direction. - **(B), (D)**: For any real liquid (with $S \\neq 0$), zero capillary rise *requires* the contact angle to be $90°$ — and conversely, whenever the contact angle *is* $90°$, the rise is zero. So the contact angle being $90°$ is both the expected (necessary, for $S\\ne0$) and a sufficient (\"may be\") condition. ✓ - **(C)**: As a separate (limiting/edge) possibility, if the surface tension itself were zero, there would trivially be no capillary action at all (regardless of the contact angle) — so \"the surface tension may be zero\" describes a valid alternative scenario leading to $h=0$. ✓ - **(A)**: However, it is *not* **necessary** for the surface tension to be zero — the much more common and expected explanation is simply that the contact angle equals $90°$ (with $S \\neq 0$). So \"must be zero\" is too strong a requirement. ✗ Answer: (B, C, D).\n- On Earth, the sphere reaches terminal velocity ($20$ m/s) when the upward viscous drag force exactly balances its (effective) downward weight: $F_{\\text{drag}}(20\\text{ m/s}) \\approx mg$ (treating the sphere as dense enough that buoyancy is a small correction). Now, in the **gravity-free hall**, there is **no weight** acting on the sphere at all (and no buoyancy either, since buoyancy itself arises from a gravity-induced pressure gradient in the fluid). The *only* force present is the **viscous drag**, which depends solely on the sphere's speed relative to the air — and since the air is at the same pressure and the sphere is moving at the same speed ($20$ m/s), the drag force has the **same magnitude as before**, $\\approx mg$, but now it is the *only* force, and it always acts **opposite to the velocity** (i.e., here, *upward*, since the sphere moves *downward*): - **(B)** Initial acceleration $= F_{\\text{drag}}/m \\approx g = 9.8\\text{ m/s}^2$, directed **upward** (opposing the downward motion). ✓ — and (A), claiming a *downward* $9.8$ m/s² (which would require gravity, absent here), is wrong. - **(C)** As the upward drag decelerates the sphere, its speed decreases — and since drag force depends on speed, the force (and hence the deceleration) **progressively decreases**. ✓ - **(D)** With no other force to sustain or reverse the motion, the sphere's speed asymptotically approaches zero, and it **eventually comes to rest** (and stays at rest, since at $v=0$ there is no drag and no other force to set it moving again). ✓ Answer: (B, C, D).",
