"title": "Bernoulli's Principle",
"summary": "Rate of flow of liquid, <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- According to the equation of continuity, $$ \\mathbf{A}_{x}\\mathbf{v}_{y}=\\mathbf{A}_{y}\\mathbf{v}_{y} $$ where $A_{x}$ and $A_{y}$ are the cross sectional areas $v_{x}$ and $v_{y}$ are velocities. Since, the fluid is flowing from a narrow section (x) to a wider section (y), to satisfy the continuity equation, the velocity at narrow must be greater than at wider section. Bernoulli's equation. $$ \\mathrm{P}+\\frac{1}{2}\\rho\\mathrm{v}^{2}+\\rho g h=\\mathrm{constant} $$ $$ \\mathrm{P}_{s}+\\frac{1}{2}\\rho\\mathrm{v}_{s}^{2}=\\mathrm{P}_{y}+\\frac{1}{2}\\rho\\mathrm{v}_{y}^{2}, $$ $$ \\mathbf{K}_{1}=\\frac{1}{2}\\rho\\mathbf{v}_{x}^{2} $$ $$ \\mathbf{K}_{2}=\\frac{1}{2}\\rho\\mathbf{v}_{y}^{2} $$ $ v_{x} > v_{y} $ it follows: Since,\n- Venturimeter is a device which is used for measuring rate of flow of fluids. It works on Bernoulli's principle. $$ \\mathbf{K}_{1}>\\mathbf{K}_{2} $$ #### Related Theory In liquid elements, an incompressible liquid's velocity must increased as it goes through a tightening as per the guideline of mass coherence, while its static pressure must diminish as per the standard of protection of mechanical energy (Bernoulli's rule).\n- Rate of flow of liquid, <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//7fd99a06-011a-431b-8b12-608a6e715545/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_801_595_1042_727.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A33Z%2F-1%2F%2F994d7e51bbb3fa6c203cab7c9c468973060ceeb66c7cc6474a1b87355b95db2b\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"20%\" /></div> $$ \\begin{aligned}Q&=a\\mathbf{v}=a\\sqrt{2gh}\\\\&=2\\times10^{-6}\\mathrm{m}^{2}\\times\\sqrt{2\\times10\\times2}\\mathrm{m/s}\\\\&=2\\times2\\times3.14\\times10^{-6}\\mathrm{m}^{3}/\\mathrm{s}\\\\&=12.56\\times10^{-6}\\mathrm{m}^{3}/\\mathrm{s}\\\\&=12.6\\times10^{-6}\\mathrm{m}^{3}/\\mathrm{s}\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- Applying Bernoulli's theorem to two points just inside the house and outside the house. $$ \\mathrm{P}+\\frac{1}{2}\\rho\\mathrm{v}^{2}=\\mathrm{constant} $$ Inside the pressure is $P_{\\mathrm{atm}}$ the pressure outside is P and v is zero inside, $$ \\therefore\\quad\\mathrm{P}-\\mathrm{P}_{atm}=\\frac{1}{2}\\rho\\mathrm{v}^{2}=\\frac{1}{2}\\times1.2\\times40^{2}=960 $$ then force is: $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{F}&=(\\mathrm{P}-\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{atm}})\\times\\mathrm{Area}\\\\&=960\\times250\\\\&=2.4\\times10^{5}\\mathrm{~N}\\end{aligned} $$ Force is in upward direction as pressure goes from higher to lower pressure area.\n- The velocity is maximum at the narrowest part of the pipe and pressure is maximum at the widest part of the pipe. Using equation of continuity. $$ \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{v}=\\mathbf{c o n s t a n t}. $$ And According to the Bernoulli's theorem. $$ \\mathbf{P}+\\mathrm{\\Large~\\frac{1}{2}~}\\rho\\mathbf{v}^{2}\\mathrm{\\Large~=~c o n s t a n t} $$",
