"title": "Pressure",
"summary": "In the given situation as shown in the figure below, Pressure due to water column of height 15 cm = Pressure due to oil column of height 20 cm $ \\Rightarrow h_{w}D_{w}g = h_{0}D_{0}g $ <div style=\"text-align:…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- From the given question, Density of liquid, $ \\rho_{l}=760\\ kg/m^{3} $ Density of mercury, $ \\rho_{m} = 13600 \\, kg/m^{3} $ Height of liquid column in mercury barometer $$ h_{m}=760\\ cm=0.76m $$ If height of liquid in liquid column is $h_{1}$ then: $$ \\begin{array}{l}P_{liquid}=P_{mercury}\\\\h_{l}\\rho_{l}g=h_{m}\\rho_{m}g\\\\h_{l}=\\frac{h_{m}\\rho_{m}}{\\rho_{l}}\\\\=\\frac{0.76\\times13600}{760}\\\\=13.6m.\\end{array} $$\n- In the given situation as shown in the figure below, Pressure due to water column of height 15 cm = Pressure due to oil column of height 20 cm $ \\Rightarrow h_{w}D_{w}g = h_{0}D_{0}g $ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//7fd99a06-011a-431b-8b12-608a6e715545/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_image_box_173_1329_440_1523.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A30Z%2F-1%2F%2F232b85b6a506ba7b1774c078303449f4cc896e774f1026460a57bf0c5e64bdca\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"22%\" /></div> $$ 15\\uprho_{w}=20\\uprho_{\\mathrm{o}} $$ $$ \\rho_{0}=\\frac{15}{20}\\rho_{w} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\rho_{0}&=\\frac{15}{20}\\times1000\\\\&\\quad(\\because Given:\\rho_{w}=1000kg m^{-3})\\\\&=750kg m^{-3}\\end{aligned} $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//7fd99a06-011a-431b-8b12-608a6e715545/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_image_box_577_1185_611_1229.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A31Z%2F-1%2F%2Faae734c0b38809920e19e364c0fc601f37ccaad7ba431207cb9258d2d59e42f2\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"2%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory According to Pascal's law, \"Pressure applied to enclosed fluid is transmitted undiminished to every point of the fluid and the walls of the containing vessel.\"\n- The given figure explain the situation of the question, <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//7fd99a06-011a-431b-8b12-608a6e715545/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_image_box_758_1370_965_1517.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A31Z%2F-1%2F%2Ffcaa4980de3a461b3ac3fc69791ba996ab3ac95e1b5e2ee150b418dccd9299ed\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"17%\" /></div> Applying Archimedes principle, $$ \\mathrm{Weight~of~cylinder}=(\\mathrm{upthrust})_{1}+(\\mathrm{upthrust})_{2} $$ $$ \\Rightarrow\\quad\\mathrm{L A}d g=(p\\mathrm{L})\\mathrm{A}(n\\uprho)\\mathrm{g}+(1-p)\\mathrm{L A}\\uprho g $$ $$ \\Rightarrow\\quad d=\\left(1-p\\right)\\uprho+\\left(p n\\right)\\uprho=\\left[1+\\left(n-1\\right)p\\right]\\uprho $$\n- Pressure = 150 mm of Hg Pumping rate = $ \\frac{dV}{dt} = \\frac{5 \\times 10^{-3}}{60} \\, \\text{m}^{3}/\\text{s} $ $$ \\begin{array}{l} \\text{Power of heart} =\\displaystyle {\\lim_{\\text{pt } d \\to 8}} \\frac{\\text{P.d} \\text{V}}{\\text{dt}} = \\rho g h \\cdot \\frac{\\text{dV}}{\\text{dt}} \\\\ \\qquad = (13.6 \\times 10^{3}) \\ (10) \\times (0.15) \\times \\frac{5 \\times 10^{-3}}{60} \\\\ \\qquad = \\frac{13.6 \\times 5 \\times 0.15}{6} = 1.70 \\text{ Watt} \\end{array} $$\n- Depth of the ocean, d = 2700 m Compressibility of water, $$ k=45.4\\times10^{-14}Pa^{-1} $$ Density of water, $ \\rho = 10^{3} $ kg/m $ ^{3} $ The pressure at the bottom of ocean is, $$ \\begin{array}{l} \\text{P} =\\displaystyle {\\lim_{\\text{pg } d \\to}} 10 ( 10^{3}+10 \\times 2700 - 27 \\times 10^{6} \\text{Pa}) \\\\ \\qquad = 10 \\text{ cm} \\end{array} $$ \\therefore Fractional compression = Compressibility $ \\times $ pressure $ =45.4 \\times 10^{-11} \\times 27 \\times 10^{6} $ $ =1.2 \\times 10^{-2} $",
