"id": "note-mechanical-properties-of-fluids-surface-tension",
"chapter": "Mechanical Properties of Fluids",
"subtopic": "Surface Tension",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-properties",
"unitLabel": "Units VI & VII — Properties of Bulk Matter",
"order": 8,
"title": "Surface Tension",
"summary": "We know that, Change in Surface Energy, $ \\Delta E = T\\Delta A $ where, $$ \\Delta A=Change~in~Surface~Area $$ $$ \\mathrm{T}=\\mathrm{Surface~Tension} $$ $$…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- For a circular disc $$ \\mathrm{F}_{\\mathrm{e x c e s s}}=2\\pi r\\mathrm{~T~} $$ where, $r$ is radius of disc and $T$ is the surface tension. Substituting the given values in eq. (i) we get $$ \\begin{aligned}F_{excess}&=2\\pi\\times4.5\\times10^{-2}\\times0.07\\\\&=2\\times\\frac{22}{7}\\times4.5\\times10^{-2}\\times7\\times10^{-2}\\\\&=198\\times10^{-4}=19.8mN\\end{aligned} $$\n- Given: Radius, $r=2\\mathrm{~cm}=2\\times10^{-2}\\mathrm{~m}$ Surface tension, $S=0.03\\mathrm{~Nm}^{-1}$ We know that, surface tension $=\\frac{\\text{Surface energy}}{\\text{Surface area}}$ $S=\\frac{U}{A}$ $U=S\\times A$ $=0.03\\times2\\times(4\\pi r^{2})$ $=0.03\\times2\\times(4\\times3.14)\\times(2\\times10^{-2})^{2}$ $=3.014\\times10^{-4}\\mathrm{~J}$\n- As we know that the pressure of the soap bubble is written as; $$ \\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{i}}-\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{o}}=\\frac{4\\mathrm{T}}{r} $$ When the soap bubble expands, the radius of the soap bubble will increase, therefore from equation (i), we see that the change in pressure is inversely proportional to the radius of the soap. ∴Soap bubble expands, the radius will increases and inside pressure will decrease.\n- A liquid does not wet the solid surface if the angle of contact is obtuse i.e., greater than $90^{\\circ}$. In this case cohesive forces will be greater than adhesive forces and so, the liquid does not wet the surfaces of solid.\n- The height of water rise in a capillary tube is, $$ \\begin{aligned}&h=\\frac{2\\mathrm{T}\\cos\\theta}{r\\rho g}\\\\ &\\begin{aligned}\\\\ &\\Rightarrow&h&\\propto\\frac{1}{r}\\\\&\\Rightarrow&\\frac{h_{1}}{h_{2}}&=\\frac{r_{2}}{r_{1}}=\\frac{2r}{r}=2\\\\&\\text{As}&m&=\\mathrm{A.h}.\\rho\\\\&&\\frac{m_{2}}{m_{1}}&=\\frac{\\mathrm{Ah}_{2}\\rho}{\\mathrm{Ah}_{1}\\rho}=\\frac{h_{2}}{h_{1}}\\\\&&&=\\frac{1}{2}\\\\&\\Rightarrow&m_{2}&=\\frac{m_{1}}{2}=\\frac{5}{2}\\\\&&&=2.5\\mathrm{~g}\\\\ &\\end{aligned}\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- Excess Pressure = $ \\frac{4T}{R} $, $$ \\begin{aligned}Gauge~Pressure&=\\rho gZ_{o}\\\\\\therefore\\quad P_{0}+&\\quad\\frac{4T}{R}=P_{0}+\\rho gZ_{o}\\\\\\Rightarrow\\quad Z_{0}&=\\frac{4T}{R\\times\\rho g}\\\\\\Rightarrow\\quad Z_{0}&=\\frac{4\\times2.5\\times10^{-2}}{10^{-3}\\times1000\\times10}m\\\\\\therefore\\quad Z_{0}&=1cm\\end{aligned} $$\n- Change in surface area, $$ \\begin{array}{c}\\Delta A=(5\\times4-4\\times2)\\times2\\\\\\left\\{film has two surface\\right\\}\\\\=24\\ cm^{2}=24\\times10^{-4}\\ m^{2}\\\\\\therefore\\quad Work~done=T.\\ \\Delta A\\\\3\\times10^{-4}=T\\times24\\times10^{-4}\\\\\\mathrm{T}=\\frac{3\\times10^{-4}}{24\\times10^{-4}}=0.125\\mathrm{~N/m}\\end{array} $$\n- From surface tension, height of capillary, $$ h=\\frac{2T\\cos\\theta}{r\\rho g} $$ From above equation. $$ \\frac{\\cos\\theta_{1}}{\\rho_{1}}=\\frac{\\cos\\theta_{2}}{\\rho_{2}}=\\frac{\\cos\\theta_{3}}{\\rho_{3}} $$ Thus, $ \\cos\\theta\\propto\\rho $ $$ \\rho_{1}>\\rho_{2}>\\rho_{3} $$ $$ \\theta_{1}>\\cos\\theta_{2}>\\cos\\theta_{3} $$ $$ 0\\leq\\theta_{1}\\leq\\theta_{2}\\leq\\theta_{3}<\\frac{\\pi}{2} $$\n- Since, the length of the capillary tube above the surface of the water is less than 'h', the water does not have enough space to over flow like a fountain. Instead, it stays at the top of the tube without overflowing.\n- We know that, Change in Surface Energy, $ \\Delta E = T\\Delta A $ where, $$ \\Delta A=Change~in~Surface~Area $$ $$ \\mathrm{T}=\\mathrm{Surface~Tension} $$ $$ \\Delta\\mathbf{A}=\\mathbf{A}_{f}-\\mathbf{A}_{i}=4\\pi\\mathbf{R}^{2}-n(4\\pi\\mathbf{r}^{2}) $$ Given, $ n \\times \\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^{3} = \\frac{4}{3} \\pi R^{3} = V $ $$ \\Rightarrow\\quad n(4\\pi r^{3})=4\\pi\\mathrm{R}^{3}=3\\mathrm{V} $$ Now, $$ \\Delta A=\\frac{4\\pi R^{3}}{R}-\\frac{n(4\\pi r^{3})}{r}=\\frac{3V}{R}-\\frac{3V}{r} $$ $$ \\therefore\\Delta E=T\\Delta A=T\\left(\\frac{3V}{R}-\\frac{3V}{r}\\right)=3VT\\left(\\frac{1}{R}-\\frac{1}{r}\\right) $$ $$ R>r $$ Therefore, energy is released.\n- The wettability of a surface by a liquid depends primarily on angle of contact between the surface and the liquid.",
