"id": "note-mechanical-properties-of-fluids-viscosity",
"chapter": "Mechanical Properties of Fluids",
"subtopic": "Viscosity",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-properties",
"unitLabel": "Units VI & VII — Properties of Bulk Matter",
"order": 8,
"title": "Viscosity",
"summary": "When we drop a ball in liquid that is highly viscous in nature and when it falls then initially gravitational force acts.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- When we drop a ball in liquid that is highly viscous in nature and when it falls then initially gravitational force acts. As it goes inside liquid then viscous force increases no its speed will be constant with time, after sometimes gravitational force is balanced by drag or viscous force. When gravitational force is balanced by drag force then the acceleration of particle which can be measured by the slope of v and t graph initially becomes negative but after some time it becomes zero which means velocity becomes constant with time. The v - t graph can be shown by, <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//7fd99a06-011a-431b-8b12-608a6e715545/markdown_3/imgs/img_in_chart_box_192_389_391_500.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A36Z%2F-1%2F%2Fdf86a4f7f65d43113fa2224e652c65ad44567fa0d208d9ccc4b727f90695c561\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"16%\" /></div> It shows motion as the graph B.\n- Given. Mass of ball = M Density of ball = d Density of glycerine = $ \\frac{d}{2} $ $$ \\begin{array}{c}\\uparrow\\\\ F_{\\mathrm{v}}\\\\\\downarrow\\\\ Mg\\end{array}\\stackrel{\\uparrow}{\\uparrow}\\stackrel{F_{\\mathrm{B}}}{\\downarrow} $$ $$ \\mathrm{F}_{\\mathbf{V}}+\\mathrm{F}_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\mathrm{M}\\mathrm{g} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}F_{B}&=\\frac{4}{3}\\pi R^{3}dg\\\\&=\\mathbf{V}g\\ dg\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{v}}=\\frac{\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf{g}}{2} $$\n- Terminal velocity of ball in viscous fluid is, $$v_{T} = \\frac{2}{9\\eta} \\, r^{2}g \\, (\\sigma - \\rho)$$ Where, $$\\eta = \\text{coeff. of viscosity of medium}$$ $$r = \\text{radius of ball}$$ $$\\sigma = \\text{density of ball}$$ $$\\rho = \\text{density of viscous medium}$$ From the formula. $$ \\mathbf{v}_{\\mathrm{T}}\\approx r^{2}\\left(\\boldsymbol{\\sigma}-\\boldsymbol{\\rho}\\right) $$ From this formula $ \\therefore \\frac{\\text{Terminal velocity of } I^{\\text{st}} \\text{ ball}}{\\text{Terminal velocity of } II^{\\text{nd}} \\text{ ball}} = \\frac{v_{1}}{v_{2}} $ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{\\mathbf{v}_{1}}{\\mathbf{v}_{2}}&=\\frac{1^{2}}{2^{2}}\\frac{(8\\rho_{2}-0.1\\rho_{2})}{(\\rho_{2}-0.1\\rho_{2})}\\\\&=\\frac{1}{4}\\times\\frac{7.9}{0.9}=\\frac{79}{36}\\end{aligned} $$\n- If, P = Viscous force $ v_{T} $ = terminal velocity $$ \\mathrm{F}=6\\pi r\\eta\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{T}} $$ $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\frac{d Q}{d t}=6\\pi\\eta r v_T\\times v_T\\\\ =6\\pi\\eta r v_T^2\\end{array} $$ We also know that terminal velocity, $$ \\begin{aligned}&V_{T}=\\frac{2}{9}\\frac{r^{2}(\\rho-\\sigma)}{\\eta}g\\\\&V_{T}\\propto r^{2}\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$ ⇄ From (i) and (iii), we get $$ \\frac{dQ}{dt}\\propto r.(r^{2})^{2} $$ $$ \\mathrm{\\frac{dQ}{dt}}\\propto r^{5} $$",
