"title": "Change of State",
"summary": "Heat required by 1 g ice at $ 0^{\\circ} $C to melt into 1 g water at $ 0^{\\circ} $C, $$ Q_{1}=mL $$ (L = latent heat of fusion) $$ =1\\times80=80cal(L=80cal/g) $$ Heat required by 1 g of water at $ 0^{\\circ} $C to boil…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Given that: $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\frac{1}{4}mgh=mL\\\\h=\\frac{4L}{g}=\\frac{4\\times3.4\\times10^{5}}{10}\\\\=136\\mathrm{~km}\\end{array} $$\n- Heat required by 1 g ice at $ 0^{\\circ} $C to melt into 1 g water at $ 0^{\\circ} $C, $$ Q_{1}=mL $$ (L = latent heat of fusion) $$ =1\\times80=80cal(L=80cal/g) $$ Heat required by 1 g of water at $ 0^{\\circ} $C to boil at $ 100^{\\circ} $C, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{Q}_{2}&=m c\\Delta\\mathrm{T}\\\\&=\\mathrm{1}\\times\\mathrm{1}(100-0)\\\\&=100\\mathrm{cal}\\end{aligned}\\quad\\begin{aligned}(c&=\\text{specific heat of water)}\\ $ c=1\\mathrm{cal}/\\mathrm{g}\\mathrm{℃}\\end{aligned} $$ Thus, total heat required by 1 g of ice to reach a temperature of $ 100^{\\circ} $C, $$ \\mathrm{Q}=\\mathrm{Q}_{1}+\\mathrm{Q}_{2}=80+100=180\\mathrm{cal} $$ Heat available with 1 g of steam to condense into 1 g of water at $ 100^{\\circ} $C, $$ \\begin{aligned}Q^{\\prime}&=mL^{\\prime}\\\\&\\quad(L^{\\prime}=latent~heat~of~vaporisation)\\\\&=1\\times536~cal\\quad(L^{\\prime}=536~cal/g)\\\\&=536~cal\\end{aligned} $$ Obviously, the whole steam will not be condensed and ice will attain temperature of $ 100^{\\circ} $C. Thus, the temperature of mixture is $ 100^{\\circ} $C.",
