"title": "Measurement Of Temperature",
"summary": "A mercury thermometer is a liquid thermometer that uses the homogeneous variation in volume of a liquid as a temperature.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- A mercury thermometer is a liquid thermometer that uses the homogeneous variation in volume of a liquid as a temperature. Mercury is opaque and bright, making it easy to see in the glass tube, and it is a good heat conductor, soon reaching the temperature of the hot bath. A mercury thermometer can be used to measure temperatures up to $ 357^{\\circ} $C because mercury begins to evaporate at $ 367^{\\circ} $C.\n- Relation between Celsius scale and Fahrenheit scale is, $$ \\frac{C}{100^{\\circ}}=\\frac{F-32^{\\circ}}{180^{\\circ}} $$ Putting value of F = 140°, we get $$ \\frac{C}{100^{\\circ}}=\\frac{140^{\\circ}-32^{\\circ}}{180^{\\circ}}=0.6 $$ $$ C=60^{\\circ} $$ Hence, Fall in temperature = Temperature of boiling water - final temperature $$ 100^{\\circ}C-60^{\\circ}C=40^{\\circ}C $$",
