"id": "note-thermal-properties-of-matter-specific-heat-capacity",
"chapter": "Thermal Properties of Matter",
"subtopic": "Specific Heat Capacity",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-properties",
"unitLabel": "Units VI & VII — Properties of Bulk Matter",
"order": 9,
"title": "Specific Heat Capacity",
"summary": "Heat required $ Q = mc\\Delta T $ $$ =\\left(\\frac{4}{3}\\pi r^{3}.\\rho\\right)c\\Delta\\mathrm{T} $$ Since, $ \\pi,\\rho,c,\\Delta T $ are constant.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Heat required $ Q = mc\\Delta T $ $$ =\\left(\\frac{4}{3}\\pi r^{3}.\\rho\\right)c\\Delta\\mathrm{T} $$ Since, $ \\pi,\\rho,c,\\Delta T $ are constant. $$ Q\\propto r^{3} $$ or, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{Q_{1}}{Q_{2}}&=\\frac{r_{1}^{3}}{r_{2}^{3}}=\\left(\\frac{r_{1}}{r_{2}}\\right)^{3}=\\left(\\frac{1.5r_{2}}{r_{2}}\\right)^{3}\\\\&=\\frac{27}{8}\\end{aligned} $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//73c546d1-790e-4d6c-8d37-a3a37f18cd3b/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_575_1256_614_1304.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A34Z%2F-1%2F%2Fdc4f47f188524fb1eccf184408dbd169a962abe0573900be7390de19162ae5eb\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"3%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory Specific heat is the amount of heat needed to raise the temperature of 1 kg of a material by $ 1^{\\circ} $C.\n- Thermal capacity of a body is defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of the (whole) body through $ 1^{\\circ} $C or 1 K. Amount of heat energy required ( $ \\Delta Q $) to raise the temperature of mass m of a body through temperature range ( $ \\Delta T $) is, $$ \\Delta\\mathbf{Q}=m s(\\Delta\\mathbf{T}) $$ where, $s$ is specific heat of the body, when, $\\Delta T = 1\\ K$, $\\Delta Q = \\text{thermal capacity}$ $\\therefore$ $\\text{Thermal capacity} = s \\times m \\times 1 = ms$ Here, $m = 40\\ g$, $s = 0.2\\ \\text{cal/g K}$ $\\therefore$ $\\text{Thermal capacity} = 40 \\times 0.2 = 8\\ \\text{cal/K}$ $= 4.2 \\times 8\\ \\text{J/K} = 33.6\\ \\text{J/K}$",
