"id": "note-thermal-properties-of-matter-thermal-expansion",
"chapter": "Thermal Properties of Matter",
"subtopic": "Thermal Expansion",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-properties",
"unitLabel": "Units VI & VII — Properties of Bulk Matter",
"order": 9,
"title": "Thermal Expansion",
"summary": "The value of coefficient of volume expansion of glycerin is, $ 5 \\times 10^{-4} \\text{K}^{-1} $ We know that, $ d_{f} = \\frac{d_{i}}{(1 + \\mathrm{V} \\Delta \\mathrm{T})} $ Fractional change, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\Delta…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- According to question, $$ L_{w}=l_{w}(1+\\alpha_{w}\\Delta T) $$ $$ L_{cu}=l_{cu}(1+\\alpha_{cu}\\Delta T) $$ $$ \\mathrm{L}_{\\mathrm{Al}}=\\mathrm{l}_{\\mathrm{Al}}(1+\\alpha_{\\mathrm{Al}}\\Delta\\mathrm{T}) $$ From eq. (ii) and eq. (iii), $$ \\mathrm{L}_{\\mathrm{A}l}-\\mathrm{L}_{\\mathrm{C}u}=l_{\\mathrm{A}l}\\left(1+\\alpha_{\\mathrm{A}l}\\Delta\\mathrm{T}\\right)-l_{\\mathrm{C}u}\\left(1+\\alpha_{\\mathrm{C}u}\\Delta\\mathrm{T}\\right) $$ Since, $$ l_{Al}\\alpha_{Al}=l_{Cu}\\alpha_{Cu} $$ ∴ $$ \\begin{array}{l}l_{\\mathrm{Al}}=\\frac{l_{\\mathrm{Cu}}\\alpha_{\\mathrm{Cu}}}{\\alpha_{\\mathrm{Al}}}\\\\ {\\quad}=\\frac{88\\times1.7\\times10^{-5}}{2.2\\times10^{-5}}=68\\mathrm{~cm}}\\end{array} $$ $$ l_{\\mathrm{A l}}=68\\mathrm{c m} $$\n- Change in length for both rods should be same, $$ \\Delta I_{1}=\\Delta I_{2} $$ $$ l_{1}\\alpha_{1}\\Delta T=l_{2}\\alpha_{2}\\Delta T $$ $$ \\Rightarrow\\quad l_{1}\\alpha_{1}=l_{2}\\alpha_{2} $$\n- The value of coefficient of volume expansion of glycerin is, $ 5 \\times 10^{-4} \\text{K}^{-1} $ We know that, $ d_{f} = \\frac{d_{i}}{(1 + \\mathrm{V} \\Delta \\mathrm{T})} $ Fractional change, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\Delta d&=\\frac{d_{i}-d_{f}}{d_{f}}=1-\\frac{d_{f}}{d_{i}}\\\\&=1-(1+\\mathrm{V}\\Delta\\mathrm{T})^{-1}=1-(1-\\mathrm{V}\\Delta\\mathrm{T})\\\\&\\quad\\{(1+x)^{n}\\approx1+nx\\}\\\\&=\\mathrm{V}\\Delta\\mathrm{T}=5\\times10^{-4}\\times40=0.020\\end{aligned} $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//73c546d1-790e-4d6c-8d37-a3a37f18cd3b/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_0_953_23_1001.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A34Z%2F-1%2F%2F84412caf377bdfbb9bb99d8d0c0ecf2930fd98ea02f51c0c6f86ab40ab3d3b45\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"1%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory The increase in volume of a solid when heated is known as volume expansion. The change of a solid with a change in temperature $t$ is given by: $\\Delta V = V_y \\Delta t$, where, $y$ is the coefficient expansion.\n- According to the question, $$ T_{1}=20^{\\circ}C,T_{2}=40^{\\circ}C $$ $$ \\rho_{20}=998\\mathrm{~k g/m^{3}},\\rho_{40}=992\\mathrm{~k g/m^{3}} $$ So, $$ \\rho_{\\mathrm{T}_{2}}=\\frac{\\rho_{\\mathrm{T}_{1}}}{(1+\\gamma\\Delta\\mathrm{T})}=\\frac{\\rho_{\\mathrm{T}_{1}}}{1+\\gamma(\\mathrm{T}_{2}-\\mathrm{T}_{1})} $$ Putting the values we get, $$ 992=\\frac{998}{1+\\gamma(40-20)} $$ $$ 992=\\frac{998}{1+20\\gamma} $$ $$ \\Rightarrow\\ 992\\ (1+20\\gamma)=998 $$ $$ \\Rightarrow\\quad1+20\\gamma=\\frac{998}{992} $$ ↓ $$ 20y=\\frac{6}{992} $$ $ \\Rightarrow $ $$ \\gamma=\\frac{6}{992}\\times\\frac{1}{20}=3\\times10^{-4}\\text{^\\circ}C^{-1} $$",
