"id": "note-thermodynamics-first-law-of-thermodynamics",
"chapter": "Thermodynamics",
"subtopic": "First Law of Thermodynamics",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-thermo",
"unitLabel": "Unit VIII — Thermodynamics",
"order": 10,
"title": "First Law of Thermodynamics",
"summary": "From the question.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- From the question. Heat spent during the conversion of sample of water at $ 100^{\\circ} $C to steam is, $$ \\Delta\\mathrm{Q}=54\\mathrm{~cal}=54\\times4.18\\mathrm{~J}=225.72\\mathrm{~J} $$ $$ \\mathrm{P}=1.013\\times10^{5}\\mathrm{N m}^{-2} $$ $\\therefore$ Work done, $\\Delta W = P\\Delta V = P[V_{\\text{steam}} - V_{\\text{water}}]$ Here, $$ V_{steam}=167.1\\ cc=167.1\\times10^{-6}\\ m^{3} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{water}}&=0.1\\mathrm{~g}=0.1\\mathrm{~cc}=0.1\\times10^{-6}\\mathrm{~m}^{3}\\\\\\Delta\\mathrm{W}&=1.013\\times10^{5}[(167.1-0.1)\\times10^{-6}]\\\\&=1.013\\times167\\times10^{-1}=16.917\\mathrm{~J}\\end{aligned} $$ We also know that, $$\\Delta Q = \\Delta U + \\Delta W$$ $$\\Delta U = \\Delta Q - \\Delta W = 225.72 - 16.917 = 208.803\\ \\text{J}$$ $$\\approx 208.7\\ \\text{J}$$\n- Using first law of thermodynamics, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\Delta U&=\\Delta Q-\\Delta W\\\\&=2\\times4.2\\times1000-500\\\\&=(8400-500)J=7900J\\end{aligned} $$\n- From first law of thermodynamics, $\\Delta Q = \\Delta U + \\Delta W$ where, $\\Delta Q$ = heat given $\\Delta U$ = change in internal energy $\\Delta W$ = work done Here, $\\Delta Q = 110\\ J$ $\\Delta U = 40\\ J$ $\\therefore \\quad \\Delta W = \\Delta Q - \\Delta U$ = 110 - 40 = 70 J\n- According to the first law of thermodynamics, when some amount of heat ($dQ$) is supplied to a system capable of doing external work, the amount of heat absorbed by the system ($dQ$) is equal to the sum of the increase in the internal energy of the system ($dU$) due to temperature rise and the external work done by the system ($dW$) during expansion, $$ i.e.,\\quad d Q=d U+d W $$ This law is basically the law of conservation of energy applied to every the rmodynamic process in nature.",
