"id": "note-thermodynamics-objective-i",
"chapter": "Thermodynamics",
"subtopic": "Objective I",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-thermo",
"unitLabel": "Unit VIII — Thermodynamics",
"order": 10,
"title": "Objective I",
"summary": "The **Kelvin–Planck statement**: *It is impossible to construct a device that, operating in a cycle, produces no other effect than the absorption of heat from a single reservoir and the performance of an equivalent…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- The first law of thermodynamics, $\\Delta U = \\Delta Q - W$, expresses that the change in internal energy equals the heat added minus the work done by the system. This is simply the **law of conservation of energy** applied to a thermodynamic system — energy cannot be created or destroyed, only converted between heat, work, and internal energy. Answer: (B).\n- First law: $\\Delta Q = \\Delta U + W$. With $\\Delta Q = 0$: $$\\Delta U = -W$$ If the gas expands (does positive work $W > 0$), internal energy decreases ($\\Delta U < 0$), so temperature falls. If compressed ($W < 0$), internal energy increases and temperature rises. Neither $\\Delta U$ nor $W$ is zero in general; temperature is not constant (that would be isothermal). Answer: (C).\n- For an isothermal process ($T =$ const), $P = nRT/V$. Work done by the gas: $$W = \\int_{V_1}^{V_2} P\\,dV = \\int_{V_1}^{V_2} \\frac{nRT}{V}\\,dV = nRT\\ln\\frac{V_2}{V_1}$$ For expansion $V_2 > V_1$, $\\ln(V_2/V_1) > 0$, so $W > 0$ (gas does positive work). Answer: (A).\n- For an **ideal gas**, the internal energy $U$ depends only on temperature. Therefore: $$\\Delta U = nC_V\\,\\Delta T$$ $\\Delta U = 0$ if and only if $\\Delta T = 0$, i.e., the process is **isothermal** (constant temperature). In an adiabatic process $T$ changes; in isobaric and isochoric processes $T$ generally changes too. Answer: (C).\n- The Carnot efficiency is derived from the ratio of heat rejected to heat absorbed: $$\\eta = 1 - \\frac{Q_C}{Q_H} = 1 - \\frac{T_C}{T_H} = \\frac{T_H - T_C}{T_H}$$ All temperatures are **absolute** (Kelvin). Since $T_C < T_H$, $\\eta < 1$ — no heat engine can be 100% efficient (second law). Answer: (B).\n- The **Kelvin–Planck statement**: *It is impossible to construct a device that, operating in a cycle, produces no other effect than the absorption of heat from a single reservoir and the performance of an equivalent amount of work.* In other words, no heat engine operating in a cycle can have 100% efficiency — some heat must always be rejected to a cold reservoir. Option A describes the Clausius statement (equivalent but different in form). Option C is incorrect (entropy increases or stays the same). Option D is false. Answer: (B).\n- $T_H = 227°C = 500\\,K$, $\\quad T_C = 27°C = 300\\,K$. $$\\eta = 1 - \\frac{T_C}{T_H} = 1 - \\frac{300}{500} = \\frac{200}{500} = 0.40 = 40\\%$$ Answer: (A).\n- **Internal energy** $U$ is a **state function** — it depends only on the thermodynamic state (temperature, pressure, volume), not on the path. In a **cyclic process**, the system returns to its initial state, so the final and initial states are identical. Therefore: $$\\Delta U_{\\text{cycle}} = U_{\\text{final}} - U_{\\text{initial}} = 0$$ By the first law: $\\Delta Q_{\\rm net} = W_{\\rm net}$ for a cyclic process. Answer: (C).",
