"id": "note-thermodynamics-objective-ii",
"chapter": "Thermodynamics",
"subtopic": "Objective II",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-thermo",
"unitLabel": "Unit VIII — Thermodynamics",
"order": 10,
"title": "Objective II",
"summary": "- **A** ✓: $S$ depends only on the thermodynamic state; $dS = \\delta Q_{\\rm rev}/T$ is an exact differential.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- A process is **irreversible** if it cannot be reversed without leaving any change in the universe (entropy increases). - **A** ✓: Free expansion is spontaneous and highly irreversible — gas expands into vacuum without doing work; cannot spontaneously re-compress. - **B** ✗: A quasi-static isothermal expansion (infinitely slow, in equilibrium at each step) is **reversible** — the ideal limiting case. - **C** ✓: Spontaneous heat flow from hot to cold is irreversible (second law). - **D** ✗: A Carnot cycle is the ideal **reversible** cycle. Answer: (A), (C).\n- In an adiabatic expansion: $\\Delta Q = 0$, volume increases, $W > 0$ (gas does work). First law: $\\Delta U = \\Delta Q - W = 0 - W = -W < 0$ (internal energy decreases). For an ideal gas, $\\Delta U = nC_V\\Delta T$ → $\\Delta T < 0$ (temperature drops). - **A** ✓: Temperature decreases. - **B** ✓: Internal energy decreases. - **C** ✓: Work done by gas is positive (expansion). - **D** ✗: No heat exchange ($\\Delta Q = 0$) — adiabatic means thermally insulated. Answer: (A), (B), (C).\n- - **A** ✓: $S$ depends only on the thermodynamic state; $dS = \\delta Q_{\\rm rev}/T$ is an exact differential. - **B** ✓: Second law: $\\Delta S_{\\rm universe} \\geq 0$, with equality only for reversible processes. Natural processes are irreversible, so $\\Delta S_{\\rm universe} > 0$. - **C** ✓: For a reversible process, $\\Delta S_{\\rm system} + \\Delta S_{\\rm surroundings} = 0$ — entropy gained by one = entropy lost by the other. - **D** ✗: In an **isolated** system, entropy **cannot decrease** ($\\Delta S \\geq 0$). This is the second law. Answer: (A), (B), (C).\n- - **A** ✓: On a $P$–$V$ diagram, $W = \\oint P\\,dV$ = area enclosed (positive if traversed clockwise). - **B** ✓: $\\Delta U = 0$ for a cycle, so by first law: $Q_{\\rm net} = W_{\\rm net}$. - **C** ✓: $U$ is a state function; complete cycle → $\\Delta U = 0$. - **D** ✗: A cycle can be irreversible (e.g., a cycle involving free expansion or friction). The Carnot cycle is the ideal reversible cycle, but general cycles are not required to be reversible. Answer: (A), (B), (C).",
