"id": "note-thermodynamics-specific-heat-capacity",
"chapter": "Thermodynamics",
"subtopic": "Specific Heat Capacity",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-thermo",
"unitLabel": "Unit VIII — Thermodynamics",
"order": 10,
"title": "Specific Heat Capacity",
"summary": "<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//ce6d776a-19c4-4d06-9191-67ae8ca469ae/markdown_4/imgs/img_in_image_box_740_935_1025_1115.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A28Z%2F-1%2F%2F8b51d2b260c68e3d154f9138253335967c2b749d7b662d9458df600a0f2b91e9\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"23%\" /></div> We know, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\Delta\\mathrm{U}&=n\\mathrm{C}_{\\mathrm{V}}\\Delta\\mathrm{T}\\\\&=n\\left(\\frac{5\\mathrm{R}}{2}\\right)\\left(\\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{B}}-\\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{A}}\\right)\\quad\\left[for diatomic gas,\\mathrm{C}_{\\mathrm{V}}=\\frac{5\\mathrm{R}}{2}\\right]\\\\&=\\frac{5n\\mathrm{R}}{2}\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{B}}\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{B}}}{n\\mathrm{R}}-\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{A}}\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{A}}}{n\\mathrm{R}}\\right)\\quad[\\because\\mathrm{PV}=n\\mathrm{RT}]\\\\&=\\frac{5}{2}\\left(\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{B}}\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{B}}-\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{A}}\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{A}}\\right)=\\frac{5}{2}\\left(2\\times10^{3}\\times6-5\\times10^{3}\\times4\\right)\\\\&=\\frac{5}{2}\\left(-8\\times10^{3}\\right)=-20\\mathrm{kJ}\\end{aligned} $$\n- Let $C_{V}$ and $C_{P}$ be molar specific heats of the ideal gas at constant volume and constant pressure, respectively, then $$ \\mathrm{C}_{\\mathrm{p}}=\\mathrm{MC}_{\\mathrm{p}}and\\mathrm{C}_{\\mathrm{V}}=\\mathrm{MC}_{\\mathrm{V}} $$ $$ \\mathbf{C}_{\\mathbf{P}}-\\mathbf{C}_{\\mathbf{V}}=\\mathbf{R} $$ from equation (i) and (ii), we get, $$ \\therefore\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf{C}_{\\mathrm{P}}-\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf{C}_{\\mathrm{V}}=\\mathbf{R} $$ $$ \\Rightarrow\\quad\\mathbf{C_{P}}-\\mathbf{C_{V}}=\\frac{\\mathbf{R}}{\\mathbf{M}} $$\n- Change in internal energy of a gas having atomicity $ \\gamma $ is given by, $$ \\Delta\\mathrm{U}=\\frac{1}{(\\gamma-1)}\\left(\\mathrm{P}_{2}\\mathrm{V}_{2}-\\mathrm{P}_{1}\\mathrm{V}_{1}\\right) $$ Given. $$ \\mathbf{V}_{1}=\\mathbf{V}_{1},\\mathbf{V}_{2}=2\\mathbf{V} $$ So. $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\Delta\\mathrm{U}=\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{\\gamma-1}\\left[\\mathrm{P}\\times2\\mathrm{V}-\\mathrm{P}\\times\\mathrm{V}\\right]\\\\ \\quad=\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{\\gamma-1}\\mathrm{P}\\mathrm{V}=\\frac{\\mathrm{P}\\mathrm{V}}{\\gamma-1}\\end{array} $$\n- Here, we know that, At constant pressure $$ \\mathbf{Q}=n\\mathbf{C}_{\\mathbf{P}}\\Delta\\mathbf{T} $$ $$ 207=C_{P}\\times10 $$ $$ \\mathrm{C_{p}=20.7} $$ At constant volume, W = 0 $$ \\mathbf{Q}=\\mathbf{U}=n\\mathbf{C}_{\\mathrm{v}}\\Delta\\mathbf{T} $$ $$ \\mathbf{C}_{\\mathbf{P}}=\\mathbf{C}_{\\mathbf{v}}+\\mathbf{R} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}&\\Rightarrow\\quad\\mathbf{C}_{\\mathbf{v}}=20.7-8.3=12.4\\\\&\\Rightarrow\\quad\\mathbf{Q}=12.4\\times10=124\\mathbf{J}\\end{aligned} $$",
