"id": "note-thermodynamics-thermodynamic-state-variables-and-equation-of-state",
"chapter": "Thermodynamics",
"subtopic": "Thermodynamic State Variables and Equation of State",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-thermo",
"unitLabel": "Unit VIII — Thermodynamics",
"order": 10,
"title": "Thermodynamic State Variables and Equation of State",
"summary": "Certain specific thermodynamic variables, such as pressure P, volume V, temperature T and entropy S, can be used to describe the thermodynamic state of a homogeneous system.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- The equilibrium state of a thermodynamic system is described by pressure, temperature and volume only.\n- Given: P = 249 kPa; T = 27°C, M = 2 × 10^{-3}kg Equation of state, $$ \\mathbf{P}\\mathbf{V}=n\\mathbf{R}\\mathbf{T} $$ or $$ \\mathbf{P}\\mathbf{M}=\\boldsymbol{\\rho}\\mathbf{R}\\mathbf{T} $$ $$ \\left[\\because n=\\frac{m}{M}\\right] $$ or $$ \\rho=\\frac{\\mathrm{P M}}{\\mathrm{R T}} $$ $$ \\rho=\\frac{(249\\times10^{3})(2\\times10^{-3})}{8.3\\times300}=0.2\\ kg/m^{3} $$\n- Certain specific thermodynamic variables, such as pressure P, volume V, temperature T and entropy S, can be used to describe the thermodynamic state of a homogeneous system. Any two of these four variables are independent and once they are known, the others can be calculated. As a result, there are just two independent variables, with the others working as functions. Certain relationships are essential for a thorough understanding of the system and we introduce some thermodynamic functions, which are functions of variables P, V, T and S. Thermodynamic functions are classified into four categories. (i) Internal energy (U) (ii) Helmholtz function (F) (iii) Enthalpy (H) (iv) Gibb's energy (G) Hence, work done is not thermodynamic function. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//42c2a837-382d-4536-a07b-52818c81510a/markdown_0/imgs/img_in_image_box_605_355_648_406.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A45Z%2F-1%2F%2F7966dca4360bc6878ffdcb24da30166e1c33f215651b6d889a80797efdd4bd8d\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"3%\" /></div> ##### Mnemonics: Gibbs's free energy formula: \"Good Honey Tastes Sweet\" $$ \\Delta\\pmb{G}=\\pmb{H}-\\pmb{T}\\Delta\\pmb{S} $$",
