"id": "note-kinetic-theory-behaviour-of-gases",
"chapter": "Kinetic Theory",
"subtopic": "Behaviour of Gases",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-kinetic",
"unitLabel": "Unit IX — Behaviour of Perfect Gas",
"order": 11,
"title": "Behaviour of Gases",
"summary": "At STP, T = 273 K, P = 10^{5} N/m^{2} Number of moles of water, $ n = \\frac{\\text{mass of water}}{\\text{molecular weight of water}} $ $ =\\frac{4.5}{1.8\\times10^{-2}}=250 $ Using equation, PV = nRT $ \\Rightarrow $ $…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- According to Charlie's law $ V \\propto T $ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//6b55f64b-cbb3-478c-9297-acf5673aa92a/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_253_877_403_1033.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A23Z%2F-1%2F%2F96f69f2b33343cebc1258df183f831c27b577c3847283cab6ee744ea809edba7\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"12%\" /></div> $$ \\therefore\\mathbf{P}_{1}>\\mathbf{P}_{2}>\\mathbf{P}_{3} $$\n- At STP, T = 273 K, P = 10^{5} N/m^{2} Number of moles of water, $ n = \\frac{\\text{mass of water}}{\\text{molecular weight of water}} $ $ =\\frac{4.5}{1.8\\times10^{-2}}=250 $ Using equation, PV = nRT $ \\Rightarrow $ $ \\frac{nRT}{P}=\\frac{250\\times8.3\\times273}{10^{5}} $ = 5.6 m³ B) If, m = mass of gas V = Volume of gas ∴ Pressure. $$ \\rho=\\mathrm{\\frac{m}{V}}=Density~of~gas $$ $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{P}=\\frac{1}{3}\\rho V_{\\mathrm{rms}}^{2}\\\\ \\\\ =\\frac{1}{3}\\rho\\frac{3RT}{\\mathrm{M}_{0}}\\\\ \\\\ =\\frac{\\rho RT}{\\mathrm{M}_{0}}\\end{array} $$ $$ \\rho=\\frac{\\mathrm{P M}_{0}}{\\mathrm{R T}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{P}m\\mathrm{N}_{\\mathrm{A}}}{\\mathrm{K N}_{\\mathrm{A}}\\mathrm{T}} $$ $$ \\rho=\\frac{\\mathrm{P}m}{\\mathrm{KT}} $$\n- As we know, $$ \\mathbf{P}\\mathbf{V}=n\\mathbf{R}\\mathbf{T} $$ $$ \\frac{\\mathbf{V}}{\\mathbf{T}}=\\frac{n\\mathbf{R}}{\\mathbf{P}} $$ The slope of the graph $\\propto\\frac{1}{P}$. So, it is evident from the graph that $P_{2}$ will be smaller as compared to $P_{1}$.\n- Using equation, $$ \\mathbf{P}\\mathbf{V}=n\\mathbf{R}\\mathbf{T} $$ or $$ \\frac{\\mathbf{P V}}{\\mathbf{M}}=\\frac{1}{\\mathbf{M}_{0}}\\mathbf{R T} $$ or $$ \\frac{\\mathbf{P}}{\\rho}=\\frac{\\mathbf{R}\\mathbf{T}}{\\mathbf{M}_{0}} $$ $$ x=\\frac{\\rho}{\\mathrm{P}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{M}}{\\mathrm{RT}} $$ $$ \\mathrm{\\frac{\\rho}{p}}\\propto\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{T}} $$ So. $$ \\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}=\\frac{T_{1}}{T_{2}}=\\frac{273+10}{273+110}=\\frac{283}{383} $$ or $$ x_{2}=\\frac{283}{383}x_{1} $$\n- We know that. $$ PV=nRT $$ $$ n=\\frac{m}{molecular mass}=\\frac{5}{32} $$ $$ \\mathbf{PV}=\\left(\\frac{5}{32}\\right)\\mathbf{RT} $$\n- According to Dalton's law of partial pressure, the total pressure exerted by a mixture of gases that do not interact with each other is equal to the sum of the partial pressures that each would impose, if alone occupied the same volume at the given temperature. When various gases are combined in one container, the mixture's pressure P will be; $$ \\mathbf{P}=\\mathbf{P}_{1}+\\mathbf{P}_{2}+\\mathbf{P}_{3} $$",
