"order": 11,
"title": "Mean Free Path",
"summary": "The average velocity of the gas molecules increases as the temperature rises.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- The mean free path \\lambda for a gas, with molecular diameter d and number density n can be expressed as, $ \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2nnd^{2}}} $\n- $ \\because $ Mean free path, $ \\lambda = \\frac{1}{\\pi nr^2} $ $ \\therefore $ $ \\lambda \\propto \\frac{1}{r^2} $ ##### Related Theory The mean free path is the average distance, that a molecule can travel without colliding, after which its direction or energy gets modified.\n- The average velocity of the gas molecules increases as the temperature rises. As a result, more molecules collide with the walls. Hence, number of collisions per unit time will increase. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//b20e71bf-57fc-449f-9bbb-d84bd788c31c/markdown_3/imgs/img_in_image_box_634_142_672_186.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A47Z%2F-1%2F%2Fed5d318bc7acb084441b8f080ac7c1f43a47b4f0d0393d8be33aae8690215de6\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"3%\" /></div>",
