"title": "How simple harmonic motion is defined",
"summary": "SHM is oscillation in which the displacement varies sinusoidally with time, x = A sin(ωt+φ); its defining feature is acceleration proportional and opposite to displacement.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $x=A\\sin(\\omega t+\\phi)$ (or a cosine), where $A$ is the amplitude, $\\omega$ the angular frequency and $\\phi$ the phase constant.\n- $\\omega=\\dfrac{2\\pi}{T}=2\\pi f$, and period $T=\\dfrac{2\\pi}{\\omega}$.\n**Exam traps**\n- SHM is both periodic and oscillatory; the phase constant fixes the starting point.\n- All periodic motion is not SHM — only that with a linear restoring force.",
