"id": "note-waves-reflection-of-waves",
"chapter": "Waves",
"subtopic": "Reflection of Waves",
"class": "XI",
"unitId": "xi-waves",
"unitLabel": "Unit X — Oscillations & Waves",
"order": 13,
"title": "Reflection of Waves",
"summary": "String is divided into three points, <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Fundamental frequency for open organ pipe, $$ f_{o}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{2\\mathbf{L}_{o}} $$ Fundamental frequency for closed organ pipe, $$ \\begin{aligned}&f_{c}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{4\\mathrm{L}_{c}}\\\\ &\\frac{f_{o}}{f_{c}}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{2\\mathrm{L}_{o}}\\times\\frac{4\\mathrm{L}_{c}}{\\mathbf{v}}\\\\ &\\begin{aligned}\\\\ &\\frac{f_{o}}{f_{c}}=\\frac{2}{1}&&\\left(\\because\\mathrm{L}_{o}=\\mathrm{L}_{c}\\right)\\\\ &\\end{aligned}\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- Length of string of musical instrument $$ \\begin{aligned}B)&Length~of~string~of~musical~instrument\\\\&l=90\\mathrm{~cm}=0.9\\mathrm{~m}\\\\&fundamental~frequency,\\\\&f_{1}=120\\mathrm{~Hz},f_{2}=180\\mathrm{~Hz}.\\\\&We~know~that:\\\\&\\quad f\\propto\\frac{1}{l}\\\\&\\Rightarrow\\quad\\frac{f_{1}}{f_{2}}=\\frac{l_{2}}{l_{1}}\\\\&\\Rightarrow\\quad l_{2}=\\frac{f_{1}}{f_{2}}\\times l_{1}\\\\&\\quad l_{2}=\\frac{120}{180}\\times0.9\\\\&\\quad l_{2}=\\frac{2}{3}\\times0.9=0.6\\mathrm{~m}\\\\&\\quad l_{r}=60\\mathrm{~cm}.\\end{aligned} $$\n- For closed organ pipe, Third harmonics, $$ f=\\frac{3\\mathbf{v}}{4I} $$ where, l is the length of closed organ pipe. For open organ pipe, fundamental frequency, $$ f=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{2l}, $$ where, $ l = \\text{length of the open organ pipe} $. Equating equation (i) and (ii) $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{3\\mathrm{v}}{4l}&=\\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{2l^{\\prime}}\\\\l^{\\prime}&=\\frac{4l}{3\\times2}=\\frac{2l}{3}\\\\\\bar{l}&=\\frac{2}{3}\\times20=\\frac{40}{3}\\\\&\\quad[\\because\\text{Since},l=20\\text{cm given}]\\\\&=13.33\\text{cm}\\end{aligned} $$\n- For first resonance, $ l_{1} = \\frac{\\lambda}{4} $ and second resonance, $ l_{2} = \\frac{3\\lambda}{4} $ $ \\Rightarrow $ $ l_{2} - l_{1} = \\frac{3\\lambda}{4} - \\frac{\\lambda}{4} = \\frac{\\lambda}{2} $ $ \\lambda = 2(l_{2} - l_{1}) $ Velocity of sound wave, $$ \\begin{aligned}&\\mathbf{v}=\\mathbf{v}\\lambda\\qquad\\quad(Where,v=frequency)\\\\&\\mathbf{v}=\\mathbf{v}\\left(2\\right)\\left(l_{2}-l_{1}\\right)\\\\&\\mathbf{v}=2[320(0.73-0.20)]\\\\&\\mathbf{v}=2\\times320\\times0.53=339.2ms^{-1}\\\\&\\mathbf{v}\\approx339ms^{-1}\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- For second overtone $(3^{rd}$ harmonics) in open organ pipe, $3\\lambda$ $$ \\frac{3\\lambda}{2}=l_{o} $$ $$ \\lambda=\\frac{2l_{p}}{3} $$ for first overtone $(2^{nd}$ harmonics)$ in closed organ pipe, $$ \\begin{aligned}&\\frac{3\\lambda}{4}=l_{c}\\\\&\\Rightarrow\\quad\\lambda=\\frac{4l_{c}}{3}=\\frac{4L}{3}\\\\&So,\\quad\\frac{2l_{o}}{3}=\\frac{4L}{3}\\\\&\\Rightarrow\\quad l_{0}=2L\\end{aligned} $$\n- The situation is shown in the given diagram, $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\displaystyle\\bigcup_{\\mathrm{L}_{\\min}}=\\frac{\\lambda}{4}\\\\ \\vdots\\\\ \\displaystyle\\mathrm{L}_{\\min}=\\frac{\\lambda}{4}\\\\ \\Rightarrow\\quad50=\\frac{\\lambda}{4}\\\\ \\Rightarrow\\quad\\lambda=200\\mathrm{~cm}\\end{array} $$ Next higher length of an column, $$ \\begin{aligned}L&=\\frac{\\lambda}{4}+\\frac{\\lambda}{2}=\\frac{3\\lambda}{4}\\\\&=\\frac{3}{4}\\times200=150cm\\end{aligned} $$\n- Two consecutive resonant frequencies for a string fixed at both ends will be, $$ \\begin{array}{c}\\frac{n\\mathbf{v}}{2l}\\ and\\ \\frac{(n+1)}{2l}\\mathbf{v}\\\\\\Rightarrow\\frac{(n+1)\\mathbf{v}}{2l}-\\frac{n\\mathbf{v}}{2l}\\ =420-315\\\\\\Rightarrow\\quad\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{2l}\\ =105\\ Hz\\end{array} $$\n- For closed organ pipe, frequency of vibration $f_{c}$ is given, $$ f_{c}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{4l} $$ l = length of closed organ pipe and for open organ pipe frequency of vibration is $ f_{0} $ $$ f_{0}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{2l^{\\prime}} $$ $ l' = \\text{length of open organ pipe} $ According to question, $$ f_{c}=3f_{o} $$ $$ \\mathrm{\\frac{v}{4l}}=\\mathrm{\\frac{3v}{2l^{\\prime}}} $$ ↓ $$ l^{\\prime}=6l $$ $$ l^{\\prime}=6\\times20=120cm $$\n- String is divided into three points, <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//469c3723-cc7c-4562-abf6-545774a2e0f7/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_742_378_963_434.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A57Z%2F-1%2F%2F92678e3fad92bd11769121b93cfc20e79af4ef12ed75c9dd0100bfa49f4febf4\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"18%\" /></div> $ l_{1} $ has frequency $ n_{1} $ $ l_{2} $ has frequency $ n_{2} $ and $l_{3}$ has frequency $n_{3}$ Using, $$ \\mathbf{v}=f\\boldsymbol{\\lambda} $$ $$ \\lambda=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{f} $$ $$ l_{1}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{n_{1}},l_{2}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{n_{2}},l_{3}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{n_{3}} $$ $$ l=l_{1}+l_{2}+l_{3} $$ $$ \\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{n}=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{n_{1}}+\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{n_{2}}+\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{n_{3}} $$ where, v is same in all case, $$ \\frac{1}{n}=\\frac{1}{n_{1}}+\\frac{1}{n_{2}}+\\frac{1}{n_{3}} $$\n- For pipe closed at one end, <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//469c3723-cc7c-4562-abf6-545774a2e0f7/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_765_964_938_1038.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A58Z%2F-1%2F%2F852b2a9bd2085642e4a711c3ebaf4a5ec1b73e481633067879edf71a4f9b1dec\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"14%\" /></div> $$ \\begin{aligned}f_{n}&=(2n-1)\\left(\\frac{\\mathbf{v}}{4l}\\right)\\\\&=(2n-1)\\times\\frac{340}{4\\times85\\times10^{-2}}\\end{aligned} $$ $$ =(2n-1)100 $$ $$ f_{1}=100\\mathrm{~Hz},f_{2}=300\\mathrm{~Hz} $$ $$ f_{3}=500Hz,f_{4}=700Hz $$ $$ f_{5}=900\\mathrm{~Hz},f_{6}=1100\\mathrm{~Hz} $$ This confirms that number of possible natural oscillations could be 6.\n- In the study of the vibration of a pipe, open at both the ends, the displacement node is pressure antinode. So, the pressure change will be maximum at the length $ \\frac{l}{2} $ and the pressure variation will be minimum at both the ends. The odd and even harmonics will be present in the vibration.\n- For standing wave, the length of one segment will be $\\frac{\\lambda}{2}$. Since, there are 5 segments and total length of the string is 10 m. $\\therefore\\quad5\\times\\frac{\\lambda}{2}=10$ $\\Rightarrow\\lambda=4\\ m$ Thus, frequency Thus, frequency, $$ f=\\frac{v}{\\lambda}=\\frac{20}{4}=5Hz\\quad(\\because v=20m/s) $$",
