"unitLabel": "Unit I — Electrostatics",
"order": 14,
"title": "How Gauss's law gives the fields of symmetric charges",
"summary": "Gauss's law quickly yields the field of symmetric distributions: an infinite line (E ∝ 1/r), an infinite sheet (uniform), and a charged spherical shell.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Infinite line of charge: $E=\\dfrac{\\lambda}{2\\pi\\varepsilon_0 r}$.\n- Infinite sheet of charge: $E=\\dfrac{\\sigma}{2\\varepsilon_0}$ (independent of distance).\n- Spherical shell: outside $E=\\dfrac{kq}{r^2}$, inside $E=0$.\n**Exam traps**\n- A sheet's field is independent of distance; the field inside a shell is zero.\n- Just outside a conductor $E=\\sigma/\\varepsilon_0$, but for an isolated sheet $E=\\sigma/2\\varepsilon_0$.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "E_{line}=\\dfrac{\\lambda}{2\\pi\\varepsilon_0 r}",
"meaning": "Field of an infinite line charge"
},
{
"latex": "E_{sheet}=\\dfrac{\\sigma}{2\\varepsilon_0}",
"meaning": "Field of an infinite charged sheet"
},
{
"latex": "E_{out}=\\dfrac{kq}{r^2},\\quad E_{in}=0",
"meaning": "Field of a charged spherical shell"
}
],
