"title": "Why like charges repel and unlike attract as an inverse square",
"summary": "Coulomb's law gives the electrostatic force between two point charges: F = kq₁q₂/r², along the line joining them — repulsive for like charges, attractive for unlike.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $F=\\dfrac{1}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0}\\dfrac{q_1q_2}{r^2}=\\dfrac{kq_1q_2}{r^2}$, with $k=9\\times10^9\\ \\text{N m}^2\\text{C}^{-2}$.\n- In a medium of dielectric constant $K$: $F=\\dfrac{1}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0 K}\\dfrac{q_1q_2}{r^2}$.\n- Electric field: $\\vec{E}=\\dfrac{\\vec{F}}{q_0}$, so for a point charge $E=\\dfrac{kq}{r^2}$.\n**Exam traps**\n- The force is a vector; for several charges use superposition (vector sum).\n- Charge is quantised, $q=ne$, and is conserved.",
