"order": 14,
"title": "How a uniform field exerts a torque on an electric dipole",
"summary": "In a uniform field a dipole feels zero net force but a torque τ = pE sinθ (τ = p×E) that tends to align it with the field.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Net force is zero in a uniform field; the torque is $\\vec{\\tau}=\\vec{p}\\times\\vec{E}$, $\\tau=pE\\sin\\theta$.\n- Potential energy: $U=-\\vec{p}\\cdot\\vec{E}=-pE\\cos\\theta$.\n- Stable equilibrium when $\\vec{p}\\parallel\\vec{E}$; unstable when anti-parallel.\n**Exam traps**\n- The net force is zero only in a UNIFORM field; a non-uniform field gives a net force.\n- The torque is maximum at $\\theta=90^\\circ$.",
