"order": 14,
"title": "Why electric flux depends only on the enclosed charge",
"summary": "Gauss's law states that the net electric flux through any closed surface equals the enclosed charge divided by ε₀: Φ = q_enc/ε₀.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $\\Phi=\\oint\\vec{E}\\cdot d\\vec{A}=\\dfrac{q_{enc}}{\\varepsilon_0}$.\n- For a uniform field through a flat area: $\\Phi=EA\\cos\\theta$.\n- The flux is independent of the surface's shape and of any charges outside it.\n**Exam traps**\n- Only the ENCLOSED charge contributes; external charges give zero net flux.\n- If the net enclosed charge is zero, the net flux is zero (even if the field is not).",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\Phi=\\oint\\vec{E}\\cdot d\\vec{A}=\\dfrac{q_{enc}}{\\varepsilon_0}",
"meaning": "Gauss's law"
},
{
"latex": "\\Phi=EA\\cos\\theta",
"meaning": "Flux of a uniform field"
}
],
