"order": 14,
"title": "How Coulomb's law and Gauss's law describe the electric field",
"summary": "Coulomb's law gives the force between charges and Gauss's law relates flux to enclosed charge; with superposition they yield the field of any charge distribution.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Force $F=\\dfrac{kq_1q_2}{r^2}$ and field $E=\\dfrac{kq}{r^2}$, combined by superposition.\n- Gauss's law $\\Phi=\\dfrac{q_{enc}}{\\varepsilon_0}$ gives symmetric fields fast.\n- An electric dipole ($p=qd$) experiences a torque in a field.\n**Exam traps**\n- The field is a vector but the potential is a scalar.\n- Charge is quantised and conserved.",
