"unitLabel": "Unit I — Electrostatics",
"order": 15,
"title": "Why the electric field inside a conductor is zero",
"summary": "In electrostatic equilibrium a conductor has zero field inside, all excess charge on its surface, and its surface is an equipotential with E perpendicular to it.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $E=0$ everywhere inside; all excess charge resides on the surface.\n- The whole conductor is at one potential; just outside the surface $E=\\dfrac{\\sigma}{\\varepsilon_0}$, perpendicular to it.\n- A field-free cavity provides electrostatic shielding.\n**Exam traps**\n- The potential is constant throughout a conductor, even if its surface is curved.\n- The field just outside is $\\sigma/\\varepsilon_0$, not $\\sigma/2\\varepsilon_0$.",
