"unitLabel": "Unit I — Electrostatics",
"order": 15,
"title": "How equipotential surfaces map the electric field",
"summary": "An equipotential surface joins points at the same potential; no work is done moving a charge along it, and the field is always perpendicular to it.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $V$ is constant over the surface, so $W=0$ for any motion along it.\n- $\\vec{E}$ is perpendicular to the surface and points toward decreasing potential.\n- More closely spaced equipotentials indicate a stronger field; for a point charge they are concentric spheres.\n**Exam traps**\n- The field is always perpendicular to an equipotential surface.\n- No work is done moving a charge along an equipotential.",
