"id": "note-electrostatic-potential-and-capacitance-potential-energy-in-an-external-field",
"chapter": "Electrostatic Potential and Capacitance",
"subtopic": "Potential Energy in an External Field",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-electrostatics",
"unitLabel": "Unit I — Electrostatics",
"order": 15,
"title": "How charges and dipoles store energy in an external field",
"summary": "A charge q at potential V has energy U = qV; a dipole in a uniform field has U = −p·E = −pE cosθ.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Single charge: $U=qV$.\n- Dipole in a field: $U=-\\vec{p}\\cdot\\vec{E}=-pE\\cos\\theta$; torque $\\tau=pE\\sin\\theta$.\n- Stable equilibrium when $\\vec{p}$ is aligned with $\\vec{E}$.\n**Exam traps**\n- The dipole energy is minimum ($-pE$) when aligned and maximum ($+pE$) when anti-aligned.\n- The torque is maximum when $\\vec{p}\\perp\\vec{E}$.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "U=qV",
"meaning": "Energy of a charge in an external field"
},
{
"latex": "U=-\\vec{p}\\cdot\\vec{E}=-pE\\cos\\theta",
"meaning": "Energy of a dipole in a field"
},
{
"latex": "\\tau=pE\\sin\\theta",
"meaning": "Torque on a dipole"
}
],
