"id": "note-electrostatic-potential-and-capacitance-potential-energy-of-a-system-of-charges",
"chapter": "Electrostatic Potential and Capacitance",
"subtopic": "Potential Energy of a System of Charges",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-electrostatics",
"unitLabel": "Unit I — Electrostatics",
"order": 15,
"title": "How to find the energy of a charge configuration",
"summary": "The potential energy of a system of charges is the work needed to assemble it; for two charges U = kq₁q₂/r, summed over all pairs for more.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Two charges: $U=\\dfrac{kq_1q_2}{r}$.\n- Many charges: $U=\\displaystyle\\sum_{i<j}\\dfrac{kq_iq_j}{r_{ij}}$ (each pair once).\n- Like charges give $U>0$, unlike charges $U<0$.\n**Exam traps**\n- Sum over distinct pairs only — do not double-count.\n- Keep the sign of the product of charges.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "U=\\dfrac{kq_1q_2}{r}",
"meaning": "PE of two point charges"
},
{
"latex": "U=\\sum_{i<j}\\dfrac{kq_iq_j}{r_{ij}}",
"meaning": "PE of a system (pairwise sum)"
}
],
