"order": 16,
"title": "Why many devices do not obey Ohm's law",
"summary": "Ohm's law fails when the V–I graph is non-linear or non-unique, or when the current depends on the sign of the voltage — as in diodes, electrolytes and at high fields or temperatures.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- A device is non-ohmic when: V–I is not a straight line (e.g. a diode), the relation is not single-valued (e.g. GaAs), or it depends on the polarity of V.\n- Resistance varies with temperature: for metals $R$ rises with $T$; for semiconductors $R$ falls with $T$.\n- Temperature dependence: $R_T=R_0(1+\\alpha\\,\\Delta T)$, where $\\alpha$ is the temperature coefficient of resistance.\n**Exam traps**\n- Ohmic conductors give a straight V–I line through the origin.\n- Common non-ohmic elements: junction diodes, transistors, electrolytes, and gas/vacuum tubes.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "R_T=R_0(1+\\alpha\\,\\Delta T)",
"meaning": "Variation of resistance with temperature"
},
{
"latex": "\\rho_T=\\rho_0(1+\\alpha\\,\\Delta T)",
"meaning": "Variation of resistivity with temperature"
},
{
"latex": "\\alpha=\\dfrac{R_T-R_0}{R_0\\,\\Delta T}",
"meaning": "Temperature coefficient of resistance"
}
],
