"id": "note-current-electricity-ohm-s-law",
"chapter": "Current Electricity",
"subtopic": "Ohm's Law",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-current",
"unitLabel": "Unit II — Current Electricity",
"order": 16,
"title": "Why V = IR holds for an ohmic conductor",
"summary": "Ohm's law states that, at constant temperature, the current through an ohmic conductor is proportional to the potential difference across it: V = IR, where R is its resistance.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $V=IR$; resistance $R=\\dfrac{V}{I}$ is measured in ohm ($\\Omega$).\n- For a uniform conductor: $R=\\rho\\dfrac{L}{A}$, where $\\rho$ is the resistivity, $L$ the length and $A$ the cross-section.\n- Conductance $G=\\dfrac{1}{R}$; conductivity $\\sigma=\\dfrac{1}{\\rho}$.\n- Microscopic (point) form of Ohm's law: $\\vec{J}=\\sigma\\vec{E}$, where $\\vec{J}$ is the current density.\n**Exam traps**\n- $R$ depends on geometry ($L,A$) and material; $\\rho$ depends only on the material and its temperature, not on $L$ or $A$.\n- 'Ohmic' requires constant temperature — a straight V–I line through the origin.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "V=IR",
"meaning": "Ohm's law"
},
{
"latex": "R=\\rho\\dfrac{L}{A}",
"meaning": "Resistance of a uniform conductor"
},
{
"latex": "\\sigma=\\dfrac{1}{\\rho},\\quad G=\\dfrac{1}{R}",
"meaning": "Conductivity and conductance"
},
{
"latex": "\\vec{J}=\\sigma\\vec{E}",
"meaning": "Microscopic form of Ohm's law"
}
],
