"chapter": "Current Electricity",
"subtopic": "Overview",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-current",
"unitLabel": "Unit II — Current Electricity",
"order": 16,
"title": "How current, resistance and DC circuits fit together",
"summary": "Electric current is the rate of flow of charge; resistors combine in series and parallel, and EMF, power and Kirchhoff's rules complete the toolkit for steady DC circuits.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Current: $I=\\dfrac{q}{t}=\\dfrac{dq}{dt}$ (ampere).\n- Series resistors (same current): $R_s=R_1+R_2+\\cdots$.\n- Parallel resistors (same voltage): $\\dfrac{1}{R_p}=\\dfrac{1}{R_1}+\\dfrac{1}{R_2}+\\cdots$.\n- Two in parallel: $R_p=\\dfrac{R_1R_2}{R_1+R_2}$.\n**Exam traps**\n- Series adds resistance; parallel adds conductance (so $R_p$ is smaller than the smallest resistor).\n- Current is the same throughout a series branch; voltage is the same across parallel branches.",
