"id": "note-current-electricity-wheatstone-bridge",
"chapter": "Current Electricity",
"subtopic": "Wheatstone Bridge",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-current",
"unitLabel": "Unit II — Current Electricity",
"order": 16,
"title": "Why a balanced Wheatstone bridge gives P/Q = R/S",
"summary": "When a Wheatstone bridge is balanced no current flows through the galvanometer, and the four arms satisfy P/Q = R/S — the principle used to measure an unknown resistance.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Balance condition (galvanometer current zero): $\\dfrac{P}{Q}=\\dfrac{R}{S}$.\n- At balance the result is independent of both the galvanometer resistance and the cell's EMF.\n- Meter (slide-wire) bridge: $\\dfrac{R}{S}=\\dfrac{l}{100-l}$, where $l$ (cm) is the balancing length.\n**Exam traps**\n- Balance is independent of the galvanometer and the driving cell; an unbalanced bridge must be solved with Kirchhoff's rules.\n- In the meter bridge the unknown is found from the balance length, not from any current reading.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{P}{Q}=\\dfrac{R}{S}",
"meaning": "Wheatstone bridge balance condition"
},
{
"latex": "S=R\\,\\dfrac{Q}{P}",
"meaning": "Unknown resistance at balance"
},
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{R}{S}=\\dfrac{l}{100-l}",
"meaning": "Meter-bridge balance (length l cm)"
}
],
