"title": "How Ampère's law gives fields from symmetry",
"summary": "Ampère's law states ∮B·dl = μ₀I_enc — a quick route to the field of symmetric current distributions such as wires and solenoids.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $\\oint\\vec{B}\\cdot d\\vec{l}=\\mu_0 I_{enc}$ (only the enclosed current counts).\n- Long straight wire: $B=\\dfrac{\\mu_0 I}{2\\pi r}$.\n- Inside a long solenoid: $B=\\mu_0 nI$; toroid: $B=\\dfrac{\\mu_0 NI}{2\\pi r}$.\n**Exam traps**\n- Choose an Amperian loop matching the symmetry; currents outside the loop contribute nothing to the line integral.",
