"order": 17,
"title": "How magnetic fields push moving charges and currents",
"summary": "A charge moving in a magnetic field feels the Lorentz force F = qv×B; a current-carrying wire feels F = IL×B.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- On a charge: $\\vec{F}=q\\vec{v}\\times\\vec{B}$, magnitude $F=qvB\\sin\\theta$.\n- On a wire: $\\vec{F}=I\\vec{L}\\times\\vec{B}$, magnitude $F=BIL\\sin\\theta$.\n- Full Lorentz force: $\\vec{F}=q(\\vec{E}+\\vec{v}\\times\\vec{B})$.\n**Exam traps**\n- The force is maximum when $\\vec{v}\\perp\\vec{B}$ and zero when they are parallel.\n- The magnetic force does no work — it changes direction, not speed.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\vec{F}=q\\vec{v}\\times\\vec{B},\\quad F=qvB\\sin\\theta",
"meaning": "Magnetic force on a charge"
},
{
"latex": "\\vec{F}=I\\vec{L}\\times\\vec{B},\\quad F=BIL\\sin\\theta",
"meaning": "Force on a current-carrying wire"
},
{
"latex": "\\vec{F}=q(\\vec{E}+\\vec{v}\\times\\vec{B})",
"meaning": "Lorentz force"
}
],
