"order": 17,
"title": "Why a charge moves in a circle or helix in a magnetic field",
"summary": "A charge moving perpendicular to B circles with radius r = mv/qB and period T = 2πm/qB (independent of speed); a velocity component along B turns the path into a helix.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Radius: $r=\\dfrac{mv}{qB}=\\dfrac{p}{qB}$.\n- Period and cyclotron frequency: $T=\\dfrac{2\\pi m}{qB}$, $f=\\dfrac{qB}{2\\pi m}$ — both independent of speed.\n- A velocity component along $\\vec{B}$ gives a helix of pitch $p=v_\\parallel T$.\n**Exam traps**\n- The period (and cyclotron frequency) does not depend on the speed or radius.\n- The magnetic force supplies the centripetal force; it never speeds the particle up.",
