"order": 17,
"title": "How currents both create and respond to magnetic fields",
"summary": "Moving charges and currents produce magnetic fields (Biot–Savart, Ampère) and also experience forces and torques in them (Lorentz force, m×B) — unifying wires, loops, solenoids and instruments.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Sources of field: the Biot–Savart law and Ampère's law $\\oint\\vec{B}\\cdot d\\vec{l}=\\mu_0 I_{enc}$.\n- Effects of field: $\\vec{F}=q\\vec{v}\\times\\vec{B}$, $\\vec{F}=I\\vec{L}\\times\\vec{B}$, $\\vec{\\tau}=\\vec{m}\\times\\vec{B}$.\n- Devices: the cyclotron, the moving-coil galvanometer and the electric motor.\n**Exam traps**\n- Keep the field-producing formulas distinct from the force/torque formulas.\n- The magnetic force never does work.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\vec{F}=q\\vec{v}\\times\\vec{B}",
"meaning": "Force on a moving charge"
},
{
"latex": "B=\\dfrac{\\mu_0 I}{2\\pi r}",
"meaning": "Field of a straight wire"
},
{
"latex": "\\vec{\\tau}=\\vec{m}\\times\\vec{B}",
"meaning": "Torque on a magnetic dipole"
},
{
"latex": "r=\\dfrac{mv}{qB}",
"meaning": "Radius of circular motion"
}
],
