"order": 18,
"title": "Magnetic Properties of Materials",
"summary": "<table border=1 style='margin: auto; word-wrap: break-word;'><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Material</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Magnetic susceptibility $ \\chi…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- The incorrect relation is $ 1 < \\mu_r < 1 + \\varepsilon $ For diamagnetic material, magnetic susceptibility is small and negative i.e., $-1 \\leq \\chi \\leq 0$. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//6909d2d9-c618-4062-813f-fb3c5cb303ec/markdown_3/imgs/img_in_image_box_85_554_127_590.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A50Z%2F-1%2F%2Fc688d60298f78fe9fad4f685128cbaf8b9bda7b2d5f041de42b6262f63a10ffd\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"3%\" /></div> ##### Caution Students should not get confused between relative permeability and magnetic susceptibility of diamagnetic, paramagnetic and ferromagnetic materials.\n- <table border=1 style='margin: auto; word-wrap: break-word;'><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Material</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Magnetic susceptibility $ \\chi $</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Diamagnetic</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>slightly less than 0</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Paramagnetic</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>slightly greater than 0</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Ferromagnetic</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ \\gg 1 $</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Non-magnetic</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>0</td></tr></table>\n- The magnetic moment of a diamagnetic atom is equal to zero.\n- Energy of current source will be converted into potential energy of the rod.\n- Magnetic susceptibility = $ \\chi $ It is negative for diamagnetic material only.\n- (I) Paramagnetic material will be feebly attracted, (II) Diamagnetic material will be feebly repelled, (III) Ferromagnetic material will be strongly attracted (IV) Non-Magnetic material will remain unaffected by magnetic field.\n- If a diamagnetic substance is brought near the north or the south pole of a bar magnet, it is repelled by both the poles.\n- Curie temperature is that temperature above which a ferromagnetic material becomes paramagnetic material.\n- Above curie temperature, ferromagnetic material behaves as paramagnetic material.\n- $ \\mu_p \\neq 0 $, $ \\mu_f \\neq 0 $ and $ \\mu_d = 0 $\n- A diamagnetic material in a magnetic field moves from stronger to the weaker part of the field. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//6909d2d9-c618-4062-813f-fb3c5cb303ec/markdown_3/imgs/img_in_image_box_657_529_694_572.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A50Z%2F-1%2F%2F9e928c926be020f4dc6e2efef0620c8961ee97644c98e119d062bab64e0b7d8f\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"3%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory A diamagnetic material tends to move from stronger to weaker regions of the magnetic field and hence decreases the number of magnetic field lines passing through it.\n- From Curie Law, $ \\chi_{m} \\propto \\frac{1}{T} $\n- Material's magnetic susceptibility is a measurement of how easily a specimen of that material may be magnetized in a magnetic field. Magnetic susceptibility ( $ \\chi_{m} $) of a diamagnetic substance is temperature independent.\n- When diamagnetic substances are placed in the magnetic field of a powerful magnet, they are weakly magnetized in the opposite direction of the field and repelled by the powerful magnet. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//6909d2d9-c618-4062-813f-fb3c5cb303ec/markdown_3/imgs/img_in_image_box_656_933_692_980.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A50Z%2F-1%2F%2F2882eaf77ef67ec9e4325b0e360b2b96838252b06c7394cfef446d75c5de233f\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"3%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory Relative permeability of the diamagnetic substance is negative.",
