"title": "Faraday's Law of Induction",
"summary": "We know that, Induced emf of coil, $ e = \\left| -\\frac{d\\phi}{dt} \\right|_{t} $ Given that, $$ \\phi=50t^{2}+4\\mathrm{a n d}\\mathrm{R}=400\\Omega $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}e&=\\left|\\frac{-d\\phi}{d…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Here, number of turns, (N) = 1000 Radius, (r) = 10 m Magnetic field, (B) = $ 2 \\times 10^{-5} $ T $$ \\mathrm{Resistance},(\\mathrm{R})=12.56\\ \\Omega $$ Angular frequency of coil, $\\omega = 2\\ \\mathrm{rad}\\ \\mathrm{s}^{-1}$ $$ \\begin{aligned}num~induced~emf,&\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{N}\\omega\\mathrm{AB}\\\\&=\\mathrm{N}\\omega(\\pi r^{2})\\mathrm{B}\\\\&=1000\\times2\\times3.14\\times(10)^{2}\\times2\\times10^{-5}\\\\&=12.56\\mathrm{V}\\end{aligned} $$ Maximum induced current. $$ \\begin{aligned}I_{max}&=\\frac{E}{R}\\\\&=\\frac{12.56}{12.56}=1A\\end{aligned} $$\n- Given: Magnetic flux, $ (\\phi)=5t^{2}+3t+16 $ Induced emf. $$ \\begin{aligned}|\\mathbf{E}|&=\\frac{d\\phi}{dt}\\\\&=\\frac{d}{dt}(5t^{2}+3t+16)\\\\&=10t+3\\end{aligned} $$ when, $$ t=4\\mathrm{~s}, $$ $$ \\left|\\mathrm{E}_{4}\\right|=(10\\times4)+3=43\\mathrm{~V} $$\n- Here, $$ \\mathrm{N=800\\tau u r n s} $$ $$ A=0.05\\ m^{2}=5\\times10^{-2}\\ m^{2} $$ $$ \\mathbf{B}=5\\times10^{-5}\\mathrm{T} $$ $$ \\Delta t=0.1\\mathrm{~s~} $$ We know that, $$ e_induced=-{}\\frac{\\Delta\\phi}{\\Delta t} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\Delta\\phi&=\\phi_{f}-\\phi_{i}\\\\\\phi_{f}&=0,\\phi_{i}=\\mathbf{N}\\big(\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}.\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{A}}\\big)\\\\&=800\\times5\\times10^{-5}\\times5\\times10^{-2}\\\\&=2\\times10^{-3}\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}e_{\\mathrm{induced}}=&-\\frac{\\Delta\\phi}{\\Delta t}=\\frac{-(0-2\\times10^{-3})}{0.1}\\\\&=0.02\\mathrm{~V}\\end{aligned} $$\n- We know that induced emf in the region is given by $$ e=-{\\frac{d\\Phi}{d t}}\\quad\\{\\because\\Phi=\\mathrm{B A}=\\pi r^{2}\\mathrm{B} $$ $$ \\because A=\\pi r^{2} $$ $$ \\frac{d\\Phi}{dt}=-\\pi r^{2}\\frac{dB}{dt} $$ From question, Rate of change of magnetic flux associated with loop (1), $$ e_{1}=-\\frac{d\\Phi_{1}}{d t}=-\\pi r^{2}\\frac{d\\Phi}{d t} $$ and Rate of change of magnetic flux associated with loop (2), $$ e_{2}=-\\frac{d\\Phi_{2}}{d t}=0\\qquad\\{\\mathrm{s i n c e}\\;\\Phi_{2}=0\\} $$\n- Rate of decrease of area of semicircular ring $$ =\\frac{\\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{A}}{\\mathrm{d}t}=(\\pi r)\\mathbf{v} $$ From Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction, $$ e = - \\frac{d \\Phi}{d t} = - \\mathbf { B } \\frac{d \\mathbf { A }}{d t} = - \\mathbf { B } ( \\pi r \\mathbf { v}) $$ $$ \\begin{array}{c}\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\\\\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad r\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\\\\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\bullet\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\oplus\\\\P\\longleftarrow2r\\longrightarrow R\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\quad\\times\\end{array} $$ As induced current in the ring produces magnetic field in upward direction, Hence, R is at higher potential.\n- We know that, Induced emf of coil, $ e = \\left| -\\frac{d\\phi}{dt} \\right|_{t} $ Given that, $$ \\phi=50t^{2}+4\\mathrm{a n d}\\mathrm{R}=400\\Omega $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}e&=\\left|\\frac{-d\\phi}{d t}\\right|_{t=2}=[100t]_{t=2}\\\\&=200\\mathrm{~V}\\end{aligned} $$ ∴ Current in the coil, $ I = \\frac{E}{R} = \\frac{200}{400} $ $$ I=0.5A $$ \\[\\begin{array}{r l}{\\mathrm{(B)}~}&{\\mathrm{W e~k n o w~t h a t,}\\phi=\\mathrm{B A}}\\\\ {\\Rightarrow}&{}\\\\ {\\mathrm{E_{i n}}=\\frac{-d\\phi}{d t}}\\\\ {\\Rightarrow}&{\\mathrm{E_{i n}}=-\\frac{d}{d t}(\\mathrm{B A})}\\\\ {\\Rightarrow}&{\\mathrm{E}=-\\mathrm{B}\\pi2r\\frac{d r}{d t}}\\\\ {\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{B}\\pi2r\\frac{d r}{d t}}\\\\ {\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{B}\\pi2r\\frac{d r}{d t}}\\\\ {E=\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{B}\\pi2r\\frac{d r}{d t}}\\\\ {E=\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{B}\\pi2r\\frac{d r}{d t}}\\\\ {E=\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{B}\\pi2r\\frac{d r}{d t}}\\\\ {E=\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{B}\\pi2r\\frac{d r}{d t\n- As the induced electric field due to change in magnetic field is non-conservative. The work done due to change in flux = QV.\n- Total number of turns, N = 20 Area of coil, $$ \\begin{array}{l} \\text{A} = 25\\ \\text{cm}^2\\\\ = 25 \\times 10^{-4}\\ \\text{m}^2 \\end{array} $$ Change in magnetic field w.r.t. t $$ \\frac{d\\mathbf{B}}{dt}=1000\\mathrm{T/s} $$ Resistance of coil, $ R = 100 \\, \\Omega $ We have, Induced current, $$ i=\\frac{e}{\\mathbf{R}} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}&=\\frac{NA\\frac{dB}{dt}}{R}\\left[\\because e=NA\\frac{dB}{dt}\\right]\\\\&=\\frac{20\\times25\\times10^{-4}\\times1000}{100}\\\\&=0.5A\\end{aligned} $$\n- When electron goes in straight line, electric flux first increases then decreases.\n- When a circuit is broken, the induced e.m.f. is largest.",
