"order": 19,
"title": "Inductance",
"summary": "Let current in bigger loop be i.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- $ \\mathbf{L} = \\mu_0 \\mu_r \\times n \\times \\mathbf{A} \\times \\mathbf{N} $ $ \\mathbf{L} = \\mu_0 \\mu_r n \\times \\mathbf{A} \\times \\frac{\\mathbf{N}}{l} \\times l $ $ \\mathbf{L} = \\mu_0 \\mu_r \\times n^2 \\times \\mathbf{A} \\times l $ $ \\mathbf{L} \\propto n^2 l $ $ \\frac{\\mathbf{L}_{\\mathrm{A}}}{\\mathbf{L}_{\\mathrm{B}}} = \\frac{n_{\\mathrm{A}}^2}{n_{\\mathrm{B}}^2} \\times \\frac{l_{\\mathrm{A}}}{l_{\\mathrm{B}}} $ $ \\mathbf{\\frac{L_{\\mathrm{A}}}{L_{\\mathrm{B}}}} = \\frac{1}{4} \\times 2 = \\frac{1}{2} $\n- As we know that, $ \\mathbf{U} = \\frac{1}{2} \\mathbf{L} \\mathbf{I}^2 $ $ \\mathbf{L} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 4 \\times 10^{-6} \\times 2 \\times 2 $ $ = 8 \\, \\mu\\mathbf{J} $\n- Let current in bigger loop be i. Magnetic field at the centre, $$ \\mathbf{B}=\\frac{\\mu_{0}i}{2\\mathbf{R}_{1}} $$ Magnetic flux through smaller coil, $$ \\mathbf{\\Phi}\\phi=\\mathbf{B}\\mathbf{A}=\\frac{\\mathbf{\\Phi}\\phi}{i}=\\frac{\\mu_{0}i}{2\\mathbf{R}_{1}}\\times\\mathbf{\\pi}\\mathbf{R}_{2}^{2} $$ $$ \\phi=\\frac{\\mu_{0}\\pi i R_{2}^{2}}{2R_{1}} $$ As per definition, $ \\phi = Mi $ $$ \\mathbf{M}=\\frac{\\phi}{i}=\\frac{\\frac{\\mu_{0}\\pi i\\mathbf{R}_{2}^{2}}{2\\mathbf{R}_{1}}}{i} $$ $$ \\mathbf{M}=\\frac{\\mu_{0}\\pi R_{2}^{2}}{2R_{1}} $$ $$ M\\propto\\frac{R_{2}^{2}}{R_{1}} $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//d4bf1e1b-d37e-4f3f-8524-f7dae63e3a0e/markdown_0/imgs/img_in_image_box_34_1213_61_1258.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A38Z%2F-1%2F%2F09e3722a4c7839cbb75296b0fc166bd7bd225d5a313b0d036760249b485314ec\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"2%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory When an emf is produced in a coil because of change in current in a coupled coil, the effect is called mutual inductance.\n- Given, $$ U=25mJ=25\\times10^{-3}J $$ $$ I=60\\ mA=60\\times10^{-3}\\ A $$ ∴ Energy stored in inductor. $$ \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{1}{2}\\mathrm{~L}\\times\\mathrm{I}^{2} $$ $$ 25\\times10^{-3}=\\frac{1}{2}L\\times(60\\times(10^{-3}))^{2} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}L&=\\frac{25\\times2\\times10^{6}\\times10^{-3}}{3600}=\\frac{500}{36}\\\\&=13.89Henry\\end{aligned} $$\n- From the question, Number of turns of the solenoid, N = 1000 Current, I = 4 A And magnetic flux, $ \\phi = 4 \\times 10^{-3} $ Wb $ \\therefore $ self induction, $ L = \\frac{\\phi N}{I} $ $ = \\frac{4 \\times 10^{-3} \\times 1000}{4} = 1 \\, \\text{H} $\n- Given: $ \\begin{array}{l} \\text{current I} = 2.5 \\, \\text{A} \\\\ \\text{Inductance, L} = 5 \\, \\text{H} \\\\ \\text{Magnetic flux, } \\phi = ? \\\\ \\text{We know, } \\quad \\phi = \\text{LI} \\\\ \\Rightarrow \\quad = 5 \\times 2.5 \\, \\text{Wb} = 12.5 \\, \\text{Wb} \\end{array} $\n- Mutual inductance between coils is, $$ \\mathbf{M}=k\\sqrt{\\mathbf{L}_{1}\\mathbf{L}_{2}} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{M}&=1\\sqrt{2\\times10^{-3}\\times8\\times10^{-3}}&\\quad\\{k=1\\}\\\\&=4\\times10^{-3}=4\\mathrm{~mH}\\end{aligned} $$\n- L = 2 mH, $ i = t^{2} e^{-t} $ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{E}&=-L\\frac{d\\boldsymbol{i}}{d t}=-L\\frac{d}{d t}[\\boldsymbol{t}^{2}\\boldsymbol{e}^{-t}]\\\\&=-\\mathrm{L}[-\\boldsymbol{t}^{2}\\boldsymbol{e}^{-t}+2t\\boldsymbol{e}^{-t}]\\end{aligned} $$ when $$ E=0, $$ $$ -e^{-t}t^{2}+2t e^{-t}=0 $$ $$ t e^{-t}(t-2)=0 $$ Here, $ t \\neq \\infty $ and $ t \\neq 0 $ $ \\therefore $ t = 2 s\n- Emf induced in the coil of self-inductance L $$ e=-\\frac{d\\phi}{d t}=-\\frac{d}{d t}(L i) $$ or $$ e=-L\\frac{di}{dt} $$ $$ \\left(\\frac{di}{dt}=\\text{rate of flow of current in coil}\\right) $$ As, $$ di=i_{2}-i_{1}=0-10=-10\\mathrm{A} $$ $$ dt=0.5s $$ $$ e=220\\mathrm{~V} $$ $$ 220=-\\mathrm{L}\\ \\frac{(-10)}{05} $$ or $$ L=\\frac{220}{20}=11H $$\n- A long solenoid is one, whose length is significantly greater than its cross-section radius. If N is the total number of turns in the solenoid, A is the area of each turn and l is the length of the solenoid, then the self-inductance of the solenoid is, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{L}&=\\frac{\\mu_{0}\\mathrm{N}^{2}\\mathrm{A}}{l}\\\\\\mathrm{L}&=\\mu_{0}n^{2}\\mathrm{Al}\\end{aligned} $$ (If the number of turns per unit length is $n$) So, $L \\propto n^{2}$ When $n^{2}$ is doubled, L becomes 4 times.",
