"title": "Motional Electromotive Force",
"summary": "<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- In the question, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathbf{B}&=0.4\\mathbf{\\Delta G}=0.4\\times10^{-4}T\\\\l&=1\\mathbf{\\Delta m}\\end{aligned} $$ $$ f=120\\ rpm=\\frac{120}{60}\\ rps=2\\ Hz $$ Induced emf between the axle and rim of the wheel is: $$ \\begin{aligned}&e=\\frac{1}{2}\\mathbf{B}\\omega l^{2}\\\\&=\\frac{1}{2}\\mathbf{B}(2\\pi f)l^{2}=\\pi\\mathbf{B}f l^{2}\\\\&=3.14\\times0.4\\times10^{-4}\\times2\\times1\\\\&=2.51\\times10^{-4}\\mathrm{V}.\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//240112aa-2f94-464c-a50d-7eeeea0d57f9/markdown_4/imgs/img_in_image_box_270_1017_511_1164.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A17%3A10Z%2F-1%2F%2F2e6a26ad5b997dac17ec0edee91879f2eb32133fa2aefcf767ee0f53370a4a55\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"20%\" /></div> According to the question, $$ \\begin{aligned}e&=\\frac{\\mathbf{B}l^{2}\\boldsymbol{\\omega}}{2}\\\\&=\\frac{1}{2}\\bullet0.1\\times\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^{2}\\times10=\\frac{1}{8}\\\\&=0.125V.\\end{aligned} $$\n- According to the question on induced emf is: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\mathrm{V} &= \\frac{\\Delta \\phi}{\\Delta t} \\\\ \\text{and current, } \\mathrm{I} &= \\frac{\\mathrm{Q}}{\\Delta t} = \\frac{\\Delta \\phi}{\\Delta t} \\times \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{R}} \\\\ \\Rightarrow \\quad \\mathrm{Q} &= \\frac{\\Delta \\phi}{\\mathrm{R}} \\end{aligned} $$\n- Given, length of conductor (l) = 0.4 m, $$ \\mathrm{speed}(\\mathbf{v})=7\\mathrm{~m/s} $$ $$ (B)=0.9\\ Wb/m^{2} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}[\\theta=90^{\\circ}]\\text{as B is perpendicular to v}]\\\\=0.9\\times0.4\\times7\\times\\sin90^{\\circ}\\\\=2.52\\text{V}\\end{aligned} $$ ##### Related Theory Magnitude of induced emf is directly proportional to the relative speed of coil magnet system.",
