"id": "note-alternating-current-objective-i",
"chapter": "Alternating Current",
"subtopic": "Objective I",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-emi",
"unitLabel": "Unit V — Electromagnetic Induction & AC",
"order": 20,
"title": "Objective I",
"summary": "In an AC circuit, instantaneous power $= vi$.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- RMS (root mean square) current: $$i_{\\rm rms} = \\sqrt{\\langle i^2 \\rangle} = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{T}\\int_0^T i_0^2\\sin^2\\omega t\\,dt} = i_0\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{2}} = \\frac{i_0}{\\sqrt{2}}$$ Similarly $V_{\\rm rms} = V_0/\\sqrt{2}$. The RMS value is what produces the same heating effect as an equivalent DC current. Answer: (B).\n- In an AC circuit, instantaneous power $= vi$. The average power dissipated (only in resistors) is: $$P = V_{\\rm rms} I_{\\rm rms} \\cos\\phi$$ where $\\phi$ is the phase angle between $V$ and $I$, and $\\cos\\phi = R/Z$ is the **power factor**. A pure inductor or capacitor has $\\phi = 90°$, so $\\cos\\phi = 0$ and $P = 0$ — no average power is dissipated. Answer: (B).\n- Resonance occurs when $X_L = X_C$ (i.e., $\\omega L = 1/\\omega C$), so the net reactance is zero. The impedance: $$Z = \\sqrt{R^2 + (X_L - X_C)^2} = \\sqrt{R^2 + 0} = R$$ At resonance, $Z = R$ (minimum), current is maximum ($I = V/R$), and the circuit is purely resistive. The resonant frequency: $\\omega_0 = 1/\\sqrt{LC}$. Answer: (B).\n- $X_L = \\omega L = 2\\pi f L$. The inductive reactance increases with frequency — at high frequency an inductor effectively blocks the current. At DC ($f = 0$), $X_L = 0$ (inductor acts as a short circuit). Answer: (B).\n- $X_C = 1/(\\omega C) = 1/(2\\pi fC)$. Capacitive reactance **decreases** with frequency — at high frequency a capacitor passes current easily (low impedance). At DC ($f = 0$), $X_C \\to \\infty$ (capacitor blocks DC). Answer: (B).\n- An ideal transformer conserves power: $V_1 I_1 = V_2 I_2$. $$\\frac{I_2}{I_1} = \\frac{V_1}{V_2} = \\frac{1}{10} \\implies I_2 = \\frac{5}{10} = 0.5\\,\\rm A$$ Step-up in voltage → step-down in current (by the same factor). Answer: (B).\n- For a pure inductor: $v = L\\,di/dt$. If $v = V_0\\sin\\omega t$, then $i = -(V_0/\\omega L)\\cos\\omega t = (V_0/\\omega L)\\sin(\\omega t - 90°)$. Current **lags** voltage by 90°. Mnemonic: **ELI** — in an inductor (L), E leads I. Answer: (B).",
