"title": "Objective II",
"summary": "At resonance ($\\omega = \\omega_0$, $X_L = X_C$): - **A** ✓: $I_{\\rm max} = V_0/R$ (maximum since $Z = R$ is minimum).",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- - **A** ✓: Inductor: $\\phi = 90°$, $\\cos\\phi = 0$, $P = 0$. - **B** ✓: Capacitor: $\\phi = -90°$, $\\cos\\phi = 0$, $P = 0$. - **C** ✓: Pure resistor: $\\phi = 0°$, $\\cos\\phi = 1$, $P = I_{\\rm rms}^2 R$. - **D** ✓: At resonance, $Z = R$, $\\phi = 0°$, $\\cos\\phi = 1$, so the circuit behaves purely resistively. Answer: (A), (B), (C), (D).\n- At resonance ($\\omega = \\omega_0$, $X_L = X_C$): - **A** ✓: $I_{\\rm max} = V_0/R$ (maximum since $Z = R$ is minimum). - **B** ✓: $P = I_{\\rm rms}^2 R$ — maximum current → maximum power in $R$. - **C** ✓: Voltage across $L$: $V_L = I\\cdot X_L = (V_0/R)\\cdot\\omega_0 L$. For high $Q = \\omega_0 L/R$, $V_L = QV_0 \\gg V_0$. Similarly $V_C = QV_0$. These can greatly exceed the supply voltage (but $V_L$ and $V_C$ cancel each other). ✓ - **D** ✗: Impedance **decreases** to its minimum value $R$ at resonance. Answer: (A), (B), (C).",
