"id": "note-alternating-current-power-in-ac-circuit-the-power-factor",
"chapter": "Alternating Current",
"subtopic": "Power in AC Circuit: The Power Factor",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-emi",
"unitLabel": "Unit V — Electromagnetic Induction & AC",
"order": 20,
"title": "Why average AC power depends on the power factor",
"summary": "The average power in an AC circuit is P = V_rms·I_rms·cosφ; cosφ is the power factor, from 1 (resistive) down to 0 (purely reactive, a 'wattless' current).",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $P=V_{rms}I_{rms}\\cos\\phi$, where the power factor $\\cos\\phi=\\dfrac{R}{Z}$.\n- Pure resistor: $\\cos\\phi=1$; pure inductor or capacitor: $\\cos\\phi=0$ (no power).\n- Only the resistance dissipates power: $P=I_{rms}^2 R$.\n**Exam traps**\n- Reactive elements store and return energy but dissipate none — this is the 'wattless' current.\n- At resonance $\\cos\\phi=1$, so power is maximum.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "P=V_{rms}I_{rms}\\cos\\phi",
"meaning": "Average AC power"
},
{
"latex": "\\cos\\phi=\\dfrac{R}{Z}",
"meaning": "Power factor"
},
{
"latex": "P=I_{rms}^2 R",
"meaning": "Only the resistance dissipates power"
}
],
