"title": "How a transformer steps voltage up or down",
"summary": "A transformer changes AC voltage by the turns ratio V_s/V_p = N_s/N_p; for an ideal (lossless) transformer V_pI_p = V_sI_s.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- $\\dfrac{V_s}{V_p}=\\dfrac{N_s}{N_p}=\\dfrac{I_p}{I_s}$.\n- Step-up ($N_s>N_p$): voltage rises, current falls; step-down: the reverse.\n- Ideal transformer conserves power: $V_pI_p=V_sI_s$.\n**Exam traps**\n- A transformer works on AC only (it relies on mutual induction).\n- Stepping voltage up necessarily steps current down (power is conserved).",
