"id": "note-electromagnetic-waves-electromagnetic-spectrum",
"chapter": "Electromagnetic Waves",
"subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-em-waves",
"unitLabel": "Unit VI — Electromagnetic Waves",
"order": 21,
"title": "Electromagnetic Spectrum",
"summary": "<table border=1 style='margin: auto; word-wrap: break-word;'><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'></td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Frequency Range (Hz)</td><td…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- The electromagnetic radiation which has the smallest wavelength are Gamma rays with wavelength less than 0.01 nm.\n- <table border=1 style='margin: auto; word-wrap: break-word;'><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'></td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Frequency Range (Hz)</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Wavelength (m)</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Microwaves</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 10^{{9}} $ to $ 10^{{12}} $</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 10^{{-3}} $ to 0.3</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Ultraviolet</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 10^{{15}} $ to $ 10^{{17}} $</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 1.5 \\times 10^{{-7}} $ to $ 3.5 \\times 10^{{-7}} $</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>X-ray</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 10^{{18}} $ to $ 10^{{20}} $</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 10^{{-11}} $ to $ 10^{{-8}} $</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Gamma rays</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 10^{{19}} $ to $ 10^{{24}} $</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 10^{{-16}} $ to $ 10^{{-13}} $</td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"3\">From above table, it is clear that Gamma rays has the shortest wavelength and has higher frequency than microwaves, X-rays and UV-rays.</td></tr></table>\n- Energy, E = h $ \\nu $ = $ \\frac{hc}{\\lambda} $ If K.E. is maximum, thus $ \\lambda $ is minimum. So, energy of emitted X-ray = energy of electron $$ \\frac{hc}{\\lambda_{\\min}}=e\\mathsf{V} $$ $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\Rightarrow\\quad\\lambda_{\\min}=\\frac{hc}{e}\\times\\frac{1}{V}\\\\ \\Rightarrow\\quad\\lambda_{\\min}\\propto\\frac{1}{V}\\end{array} $$\n- The wavelength of AM radio waves is $10^2$ m. The wavelength of microwaves lies between $10^{-3}$ m to $10^{-1}$ m. Infrared radiations wavelength lies between $4 \\times 10^{-7}$ m to $7 \\times 10^{-3}$ m. X-ray wavelength ranges from $10^{-8}$ m to $10^{-12}$ m.\n- $ \\lambda_{\\text{red}} > \\lambda_{\\text{orange}} > \\lambda_{\\text{yellow}} > \\lambda_{\\text{green}} > \\lambda_{\\text{blue}} > \\lambda_{\\text{violet}} $\n- We know, $$ E=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda} $$ $ \\Rightarrow $ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\lambda&=\\frac{hc}{E}=\\frac{6.62\\times10^{-34}\\times3\\times10^{8}}{15\\times10^{3}\\times1.6\\times10^{-19}}\\\\&=0.828\\times10^{-10}m\\\\\\lambda&=0.828\\mathring{A}\\end{aligned} $$ Since, the order of wavelength is between 10 nm and 0.001 nm, it belongs to X-ray.\n- The frequency of the microwave should match the resonant frequency of the water molecules.\n- Decreasing order of wavelength ( $ \\lambda $) Microwave > Infrared > Ultraviolet > Gamma ray. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//eb42f562-0c39-4948-9819-386f13b8d18e/markdown_3/imgs/img_in_image_box_586_762_627_811.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A50Z%2F-1%2F%2Fbc27658f915fac2d5e2265ec852c616fbf78159d4e71127529208cdd629d9feb\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"3%\" /></div> ##### Mnemonics Increasing frequency or decreasing wavelength: Roman: Radio waves Men: Microwaves Invented: Infrared Very: Visible light Unusual: Ultraviolet X-ray: X-rays Guns : Gamma rays Increasing wavelength or decreasing frequency: Good Xylophones Use Very Interesting Musical Rhythms. Gamma rays, X-rays, Ultraviolet, Visible light, Infrared. Microwaves, Radiowaves.\n- $$ \\lambda_{m}>\\lambda_{v}>\\lambda_{x} $$ In spectrum, X-rays has minimum wavelength and microwave has maximum wavelength.\n- Every body at all times, at all temperature emit radiation which fall in the infrared region.\n- $ \\beta $-rays are not electromagnetic waves.\n- Cosmic rays have very short wavelength. Wavelengths: $$ X\\text{-ray}\\to1\\mathrm{~A~t o~}100\\mathrm{~A~} $$ Ultraviolet rays $ \\rightarrow $ 100 Å to 1 Å $ \\gamma $-rays $ \\rightarrow $ 0.001 Å to 1 Å Cosmic rays $ \\rightarrow $ upto $ 4 \\times 10^{-3} $ Å\n- Frequency of radiations given are listed below. <table border=1 style='margin: auto; word-wrap: break-word;'><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'></td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Waves</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'></td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Frequency (in Hz)</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>1.</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ \\gamma $-rays</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>(a)</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 3 \\times 10^{21} $ to $ 3 \\times 10^{18} $</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>2.</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>X-rays</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>(b)</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 3 \\times 10^{18} $ to $ 3 \\times 10^{16} $</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>3.</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>Ultraviolet radiation</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>(c)</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>$ 3 \\times 10^{18} $ to $ 7.5 \\times 10^{14} $</td></tr></table> Thus, correct order is $a > b > c$.\n- In the ozone sphere, the ozone layer extends from 30 km to nearly 50 km above the Earth's surface. This layer absorbs the majority of the Sun's UV radiation and prevents it from reaching the Earth's surface. Since, the range of UV radiations is 100 Å - 4000 Å. As a result, it absorbs radiations of wavelength of less than $ 3 \\times 10^{-7} $ (or 3000 Å).",
