"id": "note-electromagnetic-waves-electromagnetic-waves",
"chapter": "Electromagnetic Waves",
"subtopic": "Electromagnetic Waves",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-em-waves",
"unitLabel": "Unit VI — Electromagnetic Waves",
"order": 21,
"title": "Electromagnetic Waves",
"summary": "Velocity of electromagnetic wave in vacuum.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- For relative permittivity and permeability, $$ \\frac{\\mathrm{H}}{\\mathrm{E}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\varepsilon_{r}\\varepsilon_{0}}{\\mu_{r}\\mu_{0}}} $$ Given. $$ \\frac{\\mu_{r}}{\\varepsilon_{r}}=\\frac{1}{4} $$ $$ \\frac{\\mathrm{H}}{\\mathrm{E}}\\;=\\;\\sqrt{\\frac{4\\varepsilon_{0}}{1\\mu_{0}}}\\quad\\mathrm{\\quad\\left(\\because\\mathrm{Given}\\frac{\\varepsilon_{0}}{\\mu_{0}}=\\frac{1}{120\\pi}\\right)} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{H}{E}&=\\frac{2}{120\\pi}\\\\&=\\frac{E}{H}=60\\pi\\end{aligned} $$\n- Electromagnetic waves do not originate from charges moving with uniform speed. So, this statement is wrong regarding an EM wave travelling in free space. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//eb42f562-0c39-4948-9819-386f13b8d18e/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_image_box_46_1310_78_1352.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A46Z%2F-1%2F%2F21b2697737d38634d9867d266f4b9300142e0c56a8a877146bf7a29cf2e6d9a7\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"2%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory The electromagnetic waves carry equal energy densities in electric and magnetic fields. The source of EM waves is accelerated charge instead of a charge moving with uniform velocity.\n- Given: $$ \\mathbf{v}=2.0\\times10^{10}Hz $$ $$ \\mathrm{E}_{0}=48\\mathrm{~V}\\mathrm{m}^{-1} $$ $$ c=3\\times10^{8}\\,\\mathrm{m s}^{-1} $$ We know that, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{B}_{0}&=\\frac{\\mathrm{E}_{0}}{c}=\\frac{48}{3\\times10^{8}}\\\\&=1.6\\times10^{-7}\\mathrm{~T}\\end{aligned} $$\n- For a plane EM wave, the E and B field are mutually perpendicular. Hence (A), (C) and (D) are not possible.\n- The magnetic field in a plane electromagnetic wave is: $$ \\mathbf{B}_{y}=\\mathbf{B}_{0}\\sin\\left(kx-\\omega t\\right) $$ The given magnetic field in a plane electromagnetic wave is, $$\\mathrm{B}_{y}=2\\times10^{-7}\\sin(\\pi\\times10^{3}x+3\\pi\\times10^{11}t)$$ comparing eq. (i) and eq. (ii) we get, $$ \\begin{array}{c}k=\\pi\\times10^{3}\\\\\\Rightarrow\\quad\\quad\\quad\\quad\\frac{2\\pi}{\\lambda}=\\pi\\times10^{3}\\\\\\Rightarrow\\quad\\quad\\quad\\quad\\lambda=\\frac{2}{10^{3}}\\\\=2\\times10^{-3}m.\\end{array} $$\n- We know that, $ \\frac{E_{0}}{B_{0}} = c $ Where, $ E_{0} $ = Peak value of electric field $ B_{0} $ = Peak value of magnetic field Intensity of electromagnetic wave, $$ 1=\\mathrm{U}_{av}\\cdot c $$ and $$ \\mathrm{U}_{a\\mathrm{v}}=u_{\\mathrm{E}}+u_{\\mathrm{B}} $$ where $u_{E}$ is average energy contribution by electric field and $u_{B}$ is average energy contribution by magnetic field. $$ \\begin{aligned}u_{\\mathrm{E}}&=\\frac{1}{2}\\varepsilon_{0}\\mathrm{E}_{0}^{2}=\\frac{1}{2}\\varepsilon_{0}(c\\mathrm{B}_{0})^{2}\\\\&=\\frac{1}{2}\\varepsilon_{0}c^{2}\\mathrm{B}_{0}^{2}=\\frac{1}{2\\mu_{0}}\\mathrm{B}_{0}^{2}\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\left(\\because c=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\mu_{0}\\varepsilon_{0}}}\\right) $$ $$ u_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\frac{1}{2\\mu_{0}}\\mathrm{B}_{0}^{2} $$ $$ u_{\\mathrm{E}}:u_{\\mathrm{B}}=1:1 $$\n- Velocity of light in medium is, $$ \\mathbf{v}=\\frac{c}{\\sqrt{\\mu_{r}\\varepsilon_{r}}} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}&\\mathrm{v}=\\frac{3\\times10^{8}}{\\sqrt{1\\times1.44}}\\\\ &\\mathrm{v}=2.5\\times10^{8}\\mathrm{m s}^{-1}\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- According to question, $$ E_{rms}=6V/m $$ Peak value of electric field $$ \\begin{aligned}&E_{0}=\\sqrt{2}E_{rms}\\\\&E_{0}=\\sqrt{2}\\times6V/m\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$ We know that. $$ c=\\frac{E_{0}}{B_{0}} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}B_{0}&=\\frac{E_{0}}{c}=\\frac{\\sqrt{2}\\times6}{3\\times10^{8}}\\\\&=\\frac{8.48}{3}\\times10^{-8}\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\mathbf{B}_{0}=2.83\\times10^{-8}\\mathrm{T} $$\n- To generate electromagnetic waves, we need accelerating charge particles.\n- Velocity of electromagnetic wave in vacuum. $$ c=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\mu_{0}\\varepsilon_{0}}}={\\bf v}_{vacuum} $$ Velocity of electromagnetic wave in medium $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{V}_{med}=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\mu_{0}\\mu_{r}\\varepsilon_{0}\\ \\varepsilon_{r}}}\\\\ \\\\ =\\frac{c}{\\sqrt{\\mu_{r}\\varepsilon_{r}}}\\end{array} $$ $\\mu_{0}$ and $\\varepsilon_{0}$ is in vacuum and $\\mu_{r}$ and $\\varepsilon_{r}$ is in medium. For dielectric medium $\\mu_{r}=1$ $$ \\mathbf{v}_{\\mathrm{med}}=\\frac{c}{\\sqrt{\\varepsilon_{r}}}Given\\varepsilon_{r}=4 $$ $$ \\mathbf{v}_{\\mathrm{med}}=\\frac{c}{\\sqrt{4}}=\\frac{c}{2} $$ ∴ Wavelength of the wave in medium, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\lambda_{med}&=\\frac{\\mathbf{v}_{med}}{\\mathbf{v}}\\\\&=\\frac{c}{2\\mathbf{v}}=\\frac{\\lambda_{vacuum}}{2}\\end{aligned} $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//eb42f562-0c39-4948-9819-386f13b8d18e/markdown_2/imgs/img_in_image_box_75_1284_111_1329.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A48Z%2F-1%2F%2F17653f6488ca9b5b11baf0e6ae3fcc6b764bb57b2016a709fc871e529e274397\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"3%\" /></div> ##### Related Theory Maxwell concluded that electromagnetic wave is transverse in nature and the light is an electromagnetic wave.\n- Since $$ c=\\frac{\\mathrm{E}_{0}}{\\mathrm{B}_{0}} $$ $$ \\frac{\\mathbf{B}_{0}}{\\mathbf{E}_{0}}=\\frac{1}{c} $$\n- $$ \\begin{aligned}\\overset{\\rightarrow}{\\mathbf{v}}&=\\overset{\\rightarrow}{\\mathbf{E}}\\times\\overset{\\rightarrow}{\\mathbf{B}}\\\\&=\\mathbf{E}_{0}\\overset{\\leftarrow}{i}\\times\\mathbf{B}_{0}\\overset{\\leftarrow}{j}\\end{aligned} $$ or (direction of propagation of waves is $ \\overrightarrow{E} \\times \\overrightarrow{B} $)\n- It is given that electric field of electromagnetic wave is: $$ \\stackrel{\\rightarrow}{\\mathrm{E}}=10\\cos\\left(10^{7}t+kx\\right)\\stackrel{\\leftarrow}{\\mathrm{j}}\\mathrm{V/m} $$ Here, $$ c=\\frac{\\omega}{k} $$ $$ 3\\times10^{8}=\\frac{10^{7}}{k} $$ $$ k=\\frac{1}{30}=0.033rad/m $$ $$ \\frac{2\\pi}{\\lambda}=\\frac{1}{30} $$ $$ \\lambda=188.4m $$\n- Electric and magnetic field vectors are perpendicular to each other and perpendicular to the direction of propagation of wave.",
