"title": "How microscopes and telescopes magnify",
"summary": "Magnifying instruments combine lenses: a simple microscope gives M = 1 + D/f, while compound microscopes and telescopes multiply the magnifications of objective and eyepiece.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Simple microscope (image at near point): $M=1+\\dfrac{D}{f}$, with $D=25$ cm.\n- Compound microscope: $M\\approx\\dfrac{L}{f_o}\\cdot\\dfrac{D}{f_e}$.\n- Astronomical telescope (normal adjustment): $M=\\dfrac{f_o}{f_e}$ and tube length $L=f_o+f_e$.\n**Exam traps**\n- A telescope needs a large objective focal length and a small eyepiece focal length; a microscope needs both short.\n- The near point distance $D=25$ cm for a normal eye.",
