"id": "note-ray-optics-and-optical-instruments-refraction-at-spherical-surfaces-and-by-lenses",
"chapter": "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments",
"subtopic": "Refraction at Spherical Surfaces and by Lenses",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-optics",
"unitLabel": "Unit VII — Optics",
"order": 22,
"title": "How the lens-maker's formula and the lens equation work",
"summary": "Refraction at one spherical surface gives n₂/v − n₁/u = (n₂−n₁)/R; combining two surfaces yields the lens-maker's formula and the thin-lens equation 1/v − 1/u = 1/f.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Single spherical surface: $\\dfrac{n_2}{v}-\\dfrac{n_1}{u}=\\dfrac{n_2-n_1}{R}$.\n- Lens-maker's formula: $\\dfrac{1}{f}=(n-1)\\!\\left(\\dfrac{1}{R_1}-\\dfrac{1}{R_2}\\right)$.\n- Thin-lens equation: $\\dfrac{1}{v}-\\dfrac{1}{u}=\\dfrac{1}{f}$, magnification $m=\\dfrac{v}{u}$.\n- Power $P=\\dfrac{1}{f}$ (dioptre, $f$ in metres); for thin lenses in contact $P=P_1+P_2$.\n**Exam traps**\n- The lens formula's sign pattern differs from the mirror formula's.\n- A converging (convex) lens has $f>0$; a diverging (concave) lens has $f<0$.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{n_2}{v}-\\dfrac{n_1}{u}=\\dfrac{n_2-n_1}{R}",
"meaning": "Refraction at a single spherical surface"
},
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{1}{f}=(n-1)\\left(\\dfrac{1}{R_1}-\\dfrac{1}{R_2}\\right)",
"meaning": "Lens-maker's formula"
},
{
"latex": "\\dfrac{1}{v}-\\dfrac{1}{u}=\\dfrac{1}{f},\\quad m=\\dfrac{v}{u}",
"meaning": "Thin-lens equation and magnification"
},
{
"latex": "P=\\dfrac{1}{f},\\quad P=P_1+P_2",
"meaning": "Power of a lens; lenses in contact"
}
],
