"id": "note-ray-optics-and-optical-instruments-total-internal-reflection",
"chapter": "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments",
"subtopic": "Total Internal Reflection",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-optics",
"unitLabel": "Unit VII — Optics",
"order": 22,
"title": "How total internal reflection traps light",
"summary": "When light in a denser medium meets the boundary beyond the critical angle, it is reflected entirely back; the critical angle satisfies sin θc = 1/n.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- It occurs only going from a denser to a rarer medium, when the angle of incidence exceeds the critical angle.\n- Critical angle: $\\sin\\theta_c=\\dfrac{n_2}{n_1}=\\dfrac{1}{n}$ (denser medium of index $n$ to air).\n- Applications: optical fibres, the brilliance of diamonds, mirages, totally-reflecting prisms.\n**Exam traps**\n- The condition is $i>\\theta_c$ and only for denser → rarer.\n- A larger refractive index gives a smaller critical angle.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "\\sin\\theta_c=\\dfrac{1}{n}",
"meaning": "Critical angle (denser medium to air)"
},
{
"latex": "\\sin\\theta_c=\\dfrac{n_2}{n_1}\\quad(n_1>n_2)",
"meaning": "Critical angle, general"
},
{
"latex": "i>\\theta_c",
"meaning": "Condition for total internal reflection"
}
],
