"id": "note-wave-optics-diffraction",
"chapter": "Wave Optics",
"subtopic": "Diffraction",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-optics",
"unitLabel": "Unit VII — Optics",
"order": 23,
"title": "Diffraction",
"summary": "<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- As, $$ \\theta_{0}=\\frac{2\\lambda}{a} $$ $$ \\frac{\\theta^{\\prime}}{\\theta_{0}}=\\frac{\\lambda^{\\prime}}{6000} $$ ⇔ $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\lambda^{\\prime}=0.7\\times6000(as\\theta^{\\prime}=0.7\\theta_{0})\\\\=4200\\mathring{A}\\end{array} $$\n- Here $f = D = 60\\ \\text{cm} = 0.6\\ \\text{m}$ Distance of first dark band from centre of screen, $$ \\begin{aligned}y&=\\frac{\\lambda\\mathrm{D}}{a}=\\frac{5\\times10^{-7}\\times0.6}{2\\times10^{-2}\\times10^{-2}}\\\\&=15\\times10^{-4}\\mathrm{~m}=0.15\\mathrm{~c}\\end{aligned} $$\n- According to the question, first minimum is observed at angle $ 30^{\\circ} $ at single slit of width a means $$ n=1,\\theta=30^{\\circ} $$ From Bragg's law $ a \\sin \\theta = n \\lambda $ a sin 30° = λ $$ a=2\\lambda $$ and the first secondary maxima. $$ a\\sin\\theta_{1}=\\frac{3\\lambda}{2} $$ $$ \\theta_{1}=\\frac{3\\lambda}{2a} $$ $ \\Rightarrow $ From eq. (i) and (ii), $$ \\begin{array}{c} \\text{From eq. (1) and (II),}\\\\ \\sin\\theta_{1}=\\dfrac{3\\lambda}{2(2\\lambda)}\\\\\\\\ \\Rightarrow\\qquad\\sin\\theta_{1}=\\dfrac{3}{4}\\\\\\\\ \\Rightarrow\\qquad\\theta_{1}=\\sin^{-1}\\left(\\dfrac{3}{4}\\right)\\\\ \\end{array} $$\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//c4a242b2-912b-4ad1-96b4-7bf2e352f73d/markdown_0/imgs/img_in_image_box_216_336_466_466.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A28Z%2F-1%2F%2F93c429d4660bb41270031049a235f949a6f08d5d8e257e84069ef8031b5cefc2\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"21%\" /></div> Phase difference, $\\Delta\\phi = \\frac{\\Delta x}{\\lambda} \\times 2\\pi = \\frac{(a / 2)\\sin\\theta}{\\lambda} \\times 2\\pi$ $$ \\Delta\\phi=\\frac{\\lambda}{2\\lambda}\\times2\\pi=\\pi\\text{radian} $$\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//c4a242b2-912b-4ad1-96b4-7bf2e352f73d/markdown_0/imgs/img_in_image_box_211_589_479_738.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A16%3A29Z%2F-1%2F%2Fe25352aad4d40c7c979be2f1d731f6e296c1bf6989261679704788c21b7dfab3\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"22%\" /></div> From diagram $ \\sin \\theta = \\frac{\\lambda}{a} $ $ \\sin\\theta=\\theta=\\frac{Y}{D} $ (for small angle) $$ \\frac{Y}{D}=\\frac{\\lambda}{a} $$ $$ Y=\\frac{\\lambda D}{a} $$ $\\therefore$ Width of central maxima = 2Y $=\\frac{2\\lambda D}{a}$\n- For a dark fringe to form, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{dy}{D}&=\\lambda\\\\y&=\\frac{D\\lambda}{d}\\\\&=\\frac{2\\times600\\times10^{-9}}{10^{-3}}=1.2mm\\end{aligned} $$ Distance between the first dark fringes on either side of central bright fringe is $ 2 \\times y = 2.4 \\, mm $.\n- As speed of electrons is increased, so wavelength of electrons will decrease. Therefore, the angular width ( $ \\propto\\lambda $) of the central maximum of diffraction pattern will decrease.\n- We know that path difference for second minimum = 2$\\lambda$. $\\therefore$ Phase difference $=\\frac{2\\pi}{\\lambda}\\times2\\lambda$\n- Huygen's construction of wavefront does not apply to origin of spectra, which is explained by quantum theory.",
