"unitLabel": "Unit VIII — Dual Nature of Radiation",
"order": 24,
"title": "How every moving particle has a de Broglie wavelength",
"summary": "Every moving particle has an associated wavelength λ = h/p = h/mv (de Broglie); this wave nature matters only for very small particles such as electrons.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- de Broglie wavelength: $\\lambda=\\dfrac{h}{p}=\\dfrac{h}{mv}$.\n- In terms of kinetic energy: $\\lambda=\\dfrac{h}{\\sqrt{2mK}}$.\n- For an electron accelerated through $V$ volts: $\\lambda=\\dfrac{12.27}{\\sqrt{V}}\\ \\text{\\AA}$.\n- Confirmed experimentally by Davisson–Germer electron diffraction.\n**Exam traps**\n- $\\lambda\\propto 1/p$: a heavier or faster particle has a shorter wavelength.\n- Macroscopic objects have an utterly negligible de Broglie wavelength.",
