"id": "note-atoms-bohr-model-of-the-hydrogen-atom",
"chapter": "Atoms",
"subtopic": "Bohr Model of the Hydrogen Atom",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-atoms",
"unitLabel": "Unit IX — Atoms & Nuclei",
"order": 25,
"title": "Bohr Model of the Hydrogen Atom",
"summary": "According to the question, Electron Electron passes from fifth energy level to ground level means, $$…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Here, $ r_1 = 5.3 \\times 10^{-11} $ m Radius of third orbit, $ r_3 = n^2 r_1 $ $ r_3 = (3)^2 \\times 5.3 \\times 10^{-11} $ m (As, n = 3) $ r_3 = 47.7 \\times 10^{-11} $ m $ r_3 = 4.77 \\times 10^{-10} $ m\n- For first excited state, $ n_{1}=2 $ For second excited state, $ n_{2}=3 $ $$ \\frac{T_{1}}{T_{2}}=\\frac{n_{2}^{2}}{n_{1}^{2}}=\\frac{3^{2}}{2^{2}}=\\frac{9}{4} $$\n- The energy of an electron in Bohr's orbit of hydrogen atom is given by the expression, $$ \\mathrm{E}_{n}=-\\frac{2\\pi^{2}m e^{4}Z^{2}}{n^{2}h^{2}(4\\pi\\varepsilon_{0})^{2}}=-13.6\\frac{Z^{2}}{n^{2}}\\mathbf{e}\\mathbf{V} $$ Since, Z = 1 for hydrogen atom. So, the above equation further simplifies to, $$ \\mathrm{E}_{n}=-\\frac{13.6}{n^{2}}\\mathrm{~e V} $$\n- Bohr's model is not valid for singly ionised neon atom $ \\mathrm{(Ne^{+})} $.\n- In Bohr's model of H-atom, $$ \\mathbf{K.E}=|\\mathbf{T E}|=\\frac{|\\mathbf{U}|}{2} $$ $$ \\mathrm{K.E=3.4~e V} $$ $$ \\mathrm{U}=-6.8\\;{\\mathrm{e V}} $$\n- $$ \\begin{array}{c}{m_{\\upmu}=207~m_{\\mathrm{e}}}\\\\ {r=0.51~\\mathring{\\mathrm{A}}}\\end{array} $$ $$ r_{n}\\propto\\frac{1}{m} $$ $$ r_{1}=\\frac{0.51\\times10^{-10}}{207}=2.56\\times10^{-13}m $$ Since $$ \\mathrm{E}\\propto m_{e} $$ $$ \\circ\\circ $$ $$ \\mathrm{E}_{1}=-13.6\\times207=-2.8\\mathrm{k e V} $$\n- We have that, KE = -(total energy) So, kinetic energy: total energy = 1 : - 1\n- Time period of an electron in Bohr orbit is, then $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{T}&=\\frac{4\\varepsilon_{0}^{2}h^{3}n^{3}}{m e^{4}}\\\\\\mathrm{T}&\\propto n^{3}\\\\\\frac{\\mathrm{T}_{1}}{\\mathrm{T}_{2}}&=\\frac{n_{1}^{3}}{n_{2}^{3}}\\\\\\mathrm{T}_{1}&=8\\mathrm{T}_{2}\\\\\\left(\\frac{8\\mathrm{T}_{2}}{\\mathrm{T}_{2}}\\right)&=\\frac{n_{1}^{3}}{n_{2}^{3}}\\\\\\left(\\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\\right)^{3}&=(2^{3})\\\\\\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}&=2\\\\n_{1}&=2n_{2}\\end{aligned} $$\n- According to the question, Electron Electron passes from fifth energy level to ground level means, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{E}_{5}-\\mathrm{E}_{1}&=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda}\\\\\\Longrightarrow\\quad\\frac{\\mathrm{Rh}c}{25}-\\mathrm{Rh}c&=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda}\\\\\\Longrightarrow\\quad\\frac{24}{25}\\mathrm{R}&=\\frac{1}{\\lambda}\\end{aligned} $$ But $$ p=\\frac{h}{\\lambda} $$ and $$ \\mathbf{v}=\\frac{\\boldsymbol{h}}{m\\lambda}=\\frac{24}{25}\\frac{\\mathbf{R}\\boldsymbol{h}}{m} $$\n- We know that, $ E = \\frac{-13.6}{n^{2}} Z^{2} $ for first excited state n = 2 and for $ \\mathrm{He}^{+} $, Z = 2 $$ \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{-13.6}{2^{2}}\\times2^{2}=-13.6\\mathrm{eV} $$\n- For n = 1, $ \\mathrm{E}_{1} = -\\frac{13.6}{(1)^{2}} = -13.6\\,\\mathrm{eV} $ For n = 3, $$ \\mathrm{E}_{3}=-\\frac{13.6}{\\left(3\\right)^{2}}=-1.51\\mathrm{eV} $$ So, required energy $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{E}&=\\mathrm{E}_{3}-\\mathrm{E}_{1}\\\\&=-\\left(1.51\\right)-\\left(-13.6\\right)=12.09\\mathrm{eV}\\end{aligned} $$\n- We know that, Number of spectral lines, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{N}&=\\frac{n(n-1)}{2}\\\\\\frac{n(n-1)}{2}&=6\\\\\\Rightarrow n^{2}-n-12&=0\\\\\\Rightarrow(n-4)(n+3)&=0\\\\\\Rightarrow n&=4\\end{aligned} $$\n- Ground state energy of hydrogen atom $$ E_{1}=-13.6eV $$ Energy of electron in first excited state $ (n=2) $ $$ \\mathrm{E}_{2}=-\\frac{13.6}{\\left(2\\right)^{2}}\\mathrm{eV} $$ ∴ Excitation energy, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\Delta E&=E_{2}-E_{1}\\\\&=-\\frac{13.6}{4}-(-13.6)\\\\&=-3.4+13.6=10.2eV\\end{aligned} $$\n- Energy of $ n^{\\text{th}} $ orbit of hydrogen atom is given by, $$ \\mathrm{E}_{n}=-\\frac{13.6}{n^{2}}\\mathrm{eV} $$ for ground state, n = 1 $$ \\mathrm{E}_{1}=-\\frac{13.6}{1^{2}}=-13.6\\mathrm{eV} $$ $$ \\mathrm{E}_{2}=-\\frac{13.6}{2^{2}}=-3.4\\,\\mathrm{eV} $$ $$ \\mathbf{K}\\mathbf{E}=|\\mathbf{E}_{2}|=3.4~e\\mathbf{V} $$",
