"order": 25,
"title": "The Line Spectra of the Hydrogen Atom",
"summary": "Using Einstein's photoelectric equation, $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{W}+\\mathrm{KE}_{\\text{max}}\\\\ =\\mathrm{W}+\\mathrm{eV}_{0}\\\\ =2.75+10\\\\ =12.75\\,\\mathrm{eV}\\end{array} $$ <div style=\"text-align:…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- $$ \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{h c}{\\lambda}\\Rightarrow\\lambda=\\frac{h c}{\\mathrm{E}}\\Rightarrow\\lambda\\propto\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{E}} $$ Energy of photon of wavelength $ \\lambda_{1} $ $$ \\Delta\\mathrm{E}_{1}=-\\left(\\frac{5\\mathrm{E}}{2}\\right)+4\\mathrm{E}=\\frac{3\\mathrm{E}}{2} $$ Energy of photon of wavelength $ \\lambda_{2} $, $$ \\Delta\\mathrm{E}_{2}=-2\\mathrm{E}-(-3\\mathrm{E}) $$ $$ \\Delta\\mathrm{E}_{2}=-2\\mathrm{E}+3\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{E} $$ Energy of photon of wavelength $ \\lambda_{3} $, $$ \\Delta\\mathrm{E}_{3}=-2\\mathrm{E}-(-4\\mathrm{E}) $$ $$ =2\\mathrm{E} $$ So. $$ \\lambda_{2}=2\\lambda_{3} $$ $$ \\lambda_{2}>\\lambda_{1} $$\n- The spectral series given in the question shows the electronic transitions from higher energy levels ( $ n_{2}=5,6,\\ldots $) to the level ( $ n_{1}=4 $), this series is the Brackett series.\n- Shortest wavelength in Balmer series is $ \\lambda $. For Balmer series, $ n_{1}=2 $, $ n_{2}=\\infty $ $$ \\begin{aligned}We know,\\frac{1}{\\lambda}&=R\\left(\\frac{1}{n_{1}^{2}}-\\frac{1}{n_{2}^{2}}\\right)\\\\\\frac{1}{\\lambda}&=\\frac{R}{2^{2}}\\end{aligned} $$ For Bracket series, $ n_{1}=4 $, $ n_{2}=\\infty $ So, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{1}{\\lambda^{\\prime}}&=\\mathbf{R}\\left(\\frac{1}{n_{1}^{2}}-\\frac{1}{n_{2}^{2}}\\right)\\\\\\frac{1}{\\lambda^{\\prime}}&=\\frac{\\mathbf{R}}{4^{2}}\\end{aligned} $$ Divide eq (i) by (ii), we get we get $$ \\frac{\\lambda^{\\prime}}{\\lambda}=\\frac{1\\times4^{2}}{2^{2}}=4 $$ $$ \\lambda^{\\prime}=4\\lambda $$ #### ! Caution Students are often confused in finding the correct option. For it just find out the relation of the physical quantity and calculate the answer.\n- Using Rydberg formula, we have, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{1}{\\lambda}&=R\\left(\\frac{1}{n_{1}^{2}}-\\frac{1}{n_{2}^{2}}\\right)\\\\&=R\\left(\\frac{1}{2^{2}}-\\frac{1}{3^{2}}\\right)=\\frac{5R}{36}\\end{aligned} $$ and $$ \\frac{1}{\\lambda^{\\prime}}=R\\left(\\frac{1}{3^{2}}-\\frac{1}{4^{2}}\\right)=\\frac{7R}{144} $$ On dividing eqns. (i) by (ii), we get $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{\\lambda^{\\prime}}{\\lambda}&=\\frac{5R}{36}\\times\\frac{144}{7R}=\\frac{20}{7}\\\\\\lambda^{\\prime}&=\\frac{20}{7}\\lambda\\end{aligned} $$\n- Infrared radiation found in Paschen, Bracket and pfund series and it is obtain when electron transitions from high energy level to minimum $3^{rd}$ energy level.\n- We know that, $$ \\begin{array}{c}n=4\\\\\\downarrow\\quad\\mathrm{E}_{1}=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda_{1}}\\\\\\downarrow\\quad\\mathrm{E}_{2}=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda_{2}}\\\\\\downarrow\\quad n=2\\end{array} $$ Energy $$ \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{h c}{\\lambda}=13.6\\left[\\frac{1}{n_{2}^{2}}-\\frac{1}{n_{1}^{2}}\\right] $$ According to the question, $$ \\mathrm{E}_{1}=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda_{1}}=13.6\\left[\\frac{1}{3^{2}}-\\frac{1}{4^{2}}\\right] $$ And $$ \\mathrm{E}_{2}=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda_{2}}=13.6\\left[\\frac{1}{2^{2}}-\\frac{1}{3^{2}}\\right] $$ On dividing eq. (ii) by (i), we get $$ \\begin{aligned}\\frac{\\lambda_{1}}{\\lambda_{2}}&=\\frac{\\frac{1}{4}-\\frac{1}{9}}{\\frac{1}{9}-\\frac{1}{16}}=\\frac{20}{7}\\\\&=20:7\\end{aligned} $$\n- According to the question, Energy released = (-3.4) - (-13.6) = 10.2 eV Using Einstein's photoelectric equation $$ \\mathbf{W}=\\mathbf{E}-\\mathbf{e}\\mathbf{V}=h\\boldsymbol{v} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\nu&=\\frac{\\mathrm{E}-e\\mathrm{V}}{h}=\\frac{(10.2-3.57)e}{6.67\\times10^{-34}}\\\\\\nu&=\\frac{6.03\\times1.6\\times10^{-19}}{6.67\\times10^{-34}}\\\\&=1.6\\times10^{15}\\mathrm{Hz}\\end{aligned} $$\n- Using Einstein's photoelectric equation, $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{W}+\\mathrm{KE}_{\\text{max}}\\\\ =\\mathrm{W}+\\mathrm{eV}_{0}\\\\ =2.75+10\\\\ =12.75\\,\\mathrm{eV}\\end{array} $$ <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//05e73bc7-dc14-4611-a568-f37fd83b803f/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_chart_box_201_254_455_405.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A54Z%2F-1%2F%2Fca15f0d48fac77e653f80b16f4f58faaf5d9846a2c1fdf2be0b34766a19d4c2d\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"21%\" /></div> ∴ Difference of $n=4$ and $n=1$ Energy level is 12.75 eV Here, higher energy level is $n=4$ and lower energy level is $n=1$. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//05e73bc7-dc14-4611-a568-f37fd83b803f/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_image_box_32_525_64_574.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A54Z%2F-1%2F%2Fd79999127e2a5aaa7d8d283f6cbafc0f61fe79bc6888a3b42232baaa0ced3e11\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"2%\" /></div> ##### Mnemonics Order of Spectral lines in a Hydrogen Atom Lion Bechara Pyasa hai Bakri ko Paani Free Lyman, Balmer, Paschen, Brackett, Pfund.\n- <table border=1 style='margin: auto; word-wrap: break-word;'><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>n=5</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>13 eV</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>0.58 eV</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>n=4</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>12.09 eV</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>0.65 eV</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>n=3</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>10.2 eV</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>1.51 eV</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>n=2</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>13.6 eV</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>3.4 eV</td></tr><tr><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>n=1</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>13.6 eV</td><td style='text-align: center; word-wrap: break-word;'>1.9 eV</td></tr></table> But 11.1 eV is not present in the diagram. So, 11.1 eV is not possible.\n- We know that, Lyman series for H-ion, $$ \\frac{hc}{\\lambda}=\\operatorname{Rhc}\\left(\\frac{1}{1^{2}}-\\frac{1}{2^{2}}\\right) $$ and for H-like atom. $$ \\frac{hc}{\\lambda}=Z^{2}\\mathrm{Rh}c\\left(\\frac{1}{2^{2}}-\\frac{1}{4^{2}}\\right) $$ compare we get, $$ \\left(\\frac{1}{1^{2}}-\\frac{1}{2^{2}}\\right)=Z^{2}\\left(\\frac{1}{4}-\\frac{1}{16}\\right) $$ Solving we get, Z = 2\n- According to question, $$ \\begin{aligned}-13.6+12.1&=\\frac{-13.6}{n^{2}}\\\\\\Rightarrow\\quad n^{2}&=\\frac{13.6}{1.5}=9\\\\\\Rightarrow\\quad n&=3\\end{aligned} $$ Number of spectral lines emitted, $$ \\begin{aligned}&lines emitted,\\\\ &=\\frac{n(n-1)}{2}=\\frac{3\\times2}{2}\\\\ &=3\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//05e73bc7-dc14-4611-a568-f37fd83b803f/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_image_box_759_386_924_545.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A54Z%2F-1%2F%2F21ba2af3e7dfe8ebc83068cb224632f585cdac5244f3de6fd43ab2e161b3bb7d\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"13%\" /></div> $$ \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{h c}{\\lambda} $$ $$ E_{CA}=E_{CB}+E_{BA} $$ $$ \\frac{hc}{\\lambda_{3}}=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda_{1}}+\\frac{hc}{\\lambda_{2}} $$ $$ \\frac{1}{\\lambda_{3}}=\\frac{1}{\\lambda_{1}}+\\frac{1}{\\lambda_{2}} $$ $$ \\lambda_{3}=\\frac{\\lambda_{1}\\lambda_{2}}{\\lambda_{1}+\\lambda_{2}} $$\n- Energy of photon, $ \\Delta E = E_{2} - E_{1} $ $$ \\begin{aligned}&=-\\frac{13.6}{9}-\\left(\\frac{-13.6}{4}\\right)\\\\&=13.6\\left[\\frac{1}{4}-\\frac{1}{9}\\right]\\\\&=1.9eV\\end{aligned} $$\n- Jump to second orbit leads to Balmer series. When an electron jumps from $4^{\\mathrm{th}}$ orbit to $2^{\\mathrm{nd}}$, we get second line of Balmer series.",
