"order": 26,
"title": "Mass-Energy and Nuclear Binding Energy",
"summary": "Mass defect, $$ \\Delta\\mathbf{m}=\\mathbf{Z}\\mathbf{M}_{\\mathrm{p}}+(\\mathbf{A}-\\mathbf{Z})\\mathbf{M}_{\\mathrm{n}}-\\mathbf{M}(\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{Z}) $$ Binding Energy, $$ \\mathbf{BE}=\\Delta mc^{2} $$ ∴ $$…",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Given, $$ A_{1}=240 $$ $$ \\mathrm{A}_{2}=\\mathrm{A}_{3}=120 $$ $$ \\mathrm{BE}_{1}=7.6\\mathrm{M e V} $$ $$ \\mathrm{BE}_{2}=\\mathrm{BE}_{3}=8.5\\ \\mathrm{MeV} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}\\Delta\\mathrm{BE}&=\\mathrm{BE}_{2}+\\mathrm{BE}_{3}-\\mathrm{BE}_{1}\\\\&=8.5+8.5-7.6\\\\&=17-7.6\\\\&=9.4\\mathrm{~MeV}\\end{aligned} $$\n- Given: $$ m=0.5\\ g=0.5\\times10^{-3}\\ kg $$ Einstein's mass-energy equivalence relation. $$ E=m c^{2} $$ where, $c = \\text{velocity of light} = 3 \\times 10^{6} \\text{ m/s}$ $$ \\begin{aligned}E&=0.5\\times10^{-3}\\times(3\\times10^{8})^{2}\\\\ &=4.5\\times10^{13}J.\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\begin{array}{r} 1 \\\\ + \\quad 6 \\\\ \\hline 16 \\end{array} $$\n- The value of energy, $$ Q=2(4\\times7.06)-7\\times(5.60) $$ $$ Q=(8\\times7.06-7\\times5.60) $$ $$ Q=56.48-39.2 $$ $$ Q=17.28MeV $$ $$ Q=17.3MeV $$\n- First increases and then decreases with increase in mass number.\n- According to the question. $$ m=1\\ \\mathrm{u},c=3\\times10^{8}\\ \\mathrm{m s}^{-1} $$ if, $$ E=931~\\mathrm{M e V},1\\mathrm{u}=931~\\mathrm{M e V/c^{2}} $$ ∴ Binding energy, B.E. $$ \\begin{aligned}\\therefore\\text{Binding energy per nucleon,}\\\\=\\frac{39.10}{7}=5.58\\simeq5.6MeV\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}&=0.042\\times931\\\\&=39.10MeV\\end{aligned} $$\n- Mass defect, $$ \\Delta\\mathbf{m}=\\mathbf{Z}\\mathbf{M}_{\\mathrm{p}}+(\\mathbf{A}-\\mathbf{Z})\\mathbf{M}_{\\mathrm{n}}-\\mathbf{M}(\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{Z}) $$ Binding Energy, $$ \\mathbf{BE}=\\Delta mc^{2} $$ ∴ $$ \\mathbf{B}\\mathbf{E}=[\\mathbf{Z}\\mathbf{M}_{\\mathbf{p}}+(\\mathbf{A}-\\mathbf{Z})\\mathbf{M}_{\\mathbf{n}}-\\mathbf{M}\\left(\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{Z}\\right)]\\mathbf{c}^{2} $$ $$ \\mathbf{M}(\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{Z})=\\mathbf{Z}\\mathbf{M}_{\\mathrm{p}}+(\\mathbf{A}-\\mathbf{Z})\\mathbf{M}_{\\mathrm{n}}-\\frac{\\mathbf{B}\\mathbf{E}}{c^{2}} $$\n- B.E. = [ZM_{p} + (A - Z)M_{n} - M(A, Z)]c^{2}\n- Energy released. $$ \\begin{aligned}&Q=(B.E.)_{product}-(B.E.)_{reactant}\\\\&Q=(28-4.4)MeV\\\\&\\quad=23.6MeV\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- Energy in given reaction = B.E. of products - B.E. of reactants = c - (a + b) = c - a - b\n- Binding energy, BE = $ [NM_n + ZM_P - M(N, Z)c^2 $ $$ \\mathrm{M}(\\mathrm{N},\\mathrm{Z})=\\mathrm{NM}_{\\mathrm{n}}+\\mathrm{Z}\\mathrm{M}_{\\mathrm{P}}-\\frac{\\mathrm{B}}{c^{2}} $$\n- According to Einstein, mass-energy equation, $$ \\mathrm{E}=m c^{2}. $$ Taking mass, $$ m=1\\mathrm{a m u} $$ $$ =1.66\\times10^{-27}kg $$ and $$ c=3.0\\times10^{8}~\\mathrm{m/s} $$ Therefore, $$ \\begin{aligned}\\mathrm{E}&=(1.66\\times10^{-27})\\times(3\\times10^{8})^{2}\\mathrm{J}\\\\&=1.49\\times10^{-10}\\mathrm{J}\\\\&=\\frac{1.49\\times10^{-10}}{1.6\\times10^{-13}}\\mathrm{~MeV}\\end{aligned} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned}(\\because1MeV&=1.6\\times10^{-13}J)\\\\&=931.25MeV\\end{aligned} $$ Hence, 1 amu ≈ 931 MeV.",
