"id": "note-nuclei-nuclear-energy",
"chapter": "Nuclei",
"subtopic": "Nuclear Energy",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-atoms",
"unitLabel": "Unit IX — Atoms & Nuclei",
"order": 26,
"title": "Nuclear Energy",
"summary": "A moderator's function is to slow down the fast-moving secondary neutrons created during fission, because only slow-moving neutrons can initiate the fission reaction.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Slow neutrons are more effective in causing fission in $ {}^{235}_{92} $U because they have a higher probability of being captured by the uranium nucleus, leading to fission. An $ \\alpha $-particle is the nucleus of a helium atom. Beta particles are high electrons or positrons that are ejected from nucleus by some radionuclides during beta-decay. X-rays have longer wavelength than gamma rays.\n- Water has high specific heat capacity so that it can absorb a significant amount of heat energy without undergoing a large increase in temperature. In nuclear reactors, efficient heat transfer is needed to manage the high amounts of thermal energy produced during nuclear fission.\n- The reaction of Uranium is: $$ {\\bf\\Phi}_{92}^{235}\\mathbf{U}+{\\bf\\Phi}_{0}^{1}n\\to{\\bf\\Phi}_{36}^{89}\\mathbf{K}\\mathbf{r}+{\\bf\\Phi}3{\\bf\\Phi}_{0}^{1}n+\\mathbf{X}_{Z}^{\\mathrm{A}} $$ According to law of conservation. (Atomic number) $ _{Reaction} $ = (Atomic number) $ _{Product} $ $$ 92+0=36+7 $$ ↓ $$ Z=92-36=56 $$ Similarly, (Atomic mass) Reactant = (Atomic mass) Product $$ 235+1=89+A+3\\times1 $$ $$ A=144 $$ The element is $ {}^{144}_{56}Ba $.\n- Energy released per $ u = \\left(\\frac{0.02866}{4}\\right) $ (931 MeV) = 6.675 MeV\n- From the question, Here, $ \\mathrm{power}, P = 1000\\ \\mathrm{W} $ $ \\mathrm{Energy} $ per hour = $ 1000 \\times 3600\\ \\mathrm{J} $ $ \\mathrm{Energy} $ per fission = 200 MeV $ = 200 \\times 1.6 \\times 10^{-13}\\ \\mathrm{J} $ No. of fission per hour, $ n = \\frac{1000 \\times 3600}{200 \\times 1.6 \\times 10^{-13}} $ \\therefore Mass per hour = $ \\frac{n}{N} \\times 235 $ $$ \\begin{array}{l}\\begin{array}{r l r}&{=\\frac{1000\\times3600\\times235}{200\\times1.6\\times10^{-13}\\times6.02\\times10^{23}}} \\\\ &{=43.9\\times10^{-6}~\\mathrm{g}=40~\\mu\\mathrm{g}}\\end{array}\\end{array} $$\n- Thermal K.E. $ \\geq $ Electrostatic P.E.\n- Mass of $_{1}H^{2}=2.014478$ amu Mass of $_{2}He^{4}=4.00388$ amu Mass of deuterium $2\\times2.01478=4.02956$ amu Energy equivalent $_{2}^{2}H=4.02956\\times1.1=4.4$ MeV Energy equivalent to $_{2}^{4}He=4.00388\\times7=28$ MeV Energy released = 28 - 4.4 = 23.6 MeV\n- The mass of fission products is always less than mass of parent nucleus.\n- For nuclei having A > 56, binding energy of nucleus gradually decreases.\n- Product is more stable so that its mass is less than the sum masses of reactants i.e., $ m_{3} < (m_{1} + m_{2}) $.\n- Solar energy $ \\rightarrow $ fusion of protons into helium.\n- In nuclear fusion, lighter nuclei merge to form a heavier nuclear.\n- On the basis of a liquid drop model of the nucleus, nuclear fission can be explained.\n- A moderator's function is to slow down the fast-moving secondary neutrons created during fission, because only slow-moving neutrons can initiate the fission reaction. The moderator should be made of a light substance that does not absorb neutrons. Heavy water, graphite, deuterium, paraffin and other materials can act as moderators. <div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://pplines-online.bj.bcebos.com/deploy/official/paddleocr/pp-ocr-vl-16-online//007ef073-949b-4d80-9808-4a33c9029e95/markdown_1/imgs/img_in_image_box_1103_1027_1152_1072.jpg?authorization=bce-auth-v1%2FALTAKDN8mY5KlNI7zaRpLmOqrw%2F2026-06-06T18%3A15%3A50Z%2F-1%2F%2F9e7f5aa2a37c8859117ef9ee974c16a9b7c6ab804b88692b91859913c323d348\" alt=\"Image\" width=\"4%\" /></div>",
