"id": "note-nuclei-size-of-the-nucleus",
"chapter": "Nuclei",
"subtopic": "Size of The Nucleus",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-atoms",
"unitLabel": "Unit IX — Atoms & Nuclei",
"order": 26,
"title": "Size of The Nucleus",
"summary": "Nuclear radii.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Nuclear radius, $ \\mathrm{R} = R_0 A^{\\frac{1}{3}} $ $ \\mathrm{R} \\propto (\\mathrm{A})^{\\frac{1}{3}} $ $ \\frac{\\mathrm{R}_{1}}{\\mathrm{R}_{2}} = \\left(\\frac{125}{64}\\right)^{1/3} $, $ \\frac{\\mathrm{R}_{1}}{\\mathrm{R}_{2}} = \\frac{5}{4} $\n- Radius of nucleus is, $ \\mathrm{R} = \\mathrm{R}_{0} \\mathrm{A}^{1/3} $ $ \\Rightarrow $ $ \\mathrm{R} \\propto \\mathrm{A}^{1/3} $ $$ \\begin{aligned}&\\therefore\\frac{\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{Al}}}{\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{Te}}}=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{A}_{\\mathrm{Al}}}{\\mathrm{A}_{\\mathrm{Te}}}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{3}}=\\left(\\frac{27}{125}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{3}}=\\frac{3}{5}\\\\ &\\quad\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{Te}}=\\frac{5}{3}\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{Al}}\\\\ &\\because\\quad\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{Al}}=3.6\\mathrm{~fm}\\\\ &\\Rightarrow\\quad\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{Te}}=\\frac{5}{3}\\times3.6=6\\mathrm{~fm}\\\\ \\end{aligned} $$\n- We know that, (C) we know that, For Al, Nuclear Radius where, A = mass number $\\Rightarrow$ $R = R_{0}A^{1/3}$ $=R_{0}(27)^{1/3}=3R_{0}$ since, nuclear radius is 3.6 fm (given) $\\Rightarrow$ $R_{0}=\\frac{3.6}{3}=1.2$ fm For Cu, $R=R_{0}A^{1/3}=1.2\\times(64)^{1/3}$ $=4.8$ fm.\n- Density of nuclear matter is independent of mass number, so the required ratio is 1:1.\n- Nuclear radii. $$ \\mathrm{R}=\\mathrm{R}_{0}\\mathrm{A}^{1/3} $$ where. $$ R_{0}=1.2\\ f m $$ or $$ \\mathrm{R}\\propto(\\mathrm{A})^{1/3} $$ $$ \\frac{R_{Be}}{R_{Ge}}=\\frac{A_{Be}^{\\frac{1}{3}}}{A_{Ge}^{\\frac{1}{3}}} $$ Given $$ \\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{G e}}=2\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{B e}} $$ or $$ \\frac{1}{2}=\\frac{\\mathrm{A}_{\\mathrm{Be}}^{\\frac{1}{3}}}{\\mathrm{A}_{\\mathrm{Ge}}^{\\frac{1}{3}}} $$ $$ \\mathrm{A_{G e}}^{1/3}=2\\times(9)^{1/3} $$ or $$ \\mathrm{A}_{\\mathrm{Ge}}=2^{3}\\times9=8\\times9=72 $$ ∴ Number of nucleus in Ge is 72. $$ \\begin{array}{l}9.\\ (D)\\ \\frac{\\text{Volume of atom}}{\\text{Volume of nucleus}}=\\frac{\\frac{4}{3}\\pi(10^{-10})^{3}}{\\frac{4}{3}\\pi(10^{-15})^{3}}\\\\ =10^{15}\\end{array} $$",
