"id": "note-semiconductor-electronics-application-of-junction-diode-as-a-rectifier",
"chapter": "Semiconductor Electronics",
"subtopic": "Application of Junction Diode as a Rectifier",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-semi",
"unitLabel": "Unit X — Semiconductor Electronics",
"order": 27,
"title": "How diodes rectify AC into DC",
"summary": "Because a diode conducts only one way, it converts AC to DC: a half-wave rectifier uses one half-cycle (one diode); a full-wave or bridge rectifier uses both half-cycles.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Half-wave (1 diode): conducts on alternate half-cycles; ripple frequency $f_{out}=f$; average output $V_{dc}=\\dfrac{V_m}{\\pi}$.\n- Full-wave / bridge (2 / 4 diodes): both half-cycles used; ripple frequency $f_{out}=2f$; average output $V_{dc}=\\dfrac{2V_m}{\\pi}$.\n- A capacitor filter smooths the pulsating output toward steady DC.\n**Exam traps**\n- Full-wave ripple frequency is $2f$, half-wave is $f$; a bridge rectifier uses four diodes.\n- A rectifier converts AC → DC (not the reverse).",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "f_{out}=f\\ \\text{(half-wave)},\\quad f_{out}=2f\\ \\text{(full-wave)}",
"meaning": "Ripple frequency"
},
{
"latex": "V_{dc}=\\dfrac{V_m}{\\pi}\\ \\text{(half-wave)}",
"meaning": "Average half-wave output"
},
{
"latex": "V_{dc}=\\dfrac{2V_m}{\\pi}\\ \\text{(full-wave)}",
"meaning": "Average full-wave output"
}
],
