"id": "note-semiconductor-electronics-classification-of-metals-conductors-and-semiconductors",
"chapter": "Semiconductor Electronics",
"subtopic": "Classification of Metals, Conductors and Semiconductors",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-semi",
"unitLabel": "Unit X — Semiconductor Electronics",
"order": 27,
"title": "Why the energy band gap separates conductors, semiconductors and insulators",
"summary": "Solids are classified by the band gap E_g between the valence and conduction bands: metals have overlapping bands (E_g ≈ 0), semiconductors a small gap (~1 eV), and insulators a large gap (> 3 eV).",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Conductors (metals): conduction and valence bands overlap, $E_g\\approx0$, so many free electrons.\n- Insulators: a large gap, $E_g>3\\ \\text{eV}$ (diamond $\\approx6\\ \\text{eV}$).\n- Semiconductors: a small gap, $E_g\\approx1\\ \\text{eV}$ (Si $\\approx1.1\\ \\text{eV}$, Ge $\\approx0.7\\ \\text{eV}$).\n**Exam traps**\n- A semiconductor's resistance DECREASES as temperature rises (negative temperature coefficient) — the opposite of a metal.\n- At absolute zero a pure semiconductor behaves as an insulator.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "E_g(\\text{Si})\\approx1.1\\ \\text{eV},\\ E_g(\\text{Ge})\\approx0.7\\ \\text{eV}",
"meaning": "Band gaps of silicon and germanium"
},
{
"latex": "\\sigma=e(n_e\\mu_e+n_h\\mu_h)",
"meaning": "Conductivity of a semiconductor"
},
{
"latex": "\\text{metals: }E_g\\approx0;\\ \\text{insulators: }E_g>3\\ \\text{eV}",
"meaning": "Band-gap classification"
}
],
