"id": "note-semiconductor-electronics-extrinsic-semiconductor",
"chapter": "Semiconductor Electronics",
"subtopic": "Extrinsic Semiconductor",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-semi",
"unitLabel": "Unit X — Semiconductor Electronics",
"order": 27,
"title": "How doping creates n-type and p-type semiconductors",
"summary": "Doping with pentavalent donors gives an n-type (electron-majority) semiconductor; trivalent acceptors give a p-type (hole-majority) one — both greatly increasing conductivity while staying electrically neutral.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- n-type: dope with pentavalent atoms (P, As, Sb) → extra electrons; majority carriers are electrons ($n_e\\gg n_h$).\n- p-type: dope with trivalent atoms (B, Al, In) → holes; majority carriers are holes ($n_h\\gg n_e$).\n- The mass-action law still holds: $n_e n_h=n_i^2$.\n**Exam traps**\n- A doped semiconductor is overall electrically neutral, despite having majority carriers.\n- Donors (pentavalent) → n-type; acceptors (trivalent) → p-type.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "n_e\\approx N_D,\\quad n_h=\\dfrac{n_i^2}{n_e}",
"meaning": "n-type carrier densities"
},
{
"latex": "n_h\\approx N_A,\\quad n_e=\\dfrac{n_i^2}{n_h}",
"meaning": "p-type carrier densities"
},
{
"latex": "n_e n_h=n_i^2",
"meaning": "Mass-action law"
}
],
