"id": "note-semiconductor-electronics-intrinsic-semiconductor",
"chapter": "Semiconductor Electronics",
"subtopic": "Intrinsic Semiconductor",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-semi",
"unitLabel": "Unit X — Semiconductor Electronics",
"order": 27,
"title": "How a pure semiconductor conducts through electron–hole pairs",
"summary": "In a pure (intrinsic) semiconductor, thermal energy breaks covalent bonds to create equal numbers of free electrons and holes, so n_e = n_h = n_i.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Equal carriers: $n_e=n_h=n_i$, the intrinsic carrier concentration.\n- Conduction is by free electrons (in the conduction band) and holes (in the valence band).\n- $n_i$ increases with temperature, so conductivity rises with $T$.\n**Exam traps**\n- Electrons and holes are present in equal numbers in an intrinsic semiconductor.\n- At $T=0$ K it acts as an insulator (no broken bonds).",
