"id": "note-semiconductor-electronics-p-n-junction",
"chapter": "Semiconductor Electronics",
"subtopic": "p-n Junction",
"class": "XII",
"unitId": "xii-semi",
"unitLabel": "Unit X — Semiconductor Electronics",
"order": 27,
"title": "How a p-n junction builds a depletion region and a barrier potential",
"summary": "At a p-n junction, carriers diffuse across and leave behind immobile charged ions, forming a depletion region whose built-in potential barrier opposes further diffusion.",
"body": "**Must know**\n- Electrons diffuse n→p and holes p→n, leaving immobile ionised donors/acceptors → a carrier-free depletion region.\n- The exposed ions set up a built-in barrier potential ($\\approx0.7\\ \\text{V}$ for Si, $\\approx0.3\\ \\text{V}$ for Ge) that opposes further diffusion.\n- Equilibrium is reached when the diffusion current is balanced by the drift current.\n**Exam traps**\n- The depletion region has essentially no free charge carriers.\n- The barrier forms with no external battery connected.",
"formulas": [
{
"latex": "V_b\\approx0.7\\ \\text{V (Si)},\\ 0.3\\ \\text{V (Ge)}",
"meaning": "Built-in barrier potential"
},
{
"latex": "E\\approx\\dfrac{V_b}{d}",
"meaning": "Electric field across a depletion width d"
},
{
"latex": "I_{diffusion}=I_{drift}\\ \\text{at equilibrium}",
"meaning": "Zero net current at equilibrium"
}
],
