"title": "Objective I",
"summary": "$E = mc^2$: - **A** in isolation is imprecise: mass and energy are not \"the same thing\" — they are related by a conversion factor $c^2$.",
"body": "**Key points from solved questions**\n- Einstein's **first postulate** (principle of relativity): the **laws of physics are identical in all inertial reference frames** — no preferred frame exists. There is no absolute rest frame. An observer in any inertial frame can claim to be \"at rest\" and apply the same physical laws. Answer: (B).\n- Einstein's **second postulate**: the speed of light in vacuum is the same constant $c$ for all inertial observers, regardless of the relative motion of the light source and observer. This contradicts Galilean addition of velocities and is the foundation of all relativistic effects (time dilation, length contraction, mass-energy equivalence). Answer: (B).\n- **Time dilation**: a clock moving with velocity $v$ relative to an observer runs slower by the Lorentz factor: $$\\Delta t' = \\gamma\\,\\Delta t_0 = \\frac{\\Delta t_0}{\\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}}$$ where $\\Delta t_0$ is the proper time (measured in the clock's rest frame) and $\\Delta t'$ is the time measured by the moving observer ($\\Delta t' > \\Delta t_0$). A moving clock reads less elapsed time — it runs slow. Confirmed by: cosmic ray muons reaching Earth's surface, GPS satellite corrections. Answer: (B).\n- **Length contraction** (Lorentz contraction): a rod of proper length $L_0$ (measured in its rest frame) moving with velocity $v$ appears contracted in the direction of motion to an observer: $$L = \\frac{L_0}{\\gamma} = L_0\\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}$$ Only the length along the direction of motion contracts; dimensions perpendicular to motion are unchanged. Answer: (B).\n- $E = mc^2$: - **A** in isolation is imprecise: mass and energy are not \"the same thing\" — they are related by a conversion factor $c^2$. - **B** ✓: Mass-energy can be converted: nuclear fission/fusion converts mass defect to energy; pair production converts photon energy to mass. - **C** ✓: $c^2 \\approx 9\\times10^{16}\\,\\rm J/kg$ — even 1 gram of mass $\\equiv 9\\times10^{13}\\,\\rm J$ (equivalent to $\\sim 20$ kilotons TNT). - **D** ✓: Both B and C are correct; A is an oversimplification. Answer: (D).\n- The relativistic momentum: $$p = \\gamma m_0 v = \\frac{m_0 v}{\\sqrt{1-v^2/c^2}}$$ At low speeds ($v \\ll c$): $\\gamma \\approx 1$, recovering Newtonian $p = m_0 v$. As $v \\to c$: $\\gamma \\to \\infty$ and $p \\to \\infty$ — it takes infinite force to accelerate a massive particle to $c$. Answer: (B).",
